ritish Journal of Criminology |volume=49 |issue=1 |pages=17\u201334 |year=2009 |last1=Critcher |first1=Chas }}\n* {{cite journal |doi=10.1093/bjc/azn016 |ssrn=1315131 |jstor=23639654 |title=Failure to Launch: Why Do Some Social Issues Fail to Detonate Moral Panics? |journal=British Journal of Criminology |volume=49 |issue=1 |pages=35\u201347 |year=2009 |last1=Jenkins |first1=Philip }}\n* {{cite journal |doi=10.1093/bjc/azn073 |ssrn=1315136 |jstor=23639655 |title=Suite Revenge?: The Shaping of Folk Devils and Moral Panics about White-Collar Crimes |journal=British Journal of Criminology |volume=49 |issue=1 |pages=48\u201367 |year=2009 |last1=Levi |first1=Michael }}\n* {{cite journal |doi=10.1093/bjc/azn067 |ssrn=1315135 |jstor=23639656 |title=Moral Panic and Neo-Liberalism: The Case of Single Mothers on Welfare in Israel |journal=British Journal of Criminology |volume=49 |issue=1 |pages=68\u201387 |year=2009 |last1=Ajzenstadt |first1=Mimi }}\n* {{cite journal |doi=10.1093/bjc/azn027 |ssrn=1315132 |jstor=23639657 |title=Legalizing Prostitution: Morality Politics in Western Australia |journal=British Journal of Criminology |volume=49 |issue=1 |pages=88\u2013105 |year=2009 |last1=Weitzer |first1=Ronald }}\n* {{cite journal |doi=10.1093/bjc/azn054 |ssrn=1315134 |jstor=23639658 |title=Organized Evil and the Atlantic Alliance: Moral Panics and the Rhetoric of Organized Crime Policing in America and Britain |journal=British Journal of Criminology |volume=49 |issue=1 |pages=106\u201328 |year=2009 |last1=Woodiwiss |first1=Michael |last2=Hobbs |first2=Dick }}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://openlearn.open.ac.uk/mod/resource/view.php?id=184696 Section 3.4: \"Interpreting the crime problem\"] from Free OpenLearn LearningSpace Unit DD100 1 ''Online Open Education Resource Creative Commons by-nc-sa Licensed'' (originally written for the [[Open University]] Course, DD100, 2000)\n* [http://www.brunel.ac.uk/cbass/social-sciences-media-communications/research/moral-panics Moral Panic Research Network], College of Business, Arts and Social Sciences, [[Brunel University London]]\n\n{{Psychological manipulation}}\n\n[[Category:Barriers to critical thinking]]\n[[Category:Crowd psychology]]\n[[Category:Deviance (sociology)]]\n[[Category:Morality|Panic]]\n[[Category:Social phenomena]]\n", "name_user": "ThreefoldTaco", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExamples", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moral_panic"}
{"title_page": "Greenhouse gas emissions by India", "text_new": "{{About|gases from the south Asian country which contribute to global warming, and their mitigation|the effects of global warming and adaptation to it|Effects of global warming on South Asia}}\n{{short description|Climate changing gases from the south Asian country}}\n\n'''Greenhouse gas emissions by India''' are the third largest in the world and the main source is coal.<ref name=CarbonBrief>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carbonbrief.org/the-carbon-brief-profile-india|title=The Carbon Brief Profile: India|date=2019-03-14|website=Carbon Brief|language=en|access-date=2019-09-25}}</ref> [[India]] emits about 3 gigatonnes ([[Gigatonne|Gt]]) [[Carbon dioxide equivalent|CO<sub>2eq</sub>]] of [[greenhouse gas]]es each year; about two and a half tons per person, which is half the world average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.climatelinks.org/sites/default/files/asset/document/India%20GHG%20Emissions%20Factsheet%20FINAL.pdf|title=Greenhouse Gas Emissions in India|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref> The country emits 7% of global emissions.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.unenvironment.org/resources/emissions-gap-report-2019|title=Emissions Gap Report 2019|last=Environment|first=U. N.|date=2019-11-19|website=UNEP - UN Environment Programme|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> {{As of|2019}} these figures are quite uncertain, but a comprehensive [[Greenhouse gas emissions accounting|greenhouse gas inventory]] is within reach.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.downtoearth.org.in/blog/climate-change/a-comprehensive-ghg-inventory-for-india-is-within-reach-62122|title=A comprehensive GHG inventory for India is within reach|website=www.downtoearth.org.in|language=en|access-date=2019-09-25}}</ref> Cutting greenhouse gas emissions, and therefore [[air pollution in India]], would have health benefits worth 4 to 5 times the cost, which would be the most cost-effective in the world.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Sampedro|first=Jon|last2=Smith|first2=Steven J.|last3=Arto|first3=I\u00f1aki|last4=Gonz\u00e1lez-Eguino|first4=Mikel|last5=Markandya|first5=Anil|last6=Mulvaney|first6=Kathleen M.|last7=Pizarro-Irizar|first7=Cristina|last8=Van Dingenen|first8=Rita|date=2020-03-01|title=Health co-benefits and mitigation costs as per the Paris Agreement under different technological pathways for energy supply|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S016041201933911X|journal=Environment International|language=en|volume=136|pages=105513|doi=10.1016/j.envint.2020.105513|issn=0160-4120|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n== Greenhouse gas sources ==\nIndia emitted 2,600 Mt of CO2 e in 2014 (2,300 Mt with LULUCF).{{sfnp|2nd biennial report|2018|page=5}}\n\n=== Energy ===\n\n==== Electricity generation ====\n{{As of|2019|}} three-quarters of electricity is generated by burning fossil fuels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carbonbrief.org/analysis-indias-co2-emissions-growth-poised-to-slow-sharply-in-2019|title=Analysis: India\u2019s CO2 emissions growth poised to slow sharply in 2019|date=2019-10-24|website=Carbon Brief|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n===== Coal fired power stations =====\nAs well as [[coal mining in India]], the country also imports coal<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=b33f5de0-e0f3-11e9-b69b-4179a3506621&url=L25ld3MvYXJ0aWNsZXMvMjAxOS0wOC0wMS9pbmRpYS13b3JsZC1zLW5vLTItY29hbC1idXllci1wbGFucy10by1jdXQtaW1wb3J0cy1ieS1hLXRoaXJk|title=India, World's No. 2 Coal Buyer, Plans to Cut Imports by a Third|last=|first=|date=|website=www.bloomberg.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref> to burn in [[List of power stations in India#Coal|coal-fired power stations in India]].\n\n==== Transport fuel ====\n90% of transport emissions are from road transport.{{sfnp|2nd biennial report|2018|page=8}}\n\n==== Home energy ====\n\n=== Industry ===\nA quarter of emissions are from industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ghgplatform-india.org/industry-sector|title=India's Industrial Sector GHG Emissions|website=www.ghgplatform-india.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==== Iron and steel ====\n\nIron and steel accounts for almost half of industrial emissions.{{sfnp|2nd biennial report|2018|page=8}}\n\n==== Cement ====\nCement production is the second largest industrial emitter.{{sfnp|2nd biennial report|2018|page=8}}\n\n=== Agriculture ===\n\n=== Waste ===\n\n== Energy efficiency ==\n{{expand section|date=September 2019}}\nIndia's [[Intended Nationally Determined Contribution]] includes reducing [[emission intensity]] by a third by 2030.<ref name=CarbonBrief/>\n\n== Planning and forecasts ==\nThe [[United Nations Environment Programme|UNEP]] forecasts that by 2030 India's annual emissions per person will be between 3 and 4 tonnes.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Reporting ==\n\n== Mitigation ==\n\n=== Energy ===\n{{See also|Renewable energy in India}}\n\nThe National Energy Plan is in accord with the [[Paris Agreement]] target of 2&nbsp;\u00b0C global warming, but if India stopped building coal-fired power stations it would meet the 1.5&nbsp;\u00b0C aspiration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/save/https://www.nationalgeographic.com/environment/2019/09/climate-change-report-card-co2-emissions/|title=Climate change report card: These countries are reaching targets|date=2019-09-19|website=Environment|language=en|access-date=2019-09-26}}</ref>\n\n=== Economics ===\n\n[[Economy of India|India\u2019s economy]] is forecast to grow significantly, with gross domestic product rising 7-8% annually. The government expects electricity capacity needs to nearly double to 2027. With accelerated coal plant closures, and an anticipated surge in renewables, thermal power will account for only an estimated 42.7% of installed capacity across India by 2027, down dramatically from 66.8% in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190926205752/http://ieefa.org/ieefa-india-new-national-electricity-plan-reinforces-intent-toward-275-gigawatts-of-renewables-generated-electricity-by-2027/|title=IEEFA India: New National Electricity Plan Reinforces Intent Toward 275 Gigawatts of Renewables-Generated Electricity by 2027|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Co-benefits ===\nCutting greenhouse gas emissions, and therefore [[air pollution in India]], would have health benefits worth 4 to 5 times the cost, which would be the most cost-effective in the world.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== Politics ==\n{{expand section|date=September 2019}}\n \nThe Indian Central Government as well as various state governments have taken certain steps in accordance with India's energy policy and the [[Paris Agreement]]. Following are some of those steps:\n\n* Doubling India\u2019s renewable energy target to 450 gigawatt (GW) by 2030 <ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190926211908/https://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/govt-to-ease-land-acquisition-finance-for-renewables-to-meet-450-gw-target-119092501326_1.html|title=Govt to ease land acquisition, finance for renewables to meet 450 GW target|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n* [[National Solar Mission]]\n\n* [[Wind power in India]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n\n====UNFCCC====\n*{{cite web  \n |work=Ministry of Environment, Forest and Climate Change\n |title=Second Biennial Update Report\n |date=December 2018   \n |url=https://unfccc.int/sites/default/files/resource/INDIA%20SECOND%20BUR%20High%20Res.pdf\n |ref={{harvid|2nd biennial report|2018}}   \n }}\n\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www4.unfccc.int/sites/NDCStaging/pages/Party.aspx?party=IND|title=Nationally Determined Contributions submitted to UN|last=|first=|date=|website=www4.unfccc.int|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-31}}\n\n====Other sources====\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.ghgplatform-india.org/ GHG Platform: An Indian Civil Society Initiative to Understand India's GHG Emission Estimates]\n* [https://www.electricitymap.org/?page=country&solar=false&remote=true&wind=false&countryCode=IN Electricity Map: Live carbon emissions from electricity generation in some states]\n\n{{Asia topic|Greenhouse gas emissions by}}\n\n[[Category:Greenhouse gas emissions by country|India]]\n[[Category:Climate change in India]]\n\n\n{{climate-change-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{About|gases from the south Asian country which contribute to global warming, and their mitigation|the effects of global warming and adaptation to it|Effects of global warming on South Asia}}\n{{short description|Climate changing gases from the south Asian country}}\n\n'''Greenhouse gas emissions by India''' are the third largest in the world and the main source is coal.<ref name=CarbonBrief>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carbonbrief.org/the-carbon-brief-profile-india|title=The Carbon Brief Profile: India|date=2019-03-14|website=Carbon Brief|language=en|access-date=2019-09-25}}</ref> [[India]] emits about 3 gigatonnes ([[Gigatonne|Gt]]) [[Carbon dioxide equivalent|CO<sub>2eq</sub>]] of [[greenhouse gas]]es each year; about two and a half tons per person, which is half the world average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.climatelinks.org/sites/default/files/asset/document/India%20GHG%20Emissions%20Factsheet%20FINAL.pdf|title=Greenhouse Gas Emissions in India|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref> The country emits 7% of global emissions.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.unenvironment.org/resources/emissions-gap-report-2019|title=Emissions Gap Report 2019|last=Environment|first=U. N.|date=2019-11-19|website=UNEP - UN Environment Programme|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> {{As of|2019}} these figures are quite uncertain, but a comprehensive [[Greenhouse gas emissions accounting|greenhouse gas inventory]] is within reach.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.downtoearth.org.in/blog/climate-change/a-comprehensive-ghg-inventory-for-india-is-within-reach-62122|title=A comprehensive GHG inventory for India is within reach|website=www.downtoearth.org.in|language=en|access-date=2019-09-25}}</ref> Cutting greenhouse gas emissions, and therefore [[air pollution in India]], would have health benefits worth 4 to 5 times the cost, which would be the most cost-effective in the world.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Sampedro|first=Jon|last2=Smith|first2=Steven J.|last3=Arto|first3=I\u00f1aki|last4=Gonz\u00e1lez-Eguino|first4=Mikel|last5=Markandya|first5=Anil|last6=Mulvaney|first6=Kathleen M.|last7=Pizarro-Irizar|first7=Cristina|last8=Van Dingenen|first8=Rita|date=2020-03-01|title=Health co-benefits and mitigation costs as per the Paris Agreement under different technological pathways for energy supply|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S016041201933911X|journal=Environment International|language=en|volume=136|pages=105513|doi=10.1016/j.envint.2020.105513|issn=0160-4120|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n== Greenhouse gas sources ==\nIndia emitted 2,600 Mt of CO2 e in 2014 (2,300 Mt with LULUCF).{{sfnp|2nd biennial report|2018|page=5}}\n\n=== Energy ===\n\n==== Electricity generation ====\n{{As of|2019|}} three-quarters of electricity is generated by burning fossil fuels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carbonbrief.org/analysis-indias-co2-emissions-growth-poised-to-slow-sharply-in-2019|title=Analysis: India\u2019s CO2 emissions growth poised to slow sharply in 2019|date=2019-10-24|website=Carbon Brief|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n===== Coal fired power stations =====\nAs well as [[coal mining in India]], the country also imports coal<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=b33f5de0-e0f3-11e9-b69b-4179a3506621&url=L25ld3MvYXJ0aWNsZXMvMjAxOS0wOC0wMS9pbmRpYS13b3JsZC1zLW5vLTItY29hbC1idXllci1wbGFucy10by1jdXQtaW1wb3J0cy1ieS1hLXRoaXJk|title=India, World's No. 2 Coal Buyer, Plans to Cut Imports by a Third|last=|first=|date=|website=www.bloomberg.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref> to burn in [[List of power stations in India#Coal|coal-fired power stations in India]].\n\n==== Transport fuel ====\n90% of transport emissions are from road transport.{{sfnp|2nd biennial report|2018|page=8}}\n\n==== Home energy ====\n\n=== Industry ===\nA quarter of emissions are from industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ghgplatform-india.org/industry-sector|title=India's Industrial Sector GHG Emissions|website=www.ghgplatform-india.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==== Iron and steel ====\n\nIron and steel accounts for almost half of industrial emissions.{{sfnp|2nd biennial report|2018|page=8}}\n\n==== Cement ====\nCement production is the second largest industrial emitter.{{sfnp|2nd biennial report|2018|page=8}}\n\n=== Agriculture ===\n\n=== Waste ===\n\n== Energy efficiency ==\n{{expand section|date=September 2019}}\nIndia's [[Intended Nationally Determined Contribution]] includes reducing [[emission intensity]] by a third by 2030.<ref name=CarbonBrief/>\n\n== Planning and forecasts ==\nThe [[United Nations Environment Programme|UNEP]] forecasts that by 2030 India's annual emissions per person will be between 3 and 4 tonnes.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Mitigation ==\n\n=== Energy ===\n{{See also|Renewable energy in India}}\n\nThe National Energy Plan is in accord with the [[Paris Agreement]] target of 2&nbsp;\u00b0C global warming, but if India stopped building coal-fired power stations it would meet the 1.5&nbsp;\u00b0C aspiration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/save/https://www.nationalgeographic.com/environment/2019/09/climate-change-report-card-co2-emissions/|title=Climate change report card: These countries are reaching targets|date=2019-09-19|website=Environment|language=en|access-date=2019-09-26}}</ref>\n\n=== Economics ===\n\n[[Economy of India|India\u2019s economy]] is forecast to grow significantly, with gross domestic product rising 7-8% annually. The government expects electricity capacity needs to nearly double to 2027. With accelerated coal plant closures, and an anticipated surge in renewables, thermal power will account for only an estimated 42.7% of installed capacity across India by 2027, down dramatically from 66.8% in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190926205752/http://ieefa.org/ieefa-india-new-national-electricity-plan-reinforces-intent-toward-275-gigawatts-of-renewables-generated-electricity-by-2027/|title=IEEFA India: New National Electricity Plan Reinforces Intent Toward 275 Gigawatts of Renewables-Generated Electricity by 2027|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Co-benefits ===\nCutting greenhouse gas emissions, and therefore [[air pollution in India]], would have health benefits worth 4 to 5 times the cost, which would be the most cost-effective in the world.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== Politics ==\n{{expand section|date=September 2019}}\n \nThe Indian Central Government as well as various state governments have taken certain steps in accordance with India's energy policy and the [[Paris Agreement]]. Following are some of those steps:\n\n* Doubling India\u2019s renewable energy target to 450 gigawatt (GW) by 2030 <ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190926211908/https://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/govt-to-ease-land-acquisition-finance-for-renewables-to-meet-450-gw-target-119092501326_1.html|title=Govt to ease land acquisition, finance for renewables to meet 450 GW target|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n* [[National Solar Mission]]\n\n* [[Wind power in India]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n\n====UNFCCC====\n*{{cite web  \n |work=Ministry of Environment, Forest and Climate Change\n |title=Second Biennial Update Report\n |date=December 2018   \n |url=https://unfccc.int/sites/default/files/resource/INDIA%20SECOND%20BUR%20High%20Res.pdf\n |ref={{harvid|2nd biennial report|2018}}   \n }}\n\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www4.unfccc.int/sites/NDCStaging/pages/Party.aspx?party=IND|title=Nationally Determined Contributions submitted to UN|last=|first=|date=|website=www4.unfccc.int|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-31}}\n\n====Other sources====\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.ghgplatform-india.org/ GHG Platform: An Indian Civil Society Initiative to Understand India's GHG Emission Estimates]\n* [https://www.electricitymap.org/?page=country&solar=false&remote=true&wind=false&countryCode=IN Electricity Map: Live carbon emissions from electricity generation in some states]\n\n{{Asia topic|Greenhouse gas emissions by}}\n\n[[Category:Greenhouse gas emissions by country|India]]\n[[Category:Climate change in India]]\n\n\n{{climate-change-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Chidgk1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlanning and forecasts", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greenhouse_gas_emissions_by_India"}
{"title_page": "Ernest Lee Thomas", "text_new": "{{infobox person\n|name = Ernest Lee Thomas\n|image =Thomas, Ernest Lee (2008).jpg\n|caption = Ernest Thomas, 2008\n|birth_name = Ernest Lee Thomas\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1949|3|26}}\n|birth_place = [[Gary, Indiana]], U.S.\n|occupation = Actor\n|yearsactive = 1974\u2013present\n}}\n[[File:What's Happening partial cast 1977.JPG|thumb|270px|<center>From TV's ''[[What's Happening!!]]'' (1977). Seated, L-R: [[Fred Berry]], Ernest Lee Thomas, and [[Haywood Nelson]] (back to camera). Standing: [[Shirley Hemphill]]. </center>]]\n'''Ernest Lee Thomas''' (born March 26, 1949) is an American actor.<ref name=LA>[http://www.lasentinel.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3500:ernest-lee-thomas-is-what-s-happenin&catid=80:local&Itemid=170 LA Sentinel]</ref><ref>[http://www.tmz.com/person/ernest-thomas/ TMZ]</ref><ref>[http://www.starpulse.com/events/13575/0/36/Essence+Music+Festival+2010+Press+Room+/1/ Starpulse.com]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://splitsider.com/2011/09/raj-from-whats-happening-is-totally-into-rob-zombie-almost-played-kunta-kinte/ |title=Splitsider.com |access-date=2013-08-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222051909/http://splitsider.com/2011/09/raj-from-whats-happening-is-totally-into-rob-zombie-almost-played-kunta-kinte/ |archive-date=2014-02-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He is best known for his role as Roger \"Raj\" Thomas on the 1970s [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] sitcom ''[[What's Happening!!]]'',<ref name=LA/> and its 1980s [[syndicated television|syndicated]] sequel, ''[[What's Happening Now!!]]'', and for his recurring role as Mr. Omar on ''[[Everybody Hates Chris]]''.\n\n==Early career and ''What's Happening!!''==\nThomas was born in [[Gary, Indiana]] and began his professional acting career as a [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] actor, appearing in the 1974 revival production of ''Love for Love'' and in the 1975 revival of ''[[The Member of the Wedding]]''.  Both shows starred actress [[Glenn Close]].  Shortly after he moved to [[Los Angeles]] to pursue a career as a TV/film actor.  In the fall of 1975 he received a role on an episode of ''[[The Jeffersons]]''.  It was during the taping of the show that he learned of an audition for the upcoming comedy sitcom ''[[What's Happening!!]]'', loosely based on the 1975 film ''[[Cooley High]]''. He eventually went on to win the role of Roger \"Raj\" Thomas on the show, which aired from 1976 to 1979.\n\nDuring the show's run, Thomas was involved in other acting film and TV projects including ''[[Baretta]]'', ''[[Roots (1977 miniseries)|Roots]]'', ''[[The Brady Bunch Hour]]'' and the film ''[[A Piece of the Action (film)|A Piece of the Action]]'' starring [[Sidney Poitier]] and [[Bill Cosby]]. Though the series rated well, ''What's Happening!!'' was cancelled after its third season in the early spring of 1979.\n\n==''What's Happening Now!!'' and later career==\n\nAfter a six-year hiatus from TV and film acting, Ernest resumed his role as Roger \"Raj\" Thomas in the sequel ''[[What's Happening Now!!]]''  The show aired in first-run syndication from 1985 to 1988.\n\nSince the show's cancellation Thomas has guest starred on a number of popular TV dramas and sitcoms including ''[[In the Heat of the Night (TV series)|In the Heat of the Night]]'', (which co-starred his TV wife [[Anne-Marie Johnson]], from ''What's Happening Now!!''), ''[[The Parent 'Hood]]'', ''[[Martin (TV series)|Martin]]'' (which starred his What's Happening Now!! co-star [[Martin Lawrence]]), ''[[Soul Food (TV series)|Soul Food]]'', ''[[The Steve Harvey Show]]'', ''[[All About the Andersons]]'' and more recently ''[[Just Jordan]]''. He has also appeared in a number of films, including a supporting role in ''[[Malcolm X (1992 film)|Malcolm X]]'' and a cameo in ''[[Dickie Roberts: Former Child Star]]''. He later had a recurring role as funeral director, Mr. Omar, on the TV sitcom ''[[Everybody Hates Chris]]''. He had an uncredited guest spot as Ernest T \"Bass\" on the TV Show ''[[Are We There Yet? (TV series)|Are We There Yet?]]'' It was titled, \"The Satchel Paige Episode\" and had him playing a Flavor Flav type personality.\n\nIn 2012, Thomas was cast in rocker/horror movie director [[Rob Zombie]]'s 2012 film ''[[The Lords of Salem (film)|The Lords of Salem]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailydead.com/ernest-thomas-joins-the-lords-of-salem/|title=Ernest Thomas joins The Lords of Salem|date=2011-09-21|website=Daily Dead|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> In 2016, he was in a comedic [[body horror]] short film called ''Earworm''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gojimmygo.net/2018/01/21/actor-ernest-thomas-discusses-his-career-and-the-40th-anniversary-of-the-doobie-brothers-appearance-on-whats-happening/|title=Actor Ernest Thomas Discusses His Career And The 40th Anniversary of The Doobie Brothers Appearance on \u2018What\u2019s Happening!!\u2019|date=2018-01-21|website=go.Jimmy.go|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\nHe has an eye condition called [[amblyopia]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Filmography==\n*1976-1979: ''[[What's Happening!!]]'' (TV Series) - Roger 'Raj' Thomas\n*1977: ''[[A Piece of the Action (film)|A Piece of the Action]]'' - John\n*1985-1988: ''[[What's Happening Now!!]]'' (TV Series) - Roger 'Raj' Thomas\n*1991: ''Kiss and Be Killed'' - Det. Ross\n*1992: ''[[Malcolm X (1992 film)|Malcolm X]]'' - Sidney\n*2003: ''The Watermelon Heist'' - Jailer\n*2003: ''[[Dickie Roberts: Former Child Star]]'' - Ernest Thomas\n*2005-2009: ''[[Everybody Hates Chris]]'' (TV Series) - Mr. Omar / Funeral Director / Radical Man\n*2007: ''Paroled'' - Royce Henderson\n*2009: ''[[Funny People]]'' - Yo Teach Principal\n*2012: ''[[The Lords of Salem (film)|The Lords of Salem]]'' - Chip McDonald (Frankenstein and the Witchhunter) (uncredited)\n*2013: ''The Pastor and Mrs. Jones'' - Pastor\n*2014: ''Basketball Girlfriend'' - Lenny\n*2014: ''Revenge'' - Neville\n*2014: ''The Slimbones'' - Uncle AB\n*2015: ''[[Mega Shark vs. Kolossus]]'' - Admiral Titus Jackson\n*2015: ''[[Chocolate City (film)|Chocolate City]]'' - Diner Manager\n*2016: '''79 Parts'' - Priore\n*2016: ''Stop Bullying Now: Live from the Big House'' - Himself\n*2016 - ''Earworm'' (short)\n*2017: ''[[Chocolate City: Vegas Strip]]'' - Mr. Williams\n*2017: ''The Gods'' - Olympus\n*2017: ''Two Wolves'' - Olivier\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n*{{IMDb name|0858808}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thomas, Ernest}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Indiana]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:African-American male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:People from Gary, Indiana]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox person\n|name = Ernest Lee Thomas\n|image =Thomas, Ernest Lee (2008).jpg\n|caption = Ernest Thomas, 2008\n|birth_name = Ernest Lee Thomas\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1949|3|26}}\n|birth_place = [[Gary, Indiana]], U.S.\n|occupation = Actor\n|yearsactive = 1974\u2013present\n}}\n[[File:What's Happening partial cast 1977.JPG|thumb|270px|<center>From TV's ''[[What's Happening!!]]'' (1977). Seated, L-R: [[Fred Berry]], Ernest Lee Thomas, and [[Haywood Nelson]] (back to camera). Standing: [[Shirley Hemphill]]. </center>]]\n'''Ernest Lee Thomas''' (born March 26, 1949) is an American actor.<ref name=LA>[http://www.lasentinel.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3500:ernest-lee-thomas-is-what-s-happenin&catid=80:local&Itemid=170 LA Sentinel]</ref><ref>[http://www.tmz.com/person/ernest-thomas/ TMZ]</ref><ref>[http://www.starpulse.com/events/13575/0/36/Essence+Music+Festival+2010+Press+Room+/1/ Starpulse.com]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://splitsider.com/2011/09/raj-from-whats-happening-is-totally-into-rob-zombie-almost-played-kunta-kinte/ |title=Splitsider.com |access-date=2013-08-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222051909/http://splitsider.com/2011/09/raj-from-whats-happening-is-totally-into-rob-zombie-almost-played-kunta-kinte/ |archive-date=2014-02-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He is best known for his role as Roger \"Raj\" Thomas on the 1970s [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] sitcom ''[[What's Happening!!]]'',<ref name=LA/> and its 1980s [[syndicated television|syndicated]] sequel, ''[[What's Happening Now!!]]'', and for his recurring role as Mr. Omar on ''[[Everybody Hates Chris]]''.\n\n==Early career and ''What's Happening!!''==\nThomas was born in [[Gary, Indiana]] and began his professional acting career as a [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] actor, appearing in the 1974 revival production of ''Love for Love'' and in the 1975 revival of ''[[The Member of the Wedding]]''.  Both shows starred actress [[Glenn Close]].  Shortly after he moved to [[Los Angeles]] to pursue a career as a TV/film actor.  In the fall of 1975 he received a role on an episode of ''[[The Jeffersons]]''.  It was during the taping of the show that he learned of an audition for the upcoming comedy sitcom ''[[What's Happening!!]]'', loosely based on the 1975 film ''[[Cooley High]]''. He eventually went on to win the role of Roger \"Raj\" Thomas on the show, which aired from 1976 to 1979.\n\nDuring the show's run, Thomas was involved in other acting film and TV projects including ''[[Baretta]]'', ''[[Roots (1977 miniseries)|Roots]]'', ''[[The Brady Bunch Hour]]'' and the film ''[[A Piece of the Action (film)|A Piece of the Action]]'' starring [[Sidney Poitier]] and [[Bill Cosby]]. Though the series rated well, ''What's Happening!!'' was cancelled after its third season in the early spring of 1979.\n\n==''What's Happening Now!!'' and later career==\n\nAfter a six-year hiatus from TV and film acting, Ernest resumed his role as Roger \"Raj\" Thomas in the sequel ''[[What's Happening Now!!]]''  The show aired in first-run syndication from 1985 to 1988.\n\nSince the show's cancellation Thomas has guest starred on a number of popular TV dramas and sitcoms including ''[[In the Heat of the Night (TV series)|In the Heat of the Night]]'', (which co-starred his TV wife [[Anne-Marie Johnson]], from ''What's Happening Now!!''), ''[[The Parent 'Hood]]'', ''[[Martin (TV series)|Martin]]'' (which starred his What's Happening Now!! co-star [[Martin Lawrence]]), ''[[Soul Food (TV series)|Soul Food]]'', ''[[The Steve Harvey Show]]'', ''[[All About the Andersons]]'' and more recently ''[[Just Jordan]]''. He has also appeared in a number of films, including a supporting role in ''[[Malcolm X (1992 film)|Malcolm X]]'' and a cameo in ''[[Dickie Roberts: Former Child Star]]''. He later had a recurring role as funeral director, Mr. Omar, on the TV sitcom ''[[Everybody Hates Chris]]''. He had an uncredited guest spot as Ernest T \"Bass\" on the TV Show ''[[Are We There Yet? (TV series)|Are We There Yet?]]'' It was titled, \"The Satchel Paige Episode\" and had him playing a Flavor Flav type personality.\n\nIn 2012, Thomas was cast in rocker/horror movie director [[Rob Zombie]]'s 2012 film ''[[The Lords of Salem (film)|The Lords of Salem]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailydead.com/ernest-thomas-joins-the-lords-of-salem/|title=Ernest Thomas joins The Lords of Salem|date=2011-09-21|website=Daily Dead|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> In 2016, he was in a comedic [[body horror]] short film called Earworm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gojimmygo.net/2018/01/21/actor-ernest-thomas-discusses-his-career-and-the-40th-anniversary-of-the-doobie-brothers-appearance-on-whats-happening/|title=Actor Ernest Thomas Discusses His Career And The 40th Anniversary of The Doobie Brothers Appearance on \u2018What\u2019s Happening!!\u2019|date=2018-01-21|website=go.Jimmy.go|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\nHe has an eye condition called [[amblyopia]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Filmography==\n*1976-1979: ''[[What's Happening!!]]'' (TV Series) - Roger 'Raj' Thomas\n*1977: ''[[A Piece of the Action (film)|A Piece of the Action]]'' - John\n*1985-1988: ''[[What's Happening Now!!]]'' (TV Series) - Roger 'Raj' Thomas\n*1991: ''Kiss and Be Killed'' - Det. Ross\n*1992: ''[[Malcolm X (1992 film)|Malcolm X]]'' - Sidney\n*2003: ''The Watermelon Heist'' - Jailer\n*2003: ''[[Dickie Roberts: Former Child Star]]'' - Ernest Thomas\n*2005-2009: ''[[Everybody Hates Chris]]'' (TV Series) - Mr. Omar / Funeral Director / Radical Man\n*2007: ''Paroled'' - Royce Henderson\n*2009: ''[[Funny People]]'' - Yo Teach Principal\n*2012: ''[[The Lords of Salem (film)|The Lords of Salem]]'' - Chip McDonald (Frankenstein and the Witchhunter) (uncredited)\n*2013: ''The Pastor and Mrs. Jones'' - Pastor\n*2014: ''Basketball Girlfriend'' - Lenny\n*2014: ''Revenge'' - Neville\n*2014: ''The Slimbones'' - Uncle AB\n*2015: ''[[Mega Shark vs. Kolossus]]'' - Admiral Titus Jackson\n*2015: ''[[Chocolate City (film)|Chocolate City]]'' - Diner Manager\n*2016: '''79 Parts'' - Priore\n*2016: ''Stop Bullying Now: Live from the Big House'' - Himself\n*2016 - ''Earworm'' (short)\n*2017: ''[[Chocolate City: Vegas Strip]]'' - Mr. Williams\n*2017: ''The Gods'' - Olympus\n*2017: ''Two Wolves'' - Olivier\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n*{{IMDb name|0858808}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thomas, Ernest}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Indiana]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:African-American male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:People from Gary, Indiana]]\n", "name_user": "Dismas", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWhat's Happening Now!! and later career:italics for title", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ernest_Lee_Thomas"}
{"title_page": "Amelia Rose Earhart", "text_new": "{{short description|American journalist and aviator}}\n{{short description|American journalist}}\n{{Use American English|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox aviator\n|name                = Amelia Rose Earhart\n|image               = Amelia Rose Earhart Media Photo.jpg\n|image_size          = \n|alt                 = Earhart smiling to the camera\n|caption             = Earhart circa 2013\n|native_name         = \n|native_name_lang    = \n|full_name           = \n|birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1983|1|18|mf=yes}}<ref>{{IMDb name|id=nm5873500}}</ref>\n|birth_place     = [[Downey, California]]\n|death_date      = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n|death_place     = \n|death_cause     = \n|resting_place   = \n|resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LATITUDE|LONGITUDE|type:landmark}} -->\n|monuments       = \n|nationality     = [[Americans|American]]\n|education       = \n|spouse          = \n|relatives       = \n|known_for       = Completed a global circumnavigation flight in a single-engine aircraft; traffic and weather news anchor for [[KUSA-TV]] in [[Denver, Colorado]]\n|first_flight_aircraft = \n|first_flight_date     = June 2, 2004\n|famous_flights  = Global circumnavigation from June 26&nbsp;\u2013 July 11, 2014\n|license_date    = \n|license_place   = \n|air_force       = \n|battles         = \n|rank            = \n|awards          = \n|memorials       = \n|first_race      = <!-- For racing aviators -->\n|racing_best     = <!-- For racing aviators -->\n|racing_aircraft = <!-- For racing aviators -->\n|website         = {{URL|www.flywithamelia.org/}}\n|module          = \n}}\n\n'''Amelia Rose Earhart''' (born 1983 in [[Downey, California]], [[United States]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.flywithamelia.org/team/ |title=The Amelia Project |publisher=Flywithamelia.org |date=2004-06-02 |accessdate=2014-02-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203071428/http://www.flywithamelia.org/team/ |archive-date=2014-02-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>) is an American [[Pilot (aircraft)|private pilot]] and [[reporter]] for NBC affiliate<ref>[http://www.9news.com/rss/story.aspx?storyid=375097 \"Traffic and Weather Reporter Amelia Earhart leaving 9NEWS, decides to chase her aviation dreams\"]{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} 9NEWS</ref> [[KUSA-TV]] in [[Denver, Colorado]], where she resides. In 2013 Earhart started the ''Fly With Amelia Foundation'', which grants flight scholarships to girls aged 16\u201318.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.flywithamelia.org/foundation/ |title=Foundation |website=The Amelia Project |publisher=Flywithamelia.org |last=Earhart |first=Amelia Rose |date=n.d. |accessdate=2014-02-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203121029/http://www.flywithamelia.org/foundation/ |archive-date=2014-02-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nEarhart was told by family members in her youth that she was a descendant of [[Amelia Mary Earhart]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Larry Copeland |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2013/07/31/amelia-earhart-amelia-rose-earhart-flight/2595857/ |title=TV anchor, namesake to re-create Amelia Earhart flight |publisher=usatoday.com |date=2013-07-31 |accessdate=2014-02-08}}</ref> When she was in college, she hired a genealogist to research her connection to Amelia Earhart. That genealogist told her that she and Amelia shared a \"distant common ancestry traced back to the 1700s\", however, a second genealogical search in 2013 found there was no traceable connection.<ref name=\"Mission\">{{cite web|url = http://www.flywithamelia.org/mission/|title = The Mission|accessdate = 12 February 2014|last = Earhart|first = Amelia Rose |date = 15 June 2014 |publisher = flywithamelia.org  |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140203090056/http://www.flywithamelia.org/mission/ |archivedate = 3 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Linda Carroll |url=http://www.today.com/news/modern-day-amelia-earhart-not-related-famous-aviator-6C10898691 |title=Modern-day Amelia Earhart not related to famous aviator |publisher=TODAY.com |date=2013-08-12 |accessdate=2014-02-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://flighttraining.aopa.org/magazine/2012/March/debrief.html |title=Debrief / Amelia Rose Earhart \u2013 Flight Training |publisher=Flighttraining.aopa.org |date=2006-11-30 |accessdate=2014-02-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=The Amelia Project |date=July 31, 2013 |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/amelia-rose-earhart-takes-flight-120000168.html |title=Amelia Rose Earhart Takes Flight; Announces Plans to Retrace Namesake's Legendary Around-the-World Adventure |publisher=Finance.yahoo.com  |accessdate=2014-02-08}}</ref>\n\nEarhart took her first flying lesson on June 2, 2004, and obtained her [[private pilot certificate]] in a [[Cessna 172]]. In December 2011, she recreated her namesake's transcontinental flight from [[Oakland, California]] to [[Miami, Florida]] in a [[Cirrus SR22]], as a completion of her instrument training hours.<ref>{{cite web|last=Grady |first=Mary |url=http://www.avweb.com/avwebflash/news/AmeliaEarhartFliesACirrus_205917-1.html |title=Amelia Earhart Flies A Cirrus  |publisher=Avweb.com |date=December 21, 2011 |accessdate=2014-06-01}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013 she was awarded the Amelia Earhart Pioneering Achievement Award by the [[Atchison, Kansas]] Chamber of Commerce. The award is given to the woman who carries on Amelia Earhart's spirit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atchisonkansas.net/index.php/chamber-events/amelia-earhart-festival/todays-pioneers/ |title=Today\u2019s Pioneers |publisher= Atchison Chamber of Commerce |date= |accessdate=2014-02-08}}</ref>\n\nIn partnership with Denver's [[Wings Over the Rockies Air and Space Museum]], Earhart completed a circumnavigation of the globe in a single-engine airplane with her copilot, Shane Jordan.<ref>{{cite web|author=Nina Bahadur |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/01/29/amelia-rose-earhart-flying-across-world_n_4690107.html |title=Meet Amelia Rose Earhart, The Woman Flying Around The World In 17 Days |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date=January 29, 2014 |accessdate=2014-02-08}}</ref><ref name=\"PressRelease01\">{{cite web|url = http://www.flywithamelia.org/press/Amelia%20Rose%20Earhart%20Takes%20Flight_Oshkosh%20Announcement.pdf|title = Amelia  Rose  Earhart  Takes  Flight;   Announces  Plans  to  Retrace Namesake\u2019s Legendary  Around the World Adventure|accessdate = 12 February 2014|last = Earhart|first = Amelia Rose|date = n.d. |publisher = flywithalelia.org |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140222134034/http://www.flywithamelia.org/press/Amelia%20Rose%20Earhart%20Takes%20Flight_Oshkosh%20Announcement.pdf |archivedate = 22 February 2014}}</ref><ref>Griggs, Mary Beth, [http://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/another-amelia-earhart-trying-fly-around-world-180951816/#9KDESYkYZ613doJ3.99 \"Another Amelia Earhart is Trying to Fly Around the World\"] ''Smithsonian Magazine'', June 20, 2014, retrieved June 21, 2014</ref> Her route was to fly across the US, then south into the Caribbean, northeast Brazil, the [[South Atlantic Ocean]], then the African continent, the Indian Ocean, the Pacific Islands, and the Pacific Ocean before returning to California.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.getconnected.aero/2014/05/ebace-2014-satellite-connectivity-help-recreate-amelia-earharts-flight/ |title=EBACE 2014: Connectivity to help relay Amelia Earhart\u2019s flight |first=Steve |last=Nichols |date=May 21, 2014 |publisher=Get Connected}} retrieved June 21, 2014</ref> Earhart and Jordan started the global circumnavigation flight on June 26, 2014, departing Oakland, California at 8:19 am Pacific Standard Time in a single engine [[Pilatus PC-12]] NG. They made 17 stops during the 24,300 nautical-mile trip over 108 flying hours, landing back in Oakland without incident on July 11, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/amelia-earhart-namesake-complete-historic-flight-article-1.1836534 |title=Amelia Earhart\u2019s namesake to attempt legendary pilot\u2019s flight around the world |publisher=NY Daily News |date=June 19, 2014 |first=Nina|last=Golgowski  |accessdate=2014-06-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ameliaearhartproject.com/faq/ |title=Frequently Asked Questions and Facts \u2013 The Amelia Project |publisher=Ameliaearhartproject.com |date= |accessdate=2014-06-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/watch/nightly-news/modern-day-amelia-earhart-sets-off-to-circle-the-globe-290122307897 |title=Modern-Day Amelia Earhart Sets Off to Circle the Globe |publisher=NBC News |date= |accessdate=2014-06-27}}</ref><ref name=FlightAware>{{citation |url=http://flightaware.com/live/flight/N58NG |title=N58NG |publisher=FlightAware}}</ref><ref name=FlightAware /><ref>{{cite web |author=Joshua Hubbard |url=http://www.9news.com/story/news/2014/06/25/amelia-earhart-flight-around-world/11346715/ |title=Amelia Earhart to start global flight on Thursday |publisher=9news.com |date=June 25, 2014 |accessdate=June 25, 2014 }}{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/ameliaroseearhart |title=Amelia Rose Earhart |publisher=Facebook |date= |accessdate=2014-06-25}}</ref><ref>Silva, Shayla (3 July 2014), [http://www.flyingmag.com/pilots-places/pilots-adventures-more/pilot-named-amelia-earhart-flies-around-world-honorary-flight#srPL8rJ4wVVx1xx5.99 Pilot Named Amelia Earhart Flies Around the World in Honorary Flight], [[Flying Magazine]], retrieved 4 July 2014.</ref><ref>[http://www.jump-in.com.au/show/today/videos/3661627397001/ Amelia Earhart Queen of the skies on Australian \"Today\" show]</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Lee |first=Henry K. |url=http://blog.sfgate.com/stew/2014/07/11/amelia-rose-earhart-completes-round-the-world-flight/ |title=Amelia Rose Earhart completes round-the-world flight \u2013 SFGate Blog |publisher=Blog.sfgate.com |date= |accessdate=2014-07-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kitv.com/news/woman-named-after-aviation-pioneer-retraces-flight/26892904#!bdwdm0 |title=Woman named after aviation pioneer retraces flight &#124; More Local News \u2013 KITV Home |publisher=Kitv.com |date=2014-07-03 |accessdate=2014-07-12}}</ref> On July 9, as she and Jordan were flying over [[Howland Island]] (the island Amelia Mary Earhart was searching for during her 1937 disappearance) she announced, via Twitter, the names of the first recipients of the Fly With Amelia Foundation flight training scholarships.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Amelia__Earhart |title=Amelia Earhart (Amelia__Earhart) on Twitter |publisher=Twitter.com |date=2010-04-15 |accessdate=2014-07-12}}</ref><ref>https://www.facebook.com/ameliaroseearhart| Amelia Rose Earhart Facebook page</ref><ref name=\"fox\"/><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/07/15/amelia-rose-earhart-pilot_n_5585998.html?ncid=fcbklnkushpmg00000046/ |title=How Pilot Amelia Rose Earhart Is Breaking Through The Glass Ceiling Of Aviation|publisher=HuffPost Live |first=Rahel |last=Gebreyes |date=July 15, 2014|accessdate=2014-07-16}}</ref>\n\nAlthough widely reported (and claiming)<ref name=fox>{{cite interview| url=http://foxnewsinsider.com/2014/07/14/amelia-rose-earhart-completes-namesake%E2%80%99s-around-world-flight |title=Amelia Rose Earhart Completes Namesake\u2019s Around-the-World Flight |publisher=Fox News Insider |date=2011-07-06 |accessdate=2014-07-15}}</ref> to have become the youngest woman to fly around the world, she is in fact the second youngest behind [[Richarda Morrow-Tait]], who was also the first woman to pilot a plane around the globe.<ref name=Stinson>{{cite book|title=Around-the-World Flights: A History|last=Stinson|first=Patrick M.|date=2011|publisher=McFarland|isbn=0786462825 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PaLLtQ3tO_gC&pg=PA187|page=187}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.flywithamelia.org/}}\n*[http://www.5280.com/magazine/2013/11/being-amelia?page=full ''Being Amelia: Who is Amelia Earhart?'']\n*[http://www.kansascity.com/living/article620439.html Amelia Earhart namesake with Kansas ties to re-create famous global flight]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QLCVXccNJt0 Earhart's flight across the US, in San Antonio Texas, 2011]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Earhart, Amelia Rose}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:American reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:American television journalists]]\n[[Category:Television personalities from California]]\n[[Category:People from Downey, California]]\n[[Category:Aviators from Colorado]]\n[[Category:American female aviators]]\n[[Category:2014 in California]]\n{{US-tv-journalist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American journalist and aviator}}\n{{short description|American journalist}}\n{{Use American English|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox aviator\n|name                = Amelia Rose Earhart\n|image               = Amelia Rose Earhart Media Photo.jpg\n|image_size          = \n|alt                 = Earhart smiling to the camera\n|caption             = Earhart circa 2013\n|native_name         = \n|native_name_lang    = \n|full_name           = \n|birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1983|1|18|mf=yes}}<ref>{{IMDb name|id=nm5873500}}</ref>\n|birth_place     = [[Downey, California]]\n|death_date      = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n|death_place     = \n|death_cause     = \n|resting_place   = \n|resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LATITUDE|LONGITUDE|type:landmark}} -->\n|monuments       = \n|nationality     = [[Americans|American]]\n|education       = \n|spouse          = \n|relatives       = \n|known_for       = Completed a global circumnavigation flight in a single-engine aircraft; traffic and weather news anchor for [[KUSA-TV]] in [[Denver, Colorado]]\n|first_flight_aircraft = \n|first_flight_date     = June 2, 2004\n|famous_flights  = Global circumnavigation from June 26&nbsp;\u2013 July 11, 2014\n|license_date    = \n|license_place   = \n|air_force       = \n|battles         = \n|rank            = \n|awards          = \n|memorials       = \n|first_race      = <!-- For racing aviators -->\n|racing_best     = <!-- For racing aviators -->\n|racing_aircraft = <!-- For racing aviators -->\n|website         = {{URL|www.flywithamelia.org/}}\n|module          = \n}}\n\n'''Amelia Rose Earhart''' (born 1983 in [[Downey, California]], [[United States]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.flywithamelia.org/team/ |title=The Amelia Project |publisher=Flywithamelia.org |date=2004-06-02 |accessdate=2014-02-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203071428/http://www.flywithamelia.org/team/ |archive-date=2014-02-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>) is an American [[Pilot (aircraft)|private pilot]] and [[reporter]] for NBC affiliate<ref>[http://www.9news.com/rss/story.aspx?storyid=375097 \"Traffic and Weather Reporter Amelia Earhart leaving 9NEWS, decides to chase her aviation dreams\"]{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} 9NEWS</ref> [[KUSA-TV]] in [[Denver, Colorado]], where she resides. In 2013 Earhart started the ''Fly With Amelia Foundation'', which grants flight scholarships to girls aged 16\u201318.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.flywithamelia.org/foundation/ |title=Foundation |website=The Amelia Project |publisher=Flywithamelia.org |last=Earhart |first=Amelia Rose |date=n.d. |accessdate=2014-02-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203121029/http://www.flywithamelia.org/foundation/ |archive-date=2014-02-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nEarhart was told by family members in her youth that she was a descendant of [[Amelia Mary Earhart]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Larry Copeland |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2013/07/31/amelia-earhart-amelia-rose-e