itor1-last=Augustsson|editor1-first=Jan-Erik|last= Svanberg|first= Jan|date= 1996|title=Signums svenska konsthistoria. Den gotiska konsten|trans-title= Signum's history of Swedish art. Romanesque art|chapter=Stenskulpturen|trans-chapter=The stone sculpture|url= |language= Swedish|location= Lund|publisher= Signum|pages=299\u2013335|isbn=91-87896-23-0|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last= Wrangel|first= Ewert|date= 1923|title= Konstverk i Lunds domkyrka|trans-title= Art in Lund Cathedral|url= https://archive.org/details/konstverkilundsd00wran/mode/2up|location= Lund|publisher= C. W. K. Gleerup}}\n*{{cite book |last= Wrangel|first= Ewert|date= 1923|title= Lunds domkyrkas konsthistoria: f\u00f6rbindelser och stilfr\u00e4nder|trans-title= The art history of Lund Cathedral: connections and stylistic equals|url= http://libris.kb.se/bib/416081|location= Lund|publisher= C. W. K. Gleerup}}\n*{{cite book |last= Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|first= Claes|date= 2014|title= Sk\u00e5nes kyrkor 1050-1949|trans-title= The churches of Sk\u00e5ne 1050\u20131949|language=Swedish|url= http://libris.kb.se/bib/18066221|location= K\u00e4vlinge|publisher= Domus Propria|isbn= 978-91-637-5874-4}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |last= Brunius|first= Carl Georg|date= 1836|title= Nordens \u00e4ldsta metropolitankyrka, eller, historisk och arkitektonisk beskrifning \u00f6fver Lunds domkyrka|trans-title= The oldest metropolitan church in the Nordic countries, or, historic and architectonic description of Lund Cathedral|url= http://libris.kb.se/bib/1694639|language= Swedish|location= Lund|publisher= Berling}}\n*{{cite book |last= Gierow|first= Krister|date= 1946|title= Lunds domkyrka i litteraturen: bibliografisk f\u00f6rteckning|trans-title= Lund Cathedral in literature: a bibliography|language= Swedish|location= Lund|publisher= C. W. K. Gleerup|url=http://libris.kb.se/bib/1186054}}\n*{{cite book |last= Zettervall|first= Helgo|date= 1916|title= Helgo Zettervall om Lunds domkyrka: en byggnadsbeskrivning i brev|trans-title= Helgo Zettervall on Lund Cathedral: description of a building in letters|url= http://libris.kb.se/bib/10258926|language= Swedish|location= Lund|publisher= }}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://lundsdomkyrka.se/ Official website of the cathedral]\n* [http://www.alvin-portal.org/alvin/view.jsf?pid=alvin-record%3A14714&dswid=3243 Digitised copy of the ''Necrologium Lundense'', with information about the book and its contents in English]\n* [http://www.alvin-portal.org/alvin/view.jsf?pid=alvin-record%3A13276&dswid=7054 Digitised copy of the ''Liber daticus vetustior'', with information about the book and its contents in English]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC3LzcTh1FX5k3C8Y4EJI0Ew YouTube channel of the cathedral]\n\n{{Churches in Scania}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1145]]\n[[Category:12th-century churches]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Lund]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic cathedrals in pre-Reformation Sweden]]\n[[Category:Lutheran cathedrals in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Romanesque architecture in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Lund]]\n[[Category:Coronation church buildings]]\n[[Category:Churches in Sk\u00e5ne County]]\n[[Category:Churches in the Diocese of Lund]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox church\n| name                   = Lund Cathedral\n| fullname               = \n| image                  = Lund Cathedral 2017-08-17.jpg\n| imagesize              = \n| imagelink              = \n| imagealt               = \n| caption                = View of Lund Cathedral from the south east\n| coordinates            = {{coord|55|42|15|N|13|11|36|E|region:SE_type:landmark|display=title}}\n| osgraw                 = \n| osgridref              = \n| location               = [[Lund]]\n| country                = [[Sweden]]\n\n| denomination           = [[Church of Sweden]]\n| previous denomination  = [[Church of Denmark]] (until 1658)<br>[[Catholic Church]] (until the [[Reformation in Denmark\u2013Norway and Holstein|Reformation]]\n| churchmanship          = \n| membership             = \n| attendance             = \n| website                = [http://www.lundsdomkyrka.se/ Website of the Cathedral]\n\n| former name            = \n| bull date              = \n| founded date           = late 11th century\n| founder                = \n| dedication             = \n| dedicated date         = \n| consecrated date       = 1123 (crypt)<br>1145 (main altar)\n| cult                   = \n| relics                 = \n| events                 = \n| past bishop            = \n| people                 = \n\n| status                 = Active\n| functional status      = Cathedral\n| heritage designation   = [[Listed buildings in Sweden|Ecclesiastical monument]] in the buildings database of the [[Swedish National Heritage Board]].<ref name=raa>{{cite web |url= http://www.bebyggelseregistret.raa.se/bbr2/anlaggning/visaHistorik.raa?anlaggningId=21300000022524&page=historik&visaHistorik=true|title= Lund kn, DOMKYRKAN 1 LUNDS DOMKYRKA|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Bebyggelseregistret|publisher= [[Swedish National Heritage Board]]|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n| designated date        = \n| architect              = Donatus<br>[[Adam van D\u00fcren]]<br>[[Carl Georg Brunius]]<br>[[Helgo Zettervall]]\n| architectural type     = \n| style                  = \n| groundbreaking         = \n| completed date         = \n| construction cost      = \n| closed date            = \n| demolished date        = \n\n| capacity               = \n| length                 = {{convert|85|m|ft}}{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=11}}\n| width                  = {{convert|30|m|ft}}{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=11}}\n| width nave             = \n| height                 = {{convert|55|m|ft}} (to the top of the towers){{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=48}}\n| diameter               = \n| other dimensions       = \n| floor area             = \n| dome quantity          = \n| dome height outer      = \n| dome height inner      = \n| dome dia outer         = \n| dome dia inner         = \n| spire quantity         = \n| spire height           = \n| materials              = \n\n| diocese                = [[Diocese of Lund]]\n| bishop                 = [[Johan Tyrberg]]\n| logo                   = \n| logosize               = \n| logolink               = \n| logoalt                = \n}}\n'''Lund Cathedral''' ({{lang-sv|Lunds domkyrka}}) is a [[cathedral]] of the [[Church of Sweden]] in [[Lund]], [[Scania]], [[Sweden]]. It is the seat of the [[List of bishops of Lund|Bishop of Lund]] and the main church of the [[Diocese of Lund]]. It was built as the [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] cathedral of the archiepiscopal see of all the Nordic countries, dedicated to [[Lawrence of Rome|Saint Lawrence]]. It is one of the oldest stone buildings still in use in Sweden.\n\nLund Cathedral has been called \"the mightiest representative of [[Romanesque architecture]] in the [[Nordic countries]]\". Its main altar was consecrated in 1145 and the cathedral was by that time largely finished; the western towers were built somewhat later. Its architecture show clear influences from contemporary north Italian architecture, conveyed via the [[Rhine Valley]]. The earliest architect was named Donatus, though his precise role in the construction of the cathedral is difficult to determine. The new cathedral was richly decorated with stone sculpture, including two unusual statues in the crypt traditionally called \"The giant Finn and his wife\" about which a local legend has developed. The cathedral was severely damaged in a fire in 1234, and major restoration works were carried out in the early 16th century under the leadership of [[Adam van D\u00fcren]]. Following the [[Reformation in Denmark\u2013Norway and Holstein|Reformation]], the cathedral suffered from lost income and dilapidation. In 1658 the city of Lund and the cathedral became a part of Sweden following the [[Treaty of Roskilde]]. Lund Cathedral was the site of the ceremony founding [[Lund University]] in 1688. Repairs were made during the 18th century but in 1832 a complete restoration of the cathedral was recommended. Subsequently much of the cathedral was restored and rebuilt during most of the 19th century. The work was first led by [[Carl Georg Brunius]] and later by architect [[Helgo Zettervall]] and not entirely finished until 1893. The changes done during the 19th century went very far; among other things, Zettervall had the entire western part, including the towers, demolished and rebuilt to his own designs.\n\nThe medieval cathedral contains several historic furnishings and pieces of art. Its main altarpiece was donated to the cathedral in 1398, and it also contains [[Gothic art|Gothic]] choir stalls, bronzes and an [[astronomical clock]] from the 15th century (although heavily restored in 1923). When it was built, Lund Cathedral was lavishly decorated with Romanesque stone sculptures. It also contains late medieval stone sculptures from the time of Adam van D\u00fcren's renovation. After the Reformation the cathedral was also equipped with a decorated [[pulpit]]. Of more recent date is the large [[mosaic]] in the [[apse]], by [[Joakim Skovgaard]], installed in 1927. Lund Cathedral has six [[church organ]]s, one of which is the largest in Sweden, and is also used as a concert venue.\n\n==Historical background==\nChristian missionaries from present-day Germany and England were active in the [[Christianization of Scandinavia|Christianisation of Denmark]], and Denmark eventually became part of the [[Prince-Archbishopric of Bremen|Archdiocese of Hamburg-Bremen]]. With the consolidation of Danish monarchy during the second half of the 11th century, and with a political crisis in continental Europe, there arose an opportunity for the Danish monarchs to bypass the German influence over the church.{{sfn|Ryd\u00e9n|1999|p=99\u2013100}} An [[episcopal see]] was created in Lund in 1060.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=25}} At the same time, another see was created in [[Dalby]], very close to Lund. However, when the first bishop of Lund ([[Henry of Lund]]) died, the erstwhile bishop of Dalby, [[Egino (Bishop of Dalby)|Egino]], was installed in Lund and Dalby abandoned as the seat of a bishop. At the same time, in 1103, Lund was proclaimed an archiepiscopal see covering all Nordic countries.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=25\u201329}}{{sfn|Wrangel|1923|p=4\u20135}}\n\nSome kind of rudimentary settlement probably existed at the site of Lund Cathedral at the end of the 10th and early 11th centuries, but no remains of buildings have been found there.{{sfn|Cinthio|1990|p=1}} Lund Cathedral is one of the oldest stone buildings still in use in Sweden.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=7}} During the [[Middle Ages]], the cathedral was surrounded by several buildings serving the diocese, of which only [[Liberiet]], which at one point served as a library, survives.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=69\u201371}}\n\n==History==\n===Foundation and construction===\n[[File:Lund domkyrka - crypt (by Pudelek).JPG|thumb|right|The crypt, the oldest part of Lund Cathedral]]\n[[File:Crypt of Lund Cathedral.png|thumb|right|Plan of the crypt]]\nThe earliest written mention of a church in Lund dedicated to [[Saint Lawrence]] \u2014 the patron saint of Lund Cathedral during the Middle Ages \u2014 dates from 1085.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=37}} Slightly later sources mention both a new and an old church dedicated to Saint Lawrence.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=38}} During the 1940s, archaeological excavations in the cathedral uncovered the foundations of another church inside the present building. The exact age, shape and function of this predecessor to the cathedral has been a matter of some debate.{{sfn|Cinthio|1957|p=1\u201342}}{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=62\u201364}} Most scholars believe that construction of a church on the site of Lund Cathedral was begun sometime during the second half of the 11th century.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=11}} Some time thereafter a new church was begun in almost the same place, but to a larger design in the form of the present cathedral. Parts of the earlier church may have been incorporated in the walls of the cathedral.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=11}} The decision to abandon Dalby as a bishopric and make Lund the sole archbishopric in Scandinavia may have promted the change of plans.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=40}}\n\nApart from the obscurity which thus surrounds the very beginning of the history of the cathedral, the construction of Lund Cathedral is probably among the most well documented among any [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque churches]].{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=28}} Two contemporary accounts of the building of the cathedral, in the form of the [[illuminated manuscripts]] ''{{ill|Necrologium Lundense|sv}}'' and ''{{ill|Liber daticus vetustior|sv}}'', are still preserved in the library of [[Lund University]]. Both books contain notes, written in [[Latin language|Latin]], with dates on the progression of the construction. The oldest part of the cathedral is the large [[crypt]]. Its main [[altar]] was inaugurated on 30 June 1123, followed by the north (1126) and south (1131) side altars in the crypt. Only then did the cathedral begin the be used.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=28}} The main altar of the cathedral was dedicated to [[Mary, mother of Jesus|Saint Mary]] and Saint Lawrence in 1145, by the second archbishop of Lund, [[Eskil of Lund|Eskil]], in a ceremony attended by bishops from present-day Germany, Denmark and Sweden.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=29\u201330}} By then, the construction of the cathedral to more or less its present dimensions was complete.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=30}}{{sfn|Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|2004|p=186\u2013187}}\n\nUnusually for that time, the architect of the cathedral is known by his name, Donatus.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=11}}{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=30}}{{sfn|Wrangel|1923|p=164}} The name appears in both the ''Necrologium Lundense'' (as \"Donatus architectus\") and the ''Liber daticus vetustior''. Donatus may have been responsible for the layout of the crypt and the cathedral above ground as far west as the current north and south portals of the cathedral, although it is difficult to draw any definitive conclusions about his precise role.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=30}}{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=64}} The same is true for his successor, possibly a builder named Ragnar.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=32}} The building erected during the time of Donatus and his successor show clear influences from Romanesque architecture in [[Lombardy]], conveyed via the [[Rhine Valley]].{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=66}} Donatus himself appears to have been from, or at least educated in, Lombardy.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=58}} [[Speyer Cathedral]] in western Germany is stylistically closely related to Lund Cathedral (especially the crypt), and it has been proposed that Donatus came to Lund from Speyer, where construction more or less ceased in 1106 following the death of [[Henry IV, Holy Roman Emperor|Emperor Henry IV]].{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=59}}{{sfn|Wrangel|1923|p=148}} Similarities have also frequently been pointed out between Lund Cathedral and [[Mainz Cathedral]], and the design of the apse is similar to that of the [[Basilica of Saint Servatius]] in [[Maastricht]].{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=68}} On a more general level, the origins of the style of Lund Cathedral can be found in [[Basilica of Sant'Ambrogio]] ([[Milan]]), [[Modena Cathedral]] and several churches in [[Pavia]], all in northern Italy.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=62}} Similar stylistic influences can be seen in other cathedrals in Denmark from the same time, e.g. in [[Ribe Cathedral]].{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=64}}\n\nThe building of Lund Cathedral must have involved a large number of people and was a collective undertaking.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=68}} Comparable but somewhat later workshops at [[Cologne Cathedral]] and [[Uppsala Cathedral]] employed a workforce of about 100 and 60 people, respectively.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=68}} The project was instrumental in establishing a workshop where local craftsmen could be educated, and thus disseminating artistic influences from continental Europe in Scandinavia. The stone sculptors {{ill|Carl stenm\u00e4stare|sv}}, {{ill|M\u00e5rten stenm\u00e4stare|sv}} and [[Majestatis]] were probably all Scandinavians who were educated at the construction site.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=62}} Many early Romanesque stone churches in the countryside, particularly in Scania but also in the rest of Sweden, show direct influences from Lund Cathedral, notably {{ill|V\u00e4 Church|sv|V\u00e4 kyrka}} (Scania).{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=79\u201381}}{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=265\u2013281}} Other examples are e.g. {{ill|Lannaskede Old Church|sv|Lannaskede gamla kyrka}} ([[Sm\u00e5land]]), {{ill|Hogstad Church|sv|Hogstads kyrka}} ([[\u00d6sterg\u00f6tland]]) and [[Havdhem Church]] ([[Gotland]]).{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=90\u201392}}\n\n===Fire and repairs===\nThe plan and layout of the building consecrated in 1145 was by and large similar to the one see today. A noticeable difference was that the entire choir was separated from the nave by a wall and reserved for the clergy. The towers were also not built until a few decades later.{{sfn|Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|2014|p=187}}{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=52}} The intention was probably to provide the cathedral with [[vault (architecture)|vaults]], but instead a flat wooden ceiling was installed.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=68\u201369}} The cathedral was adorned with [[Church murals in Sweden|wall paintings]] and almost certainly by [[Medieval stained glass in Sweden|stained glass windows]], but none of these remain.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=66}} In 1234, the cathedral was heavily damaged by a large fire.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=78}} Large donations were to the church in the following years, to allow for repairs.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=74}} Even so, repairs were continuously made during the entire 13th century.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=80}} Following the fire, the burnt-out ceiling was replaced by [[brick]] vaults.{{sfn|Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|2014|p=187}} Changes were also made to the layout of the westernmost part of the building.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=76}} A conflict erupted between King [[Christopher I of Denmark]] and Archbishop [[Jakob Erlandsen]] in 1257 partially because the choir had been enlarged and the seats of the royal family moved, itself a testimony of the growing power of the Church.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=76\u201378}} Two [[chapel]]s were added to the cathedral during the 14th and 15th centuries; one located adjacent to the two westernmost [[Bay (architecture)|bays]] of the south aisle of the nave, and the other as a southern extension of the east transept.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=80\u201381}} [[Buttress]]es were also added piecemeal to the building during the 13th and 14th centuries, to stabilise the building which was under strain from the new, heavier vaults, the added chapels and the constant ringing of the 8.5 [[tonne]] [[church bell]].{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=86\u201387}}\n\n===Changes by Adam van D\u00fcren and later===\n[[File:Lunds domkyrka - KMB - 16001000533737.jpg|thumb|right|A drawing of the cathedral as it appeared in 1750]]\nThe German sculptor and builder [[Adam van D\u00fcren]] apparently worked intermittently at restoring and altering the cathedral between {{circa}} 1506 or 1507 and 1524.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=90\u201391}} Despite, and to some extent because of, the work that had been done during the preceding centuries since the great fire of 1234, the cathedral was in need of a thorough restoration.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=87}} Adam van D\u00fcren and his workshop made several changes and contributions. A new drainage system was installed in the crypt, and as part of that work a [[well]], which probably replaced an earlier well in the same location, was decorated with [[satire|satirical]] [[allegory|allegories]].{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=12}}{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=88\u201395}} The workshop of van D\u00fcren also created two new windows in the choir, built a large buttress to support the southern transept (before 1513), and rebuilt the [[gable]] of the northern transept (1524) as well as its vaults. New and considerably larger windows with [[Pointed arch (architecture)|pointed arches]] were installed in both the northern wall of the north transept and in the southern wall of the south transept.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=12}}{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=100}} The towers and western facade were also repaired in 1512\u201318 and again in 1527.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=91}} It has been argued that the cathedral may have collapsed, were it not for the work done by van D\u00fcren.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=104}}\n\nFollowing the Reformation in the 16th century, the diocese lost much of its revenues.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=126}} The building was still subjected to much stress, not least by the use of the large church bell, and suffered during the recurrent [[List of wars involving Denmark|wars between Denmark and Sweden]]; in 1658 Lund permanently became part of Sweden. Despite van D\u00fcren's repairs, the church was described as being \"very dilapidated\" in 1682.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=128}} During the 18th century, the chapels of the church were used for funerals, but also as an improvised [[morgue]] where corpses were occasionally left for several years.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=130}} Attempts at repairs were made; among them the entire apse was dismantled and then re-erected.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=12}} Many of the repairs were however either temporary or outright detrimental to condition of the building. King [[Gustav III of Sweden]] visited the cathedral crypt in 1785 and expressed his displeasure at its state.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=13}}{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=132}} In 1812, the aforementioned chapels from the 14th and 15th centuries were demolished.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=134}}\n\n===Changes by Carl Georg Brunius and Helgo Zettervall===\n[[File:Demolition of the tower of Lund Cathedral.jpg|thumb|right|Demolition of the south tower of the cathedral during the time of Zettervall]]\nWhen the congregation wanted to build a new [[church organ]] in the early 19th century, architect {{ill|Axel Nystr\u00f6m|sv|Axel Nystr\u00f6m (1793\u20131868)}} was invited to examine the situation in 1832. Nystr\u00f6m recommended a complete renovation of the cathedral.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=134}} The chairman of the council in charge of administering the cathedral buildings, [[Carl Georg Brunius]], was called to execute the plans of Nystr\u00f6m, and he did so while also making changes according to his own convictions. He also wrote the first systematic art history of the cathedral.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=135}} Brunius had the organ moved, the crypt repaired, installed a set of steps connecting the choir with the nave and improved the drainage system.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=135}} He also removed modern furnishings, re-built some of the buttresses and changed the stone of a large part of the facade.{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=121}} Brunius retired due to old age in 1859, but as there was still a substantial need for repairs, the young architect [[Helgo Zettervall]] appointed to carry out the rest of the work in 1860.{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=121\u2013122}} A conflict between Brunius and Zettervall developed almost immediately, but Zettervall would keep working on restoring the cathedral until 1893 and ultimately got his will through, for the most part.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=135}}{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=121\u2013181}} A compromise in 1862 proposed that the Danish architect [[Ferdinand Meldahl]] would assume the main responsibility, and Zettervall would merely assist Meldahl. However, it soon became apparent that Zettervall would not accept a subordinate role and Meldahl himself showed little interest in the project.{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=141}} In 1862 Zettervall traveled extensively through Germany and Italy to study stylistically related architecture, and also to visit the latest examples of building restoration so that he could draw upon that experience in his work at Lund.{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=134\u2013141}} In 1863, he presented a first proposal for a complete restoration of the cathedral. Zettervall himself considered it a \"reasonable middle ground between reparation and reconstruction\".{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=142}} The proposal would mean the removal of all buttresses, a new roof, completely rebuilt towers, and the removal of the large Gothic windows in the transepts. Zettervall also proposed to add an octagonal dome over the [[Crossing (architecture)|crossing]]. Far-reaching changes would also affect the interior. In the proposal Zettervall strove to reduce and refine the building volumes of the cathedral and create a unified composition of block-like elements.{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=142\u2212152}}\n\nThe proposal by Zettervall was criticised, not least by Meldahl. Zettervall re-worked the proposal and put forward a revised, less far-reaching proposal in 1864, notably without the central dome.{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=152}} This proposal was also rejected and the plan for a complete overhaul abandoned; however it was at the same time decided that Zettervall would continue working on repairing the cathedral and every year make what changes that were deemed necessary. In this way, Zettervall could piecemeal over the next decades in effect rebuild the cathedral largely in line with the proposal from 1864.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=135}}{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=158\u2013159}}\n\nThe cathedral was radically transformed by the work of Brunius and Zettervall. All windows were replaced, several vaults and pillars were repaired or rebuilt, and both architects effected extensive changes to the transept. Just as he had suggested, Zettervall had all the buttresses removed and demolished the entire western part of the church, including the towers, and rebuilt them according to his own [[Romanesque Revival architecture|Neo-Romanesque]] designs.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=13\u201314}}<ref name=byggnaden>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/rundtur/byggnaden/|title= En kyrka i st\u00e4ndig f\u00f6r\u00e4ndring|trans-title= A constantly changing church|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\nIn the 20th century, archaeological excavations were carried out in and around the cathedral. The building also underwent a major restoration in 1954\u20131963, led by architect {{ill|Eiler Gr\u00e6be|sv}}. During this time the decorative painting from the 19th century was removed.<ref name=byggnaden/> The large [[mosaic]] decorating the apse was installed in 1927, to designs by [[Joakim Skovgaard]].{{sfn|Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|2014|p=187}}{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=14}} In 1990 the layout of the choir was changed and the altar placed in the crossing.<ref name=byggnaden/> [[Pope Francis]] visited the cathedral on 31 October 2016 to observe the 499th anniversary of the [[Protestant Reformation|Reformation]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Anderson|first1=Christina|title=Pope Francis, in Sweden, Urges Catholic-Lutheran Reconciliation|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/01/world/europe/pope-francis-in-sweden-urges-catholic-lutheran-reconciliation.html|accessdate=1 November 2016|work=The New York Times|date=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Architecture and decoration==\nLund Cathedral has been called \"the mightiest representative of Romanesque architecture in the Nordic countries\".{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=11}} It consists of the two towers built by Zettervall, which flank the main entrance to the west. Behind them a [[nave]] with two [[aisle]] opens up to a [[transept]] that is somewhat higher than the nave. A short flight of stairs thus connect the nave with the [[choir (architecture)|choir]] and with the crypt under it. The choir ends in an apse. Two bronze doors built by {{ill|Carl Johan Dyfverman|sv|Carl Johan Dyfverman (konstn\u00e4r)}} serve as the main entrance. They have 24 reliefs with subjects from the Bible, particularly the Old Testament. Above the doorway, the tympanon depicts Christ, Canute IV of Denmark and Saint Lawrence.<ref name=byggnaden/> The original, Romanesque, north and south entrances of the nave still exist. The cathedral has two [[sacristy|sacristies]].{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=48}} The bays are supported by [[groin vault]]s.\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" caption=\"Overview of Lund Cathedral\" heights=\"175px\">\nFile:Lunds domkyrka. Plan.png|Plan\nFile:Lunds domkyrka\u2013flygbild 06 september 2014.jpg|Aerial view from the south east\nFile:Lund Cathedral 2017-08-17 4.jpg|View from the entrance towards east\nFile:Lund cathedral interior 2015-03-30-4746.jpg|View from the altar towards west\n</gallery>\n\n===Sculptures===\n[[File:Finn the Giant, Lund Cathedral crypt 2017-08-17 1.jpg|thumb|right|\"The giant Finn\" in the crypt, probably a depiction of the biblical hero Samson]]\nWhen it comes to stone sculpture, Lund Cathedral was the most lavishly decorated Romanesque building to be built in the Nordic countries.{{sfn|Svanberg|1995|p=152}} Perhaps the most well-known and striking of these are the sculptures of two figures traditionally called \"The giant [[Fin (troll)|Finn]] and his wife\" in the crypt.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=75}} According to a local legend, the giant helped build the cathedral, but when he was not payed for his services he tried to destroy it by shaking the pillars, but was petrified.<ref name=finn>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/fordjupning/jatten-finn/|title= J\u00e4tten Finn vakar \u00f6ver kryptan|trans-title= The giant Finn watches over the crypt|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref> The larger of the two figures is embracing a column, while the smaller is attached to another column with a rope. These sculptures have probably been the subject of more attempts at an explanation than any other medieval artworks in Sweden.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=77}} Most scholars today believe thelarger sculpture depicts [[Samson]], but what the smaller figure is supposed to represent is not know. The sculptures date from the construction of the crypt but have been treated poorly, especially during the 18th century, and lost much of their original detailing.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=77}}\n\nThe fluted columns also found in the crypt are similar in style to [[Norman architecture|English Norman architecture]] and may indicate that the very first artistic influences came from the area bordering the [[English Channel]].{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=64\u201365}} Apart from these columns however, the rich stone ornamentation is clearly Lombard in style, i.e. strongly related to north Italian art of the period.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=66}} The southern portal of the nave is perhaps the oldest of the cathedral. Five decorated [[archivolt]]s supported by small columns with variously decorated [[capital (architecture)|capitals]], frame a [[tympanon]] depicting the [[Lamb of God]].{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=70\u201371}} The northern portal is slightly later and more richly decorated. The original western portal is not preserved, but a [[baldachin]] now immured in the east wall of the north transept may have been part of it; Its columns have [[Corinthian order|Corinthian capitals]] and support a richly decorated archivolt on which traces of original paint survives. Opposite, in the south wall, is a smaller baldachin where the columns themselves are sculpted angels (one with [[feather tights]]) standing on lions. Similar sculptures exist in e.g. [[Como]] and Modena in northern Italy.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=74\u201375}} In addition, the capitals of the columns in the church are all of high artisanal quality, and can be broadly divided into two groups displaying either [[Classical architecture|Classical]] or [[Byzantine architecture|Byzantine]] influences.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=75}} Apart from its rich Romanesque decoration, Lund Cathedral also contains several late medieval sculptures made by Adam van D\u00fcren, as mentioned above. Several of these are of animals and contain inscriptions in [[Low German]]. A relief in the south transept displaying the [[Woman of the Apocalypse]] flanked by Saint Lawrence and Saint Canute is similar to the portal relief van D\u00fcren made a couple of years earlier at [[Glimmingehus]].{{sfn|Svanberg|1996|p=196\u2013197}}\n\n===Altarpiece===\nThe medieval main [[altarpiece]] was donated to the cathedral in 1398 by [[Ide Pedersdatter Falk]].<ref name=kor>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/rundtur/hogkoret/|title= Gyllene mosaik och korstolar fr\u00e5n 1300-talet|trans-title= Golden mosaics and choir stalls from the 14th century|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref> The altarpiece is stylistically similar to a group of altarpieces from northern Germany. Its central panel depicts the [[Coronation of the Virgin]], surrounded by two rows of 40 saints, 26 of which are original. 12 figures have been taken from other medieval altarpieces, while two of the added figures are from the 17th century. The altarpiece is {{convert|7.6|m|ft}} wide but is missing an original pair of wings.{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=20\u201323}}{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=112\u2013113}}\n\n===Choir stalls===\n[[File:Lunds Domkyrka korstolar h\u00f6ger om koret.JPG|thumb|right|The right side of the choir, showing parts of the choir stalls (right) and the main altarpiece (left)]]\nThe choir contains two rows of medieval choir stalls containing in total 78 seats. The wooden stalls date from the end of the 14th century, probably commissioned by archbishop Nils J\u00f6nson some time between 1361 and 1379. They were clearly made by several different wood carvers. They are approximately {{convert|3|m|ft}} tall without their gables and profusely decorated with carved details. These are biblical scenes from both the [[Old Testament|Old]] and [[New Testament]], but the stalls also contain [[misericord]]s portraying animals and other small details. Their style is [[Gothic art|High Gothic]] and they are stylistically linked with contemporary art from the Rhine Valley. They are among the largest wooden Gothic sculptures to survive in the Nordic countries, and have been described as being of internationally high quality. The choir stalls in Lund Cathedral also lent stylistic inspiration to the choir stalls in [[Roskilde Cathedral]] and [[St. Bendt's Church, Ringsted]].{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=24\u201332}}{{sfn|Dun\u00e9r|1984|p=1\u20139}}\n\nSlightly older than the choir stalls is a [[Cathedra|bishop's throne]] which survives in a damaged state and is placed in the south transept. It is somewhat similar in construction to the choir stalls but stylistically different and more closely related to contemporary art from north Germany.{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=32\u201335}}\n\n===Astronomical clock===\n{{Main|Horologium mirabile Lundense}}\n[[File:Lunds astronomiska ur-2.jpg|thumb|right|The astronomical clock]]\nThe [[astronomical clock]] of Lund Cathedral, presently located at the west end of the north aisle, dates from the late Middle Ages and was installed in Lund Cathedral {{circa}} 1425. In 1837 it was dismantled. It was restored at the initiative of architect {{ill|Theodor W\u00e5hlin|sv}} and the Danish clock-maker Julius Bertram Larsen and re-inaugurated in 1923. The upper part, which is original, is the clock, while the lower part, a reconstruction, is a calendar. Twice every day the two knights on the top clash their swords. The clock then plays the tune ''[[In dulci jubilo]]'' and a procession of figures parades across the face of the clock.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=125\u2013126}} Three astronomical clocks of similar design are preserved in Europe. The clock in Lund was repaired 2009\u20132010.{{sfn|Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|2014|p=187}}<ref name=svt>{{cite web |url= https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/skane/lund-uret-i-domkyrkan-slutar-sla|title= Lund \u2013 Uret i domkyrkan slutar sl\u00e5|trans-title= The clock in  the cathedral ceases to strike|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 12 October 2009|website= |publisher= [[Sveriges television]]|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref><ref name=uret>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/rundtur/uret/|title= Det underbara uret i Lund|trans-title= The astonishing clock in Lund|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\n===Bronzes===\nThe cathedral also owns three High Gothic [[bronze]] columns carrying statuettes and a seven-branched candelabrum from the end of the Middle Ages. Two of the bronze columns are crowned by angels, and the third one by a statuette of Saint Lawrence, holding a gridiron, the symbol of his martyrdom. It probably dates from the middle of the 14th century, while the two angel-bearing columns may be somewhat later. Saint Lawrence's column is approximately {{convert|3|m|ft}} tall (and the saint {{convert|70|cm|inch}}), while the columns with angels are slightly smaller.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=114}} The three columns were probably made in [[L\u00fcbeck]] or [[Hamburg]]. Presently located in the south transept is also the {{convert|3.5|m|ft}} tall seven-branched candelabrum or candle holder from the late 15th century, manufactured by Harmen Bonstede in Hamburg.<ref name=stake>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/rundtur/sjuarmade-ljusstakens-kapell/|title= V\u00e5r tids martyrer och den sjuarmade ljusstaken|trans-title= The martyrs of our time and the seven-branched candelabrum|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref> It was supplied to the cathedral in a dismantled state, and traces of its assembly instruction is still discernible on the candelabrum. Similar candelabra were installed in a number of Scandinavian cathedrals at approximately the same time; although the one in Lund is larger than those in the cathedrals of [[Aarhus Cathedral|Aarhus]], Ribe, [[Viborg Cathedral|Viborg]] and [[Storkyrkan|Stockholm]].<ref name=stake/>{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=114\u2013116}}\n\n===Pulpit===\nThe current [[pulpit]] was commissioned at the end of the 16th century and is marked with the date 1592. The artist was [[Johannes Ganssog]] from [[Frankfurt and der Oder]] in present-day Germany. It is technically skillfully attached to one of the pillars of the nave, and it is entered through a stair cut inside the pillar. The building material is sandstone, black [[limestone]] and black and white [[marble]], and it is partially painted and [[gilding|gilded]]. Reliefs of [[alabaster]] on the side show scenes from the New Testament.{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=60\u201364}}{{sfn|Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|2014|p=187}}\n\n==Flora==\n[[File:Flickr - Sigfrid Lundberg - Wall-rue, Asplenium ruta-muraria.jpg|thumb|right|Wall-rue growing on the apse]]\nSeveral surveys and descriptions of the [[flora]] of the cathedral, i.e. the plants that grow on its walls, have been made. The first to describe the flora of the cathedral was [[Daniel Rolander]], one of the [[apostles of Linnaeus]], who made a list of the [[vascular plant]]s, [[moss]]es and [[lichen]] he found growing on the building in 1771.{{sfn|Johansson|1993|p=25}} It was rediscovered in the 20th century and published in 1931. [[Elias Magnus Fries]] also made observations about the flora of the cathedral during the first half of the 19th century. More systematic surveys of the flora of the building have been published in 1922 and in 1993 (the latter only encompassing lichen).{{sfn|Johansson|1993|p=25}} Of the species observed growing on the cathedral, the minute [[fern]] [[Asplenium ruta-muraria|wall-rue]] was mentioned as early as 1756 by {{ill|Anders Tidstr\u00f6m|sv}} and is perhaps the most conspicuous member of the cathedral flora.{{sfn|Gertz|1923|p=458}} When the lichen flora was surveyed in 1993, 15 species were discovered. One of these, [[Lecanora perpruinosa]], had not been observed in the province of Scania before.{{sfn|Johansson|1993|p=26}}\n\n==Relationship with Lund University==\n[[Lund University]] was founded in a ceremony in the cathedral in 1688.<ref name=nyckeltal>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/fordjupning/nyckelartal/|title= Ett p\u00e4rlband av h\u00e4ndelser|trans-title= A string of events|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 20 April 2020|quote=}}</ref> Following the Reformation, the choir of the cathedral was for a long time used as a classroom, first by [[Lund Cathedral School]] and later by the university. The university also used the choir to store its [[library]] for some time.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=128\u2013129}} The cathedral is still the place for the ceremony of the conferment of new doctor's degrees at the university.<ref name=universitet>{{cite web |url= https://www.lu.se/om-universitetet/akademiska-hogtider/doktorspromotionen/promotionsdagen|title= Promotionsdagen|trans-title= The day of conferment of the doctor's degree|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= |publisher= [[Lund University]]|access-date= 20 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\nThe cathedral has five [[choir (music)|choirs]] for adults and two choirs for children.<ref name=korer>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/musik-kultur/korer-2/|title= K\u00f6rer|trans-title= Choirs|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 20 April 2020|quote=}}</ref> The cathedral is also frequently used for concerts.\n\nThere are currently six church organs in Lund Cathedral, including the largest church organ in Sweden. The gallery organ was built between 1932 and 1934 by the Danish company Marcussen & S\u00f8n and renovated by the same company in 1992. It has 102 stops distributed between four manuals and a pedalboard. There are 7,074 pipes in total. The smallest organ is inside the astronomical clock, where it plays ''In dulci jubilo''.<ref name=orglar>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/fordjupning/orglar/|title= Sex orglar i Domkyrkan|trans-title= Six organs in the cathedral|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Works cited==\n*{{cite book |last= Bodin|first= Anders|date= 2017|title= Helgo Zettervalls arkitektur: kyrkor|volume=II|trans-title= The architecture of Helgo Zettervall: churches|url= http://kth.diva-portal.org/smash/get/diva2:1094819/FULLTEXT01.pdf|language= Swedish|location= Stockholm|publisher= Carlssons bokf\u00f6rlag|isbn=9789173317856}}\n*{{cite book |last= Cinthio|first= Erik|date= 1957|title= Lunds domkyrka under romansk tid|trans-title= Lund Cathedral during the Romanesque era|url= https://portal.research.lu.se/portal/files/21557081/Diss_Erik_Cinthio.pdf|language= Swedish|location= Lund|publisher= C. W. K. Gleerup|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last= Cinthio|first= Erik|date= 1990|title= Lunds domkyrkas f\u00f6rhistoria. S:t Laurentiuspatrociniet och Knut den Heliges kyrka \u00e4n en g\u00e5ng|trans-title= The pre-history of Lund Cathedral. The patronage of St. Lawrence and the church of Canute the Holy once more|url= https://www.tidskriftenale.nu/pdfale/ALE-1990-2_v02.pdf|language= Swedish|journal= Ale. Historisk tidskrift f\u00f6r Sk\u00e5ne, Halland och Blekinge|volume= 2|issue= |pages= 1\u201313|doi= |access-date=|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last= Dun\u00e9r|first= Uno|date= 1984|title= Gideon och ullen|trans-title= Gideon and the wool|url= https://www.tidskriftenale.nu/pdfale/ALE-1984-3_v02.pdf|language= Swedish|journal= Ale. Historisk tidskrift f\u00f6r Sk\u00e5ne, Halland och Blekinge|volume= 3|issue= |pages= 1\u201310|doi= |access-date=|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last= Gertz|first= Otto|date= 1923|title= Vegetationen \u00e5 ruinerna av Alvastra klosterkyrka|trans-title= The vegetation on the ruins of Alvastra monastery church|url= |language= Swedish|journal= Botaniska notiser|volume= |issue= |pages= 457\u2013463|doi= |access-date=|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last= Johansson|first= Per|date= 1993|title= Lavfloran p\u00e5 Lunds domkyrka|trans-title= The lichen flora of Lund Cathedral|url= http://www.diva-portal.org/smash/get/diva2:1203014/FULLTEXT01.pdf|language= Swedish|journal= Svensk Botanisk Tidskrift|volume= |issue= 87|pages= 25\u201330|doi= |access-date=|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Karlsson|editor1-first=Lennart|last= Lindgren|first= Mereth|date= 1995|title=Signums svenska konsthistoria. Den romanska konsten|trans-title= Signum's history of Swedish art. Romanesque art|chapter=Stenarkitekturen|trans-chapter=The stone architecture|url= |language= Swedish|location= Lund|publisher= Signum|pages=299\u2013335|isbn=91-87896-23-0|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last= Rydbeck|first= Otto|date= 1915|title= Bidrag till Lunds domkyrkas byggnadshistoria|trans-title= Contributions to the building history of Lund Cathedral|url= http://libris.kb.se/bib/1694254|location= Lund|publisher= C. W. K. Gleerup}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last= Newman|editor1-first= Ernst|last= Rydbeck|first= Otto|date= 1946|title= Lunds domkyrkas historia 1145\u20131945|trans-title= History of Lund Cathedral 1145\u20131945|chapter= Lunds domkyrka, byggnadens och dess inventariers historia enligt de nyaste forskningsresultaten|trans-chapter= Lund Cathedral, the history of the building and its furnishings according to the latest research|url=http://libris.kb.se/bib/8073961|language= Swedish|location= Stockholm|publisher= Svenska kyrkans diakonistyrelses bokf\u00f6rlag|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last= Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|editor1-first= Claes|last= Ryd\u00e9n|first= Thomas|date= 1998|title= Metropolis Daniae: ett stycke Europa|trans-title= Metropolis Daniae: a piece of Europe|chapter= Lunds domkyrka, det universella rummet|trans-chapter= Lund Cathedral, the universal space|url= https://portal.research.lu.se/portal/files/63935286/Ryden_LundsDomkyrkaUniversellaRummet.pdf|language= Swedish|location= Stockholm|publisher= Lund University|issn=0454-5915|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last= L\u00f6fvendahl|editor1-first= Runo|editor2-last= Sundn\u00e9r|editor2-first= Barbro|last= Sundn\u00e9r|first= Barbro|date= 1997|title= Lunds domkyrka: stenmaterial och skadebild|trans-title= Lund Cathedral: stone material and damages|chapter= Byggnadshistoria|trans-chapter= Building history|url= http://www.diva-portal.org/smash/get/diva2:1289650/FULLTEXT01.pdf|language= Swedish|location= Stockholm|publisher= Riksantikvarie\u00e4mbetet ([[Swedish National Heritage Board]])|isbn=91-7209-006-5|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Karlsson|editor1-first=Lennart|last= Svanberg|first= Jan|date= 1995|title=Signums svenska konsthistoria. Den romanska konsten|trans-title= Signum's history of Swedish art. Romanesque art|chapter=Stenskulpturen|trans-chapter=The stone sculpture|url= |language= Swedish|location= Lund|publisher= Signum|pages=299\u2013335|isbn=91-87896-23-0|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Augustsson|editor1-first=Jan-Erik|last= Svanberg|first= Jan|date= 1996|title=Signums svenska konsthistoria. Den gotiska konsten|trans-title= Signum's history of Swedish art. Romanesque art|chapter=Stenskulpturen|trans-chapter=The stone sculpture|url= |language= Swedish|location= Lund|publisher= Signum|pages=299\u2013335|isbn=91-87896-23-0|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last= Wrangel|first= Ewert|date= 1923|title= Konstverk i Lunds domkyrka|trans-title= Art in Lund Cathedral|url= https://archive.org/details/konstverkilundsd00wran/mode/2up|location= Lund|publisher= C. W. K. Gleerup}}\n*{{cite book |last= Wrangel|first= Ewert|date= 1923|title= Lunds domkyrkas konsthistoria: f\u00f6rbindelser och stilfr\u00e4nder|trans-title= The art history of Lund Cathedral: connections and stylistic equals|url= http://libris.kb.se/bib/416081|location= Lund|publisher= C. W. K. Gleerup}}\n*{{cite book |last= Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|first= Claes|date= 2014|title= Sk\u00e5nes kyrkor 1050-1949|trans-title= The churches of Sk\u00e5ne 1050\u20131949|language=Swedish|url= http://libris.kb.se/bib/18066221|location= K\u00e4vlinge|publisher= Domus Propria|isbn= 978-91-637-5874-4}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |last= Brunius|first= Carl Georg|date= 1836|title= Nordens \u00e4ldsta metropolitankyrka, eller, historisk och arkitektonisk beskrifning \u00f6fver Lunds domkyrka|trans-title= The oldest metropolitan church in the Nordic countries, or, historic and architectonic description of Lund Cathedral|url= http://libris.kb.se/bib/1694639|language= Swedish|location= Lund|publisher= Berling}}\n*{{cite book |last= Gierow|first= Krister|date= 1946|title= Lunds domkyrka i litteraturen: bibliografisk f\u00f6rteckning|trans-title= Lund Cathedral in literature: a bibliography|language= Swedish|location= Lund|publisher= C. W. K. Gleerup|url=http://libris.kb.se/bib/1186054}}\n*{{cite book |last= Zettervall|first= Helgo|date= 1916|title= Helgo Zettervall om Lunds domkyrka: en byggnadsbeskrivning i brev|trans-title= Helgo Zettervall on Lund Cathedral: description of a building in letters|url= http://libris.kb.se/bib/10258926|language= Swedish|location= Lund|publisher= }}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://lundsdomkyrka.se/ Official website of the cathedral]\n* [http://www.alvin-portal.org/alvin/view.jsf?pid=alvin-record%3A14714&dswid=3243 Digitised copy of the ''Necrologium Lundense'', with information about the book and its contents in English]\n* [http://www.alvin-portal.org/alvin/view.jsf?pid=alvin-record%3A13276&dswid=7054 Digitised copy of the ''Liber daticus vetustior'', with information about the book and its contents in English]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC3LzcTh1FX5k3C8Y4EJI0Ew YouTube channel of the cathedral]\n\n{{Churches in Scania}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1145]]\n[[Category:12th-century churches]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Lund]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic cathedrals in pre-Reformation Sweden]]\n[[Category:Lutheran cathedrals in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Romanesque architecture in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Lund]]\n[[Category:Coronation church buildings]]\n[[Category:Churches in Sk\u00e5ne County]]\n[[Category:Churches in the Diocese of Lund]]\n", "name_user": "Yakikaki", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePulpit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lund_Cathedral"}
{"title_page": "Ab-Soul", "text_new": "{{short description|American hip hop recording artist from California}}\n{{Update|date=September 2019}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name            = Ab-Soul\n|background      = solo_singer\n|image           = File:Ab-Soul - These Days Tour 2014 (cropped).jpg\n|alt             =\n|caption         = Ab-Soul performing in Toronto in 2014\n|birth_name      = Herbert Anthony Stevens IV\n|birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1987|2|23}}\n|birth_place     = [[Los Angeles, California]], United States\n|origin          = [[Carson, California]], United States\n|genre           = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n|occupation      = Rapper\n|years_active    = 2002\u2013present\n|label           = {{flatlist|\n* [[Top Dawg Entertainment|Top Dawg]] {{small|(current)}}\n* StreetBeat {{small|(former)}}\n}}\n|associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[Black Hippy]]\n* [[Bas (rapper)|Bas]]\n* [[BJ the Chicago Kid]]\n* [[Danny Brown]]\n* [[Jhen\u00e9 Aiko]]\n* [[JMSN]]\n* [[Mac Miller]]\n* [[Punch (rapper)|Punch]]\n* [[SZA (singer)|SZA]]\n}}\n|website         = \n}}\n'''Herbert Anthony Stevens IV''' (born February 23, 1987),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thugradio.net/absoul-main.html |title=Ab-Soul |publisher=Thugradio.net |date= |accessdate= March 29, 2012}}</ref> better known by his [[stage name]] '''Ab-Soul''', is an American rapper from [[Carson, California]]. In 2007, he signed to indie record label [[Top Dawg Entertainment]] (TDE), where he eventually formed a West Coast hip hop [[Black Hippy]] alongside West Coast rappers [[Jay Rock]], [[Kendrick Lamar]] and [[Schoolboy Q]]. He is perhaps best known for his introspective lyrics and his four [[independent album]]s under TDE, ''[[Longterm Mentality]]'', ''[[Control System]]'', ''[[These Days... (Ab-Soul album)|These Days...]]'', and ''[[Do What Thou Wilt.]]'', which were all released to positive reviews and commercial success.\n\n==Early life==\nHerbert Anthony Stevens IV was born on February 23, 1987, in [[Los Angeles]]. Stevens spent the first four years of his life in Germany while his father was in the military, right up until his parents split and he and his mother subsequently moved back to the United States, to live in his grandmother's house in [[Carson, California]].<ref name=\"germany\">{{cite web|url=http://www.csnowheaties.com/2012/07/24/the-source-presents-ab-soul-documentary/|title=The Source Presents: Ab-Soul Documentary (Video)|date=July 24, 2012|publisher=csnowheaties.com|accessdate=September 19, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102192306/http://www.csnowheaties.com/2012/07/24/the-source-presents-ab-soul-documentary/|archive-date=January 2, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He once recalled being five years old: \"I was serious into [[video games]] and [[basketball]], at five. But video games for sure. Five\u2026 What was that, [[Nintendo]]? [[Sega]]. [[Sonic the Hedgehog (series)|Sonic the Hedgehog]]. [[Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles]] on TV. But I know early on, I really, really liked [[Michael Jackson]], like we all did. Newborn babies loved Michael Jackson.\"<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite web|author= Ramirez, Erika |title=Ab-Soul's Timeline: The Rapper's Life From 5 Years Old to Now|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/480657/ab-souls-timeline-the-rappers-life-from-5-years-old-to-now| work =[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=August 8, 2012|accessdate=December 7, 2012}}</ref> At the age of 10, Stevens contracted [[Stevens\u2013Johnson syndrome]], which caused him to be hospitalized and is the origin of his dark lips and [[Light sensitivity|light-sensitive]] eyes.<ref name=\"Billboard\"/> In his adolescent years, Stevens was severely [[Teasing|teased]] about his condition.<ref name=\"complex4\">{{cite web|author= Ahmed, Insanu|title=Who Is Ab-Soul? \u2013  His Nickname, Black Lipped Bastard|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/07/who-is-ab-soul/his-nickname-black-lipped-bastard| work =[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=July 10, 2012|accessdate=July 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\nStevens encountered music at a very young age, due to his family owning a [[record store]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/videos/id.14056/title.ab-soul-grew-up-at-the-record-store-turning-points|title=Ab-Soul|author=HipHopDX|date=August 22, 2013|work=HipHopDX|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> Stevens also began crafting his [[rapping]] skills at an early age: \"I was on [[BlackPlanet]] [[Freestyle rap|freestyle]] [[Online chat|chat]], rapping my ass off. Text [[Battle rap|battle]]. It is a very interesting world. I think that it still exists online, where you [[Freestyle rap|freestyle]] but you type it. They call it keystyle. I think that is where I developed my rhyming skills. I had been rapping a little earlier, maybe around 12 [years old], but when I hopped online and into that culture, that textcee culture. It really got me going as far as being a rapper.\"<ref name=\"Billboard\"/>\n\nStevens claims to have written his first [[Verse (popular music)|verse]] when he was 12 years old, to the [[hip hop production|beat]] of [[Twista]]'s \"[[Emotions (Twista song)|Emotions]]\".<ref name=\"complex2\">{{cite web|author=Ahmed, Insanu|title=Who Is Ab-Soul? \u2013  Learning How To Rap|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/07/who-is-ab-soul/learning-to-rap| work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=July 10, 2012|accessdate=July 11, 2012}}</ref> Rapping continued on as a [[hobby]] for Stevens, whose parents \"saw a bright, college-type future\" for him and enrolled him in advanced classes.<ref name=\"Billboard\" /> It was not until Stevens graduated from high school that he began to take his music career seriously.<ref name=\"complex2\"/>\n\n== Musical career ==\n\n=== 2002\u201310: Career beginnings and signing to TDE ===\n[[File:Ab-Soul.jpg|thumb|right|Ab-Soul in 2011.]]\nIn 2002, Stevens recorded his first song. In 2005, he signed a [[recording contract]] with StreetBeat Entertainment, but just a year later, in 2006, he met [[Punch (rapper)|Punch]], [[President (corporate title)|President]] and [[Chairman]] of Carson-based [[independent record label|indie record label]], [[Top Dawg Entertainment]] (TDE), who as Stevens says, \"saw more in his music than [[metaphor]]s and [[Punch line|punchlines]]\".<ref name=\"complex3\">{{cite web|author= Ahmed, Insanu |title=Who Is Ab-Soul? \u2013  Joining TDE|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/07/who-is-ab-soul/joining-tde| work =[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=July 10, 2012|accessdate=July 11, 2012}}</ref> Before signing to TDE, Stevens was a part of a [[rap group]] called Area 51, alongside [[Brooklyn]]-native and fellow American rapper Snake Hollywood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nahright.com/news/2013/09/13/snake-hollywood-ft-ab-soul-choke/|title=Snake Hollywood ft. Ab-Soul \u2013 Choke - Nah Right|publisher=|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopfeeling.com/2013/09/13/audio-snake-hollywood-ft-ab-soul-choke/|title=hiphopfeeling.com|publisher=|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Stevens officially became part of the Top Dawg roster. Stevens cited the book ''[[The Autobiography of Malcolm X]]'' (1964) as being highly influential.<ref>Afromighty (June 29, 2012).  [http://respect-mag.com/exclusive-interview-ab-soul-appointed-genius-of-tde-is-much-more-than-meets-the-third-eye \"Ab-Soul, Appointed 'Genius' of TDE, Much More Than Meets the (Third) Eye\"].  ''[[RESPECT. (magazine)|Respect.]]''  Retrieved December 31, 2012.</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Stevens made a brief [[cameo appearance]] in the [[music video]] for his TDE-mate Jay Rock's commercial debut single, \"[[All My Life (In the Ghetto)]]\". Also in 2008, he began recording music for his debut [[mixtape]], at the TDE Recording Studio: House of Pain. In December 2008, Stevens released his first [[music video]], for a song from the mixtape, titled \"A Day in the Life\", through [[YouTube]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SKcXPeijs8k|title=Ab Soul \"Day In The LIfe\"|date=December 4, 2008|work=YouTube|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> The mixtape, entitled ''Longterm'', was released in January 2009. It was the first in a series, that Stevens claims will have four installments: \"When I did the first ''Longterm'' I knew that there would be four of them. When I did the first one. So there will be four of them: ''Longterm 1, 2, 3, and 4''. So right now we're at two. You'll have to wait for the next one. That's for the next Ab-Soul interview.\".<ref name=\"complex5\">{{cite web|author=Ahmed, Insanu|title=Who Is Ab-Soul? \u2013  The Themes of Vision and Light in His Music|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/07/who-is-ab-soul/the-themes-of-vision-and-light-in-his-music| work =[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=July 10, 2012|accessdate=July 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, he formed supergroup [[Black Hippy]], with his frequent collaborators and TDE label-mates Schoolboy Q, Jay Rock and K-Dot. Stevens released his second mixtape, and the [[sequel]] to his first, on June 28, 2010. The tape, titled ''Longterm 2: Lifestyles of the Broke and Almost Famous'' was highly acclaimed and featured Stevens [[singing]] on several songs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.djbooth.net/index/mixtapes/entry/ab-soul-longterm-2/|title=Ab-Soul - Longterm 2: Lifestyles Of The Broke & Almost Famous|work=DJBooth.net|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== 2011\u201312: ''Longterm Mentality'' and ''Control System'' ===\n{{Main|Longterm Mentality|Control System}}\nIn February 2011, Ab-Soul revealed he was working on an album titled ''[[Longterm Mentality]]'', and subsequently released \"Hell Yeah\", a track featuring Schoolboy Q.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2011/02/10/ab-soul-hell-yeah-f-schoolboy-q/ |title=Ab-Soul \u2013  Hell Yeah f. Schoolboy Q |publisher=2DopeBoyz |date= February 10, 2011 |accessdate= April 2, 2013}}</ref> On February 22, 2011 Stevens released another promotional recording taken from the album, \"Moscato\", a collaboration with another fellow Black Hippy, Kendrick Lamar.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2011/02/22/ab-soul-%E2%80%93-moscato-f-kendrick-lamar/ |title=Ab-Soul \u2013  Moscato f. Kendrick Lamar |publisher=2DopeBoyz |date= February 22, 2011 |accessdate= April 2, 2013}}</ref> In February 2011, Stevens also embarked on the \"Road to [[Paid Dues]]\" [[concert tour]], after being enlisted by fellow American rapper [[Murs (rapper)|Murs]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.13905/title.murs-launches-road-to-paid-dues-tour-with-tabi-bonney-ab-soul | title=Murs Launches Road To Paid Dues Tour With Tabi Bonney, AB-Soul | work=HipHopDX | publisher=Cheri Media Group | date=February 1, 2011 | accessdate=April 2, 2011 | author=Paine, Jake}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, 2011 Stevens released the music video for a song titled \"Nothin' New\", in promotion for the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2011/03/21/ab-soul-nothin-video/ |title=Ab-Soul \u2013  Nothin' New (video) |publisher=2DopeBoyz |date= March 21, 2011 |accessdate= April 2, 2013}}</ref> On March 25, he released \"Gone Insane\", the fourth track liberated that was taken from the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2011/03/25/ab-soul-gone-insane/ |title=Ab-Soul \u2013  Gone Insane |publisher=2DopeBoyz |date= March 25, 2011 |accessdate= April 2, 2013}}</ref> On March 30, a [[trailer (promotion)|trailer]] for ''Longterm Mentality'', was released via Top Dawg Entertainment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2011/03/30/ab-soul-longterm-mentality-trailer/ |title=Ab-Soul \u2013  LongTerm: Mentality (Trailer) |publisher=2DopeBoyz |date= March 30, 2011 |accessdate= April 2, 2013}}</ref> On April 1, 2011 he released the music video for \"Gone Insane\", directed by Top Dawg in-house directors Fredo Tovar and Scott Fleishman.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2011/04/01/ab-soul-%E2%80%93-gone-insane-video/ |title=Ab-Soul \u2013  Gone Insane (video) |publisher=2DopeBoyz |date= April 1, 2011 |accessdate= April 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\nStevens has stated the respective [[independent album]]s of his label-mates partly inspired material on ''Longterm Mentality'': \"I compare [the process behind] ''Longterm Mentality'' to the process with all of my joints. Kendrick's ''[[Overly Dedicated|OD]]'' had came out and Q's ''[[Setbacks (album)|Setbacks]]'' had came out. I had these bodies of work to go off of as references, as inspiration. I hear what Kendrick is talking about, I hear what Q is talking about, I heard what Jay Rock was talking about. So how am I going to piece this all together and add my own two cents, too? How do I continue the sound but have my individuality as an artist? It's the same challenge every single time.\"<ref name=\"complex6\">{{cite web|author= Ahmed, Insanu|title=Who Is Ab-Soul? \u2013  His Longterm Mentality Series|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/07/who-is-ab-soul/his-long-term-mentality-series| work =[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=July 10, 2012|accessdate=July 11, 2012}}</ref> Stevens released his first [[independent album]], under Top Dawg Entertainment, exclusively through [[iTunes]] on April 5, 2011. The album subsequently peaked at #73 on the US [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/longterm-mentality-mw0002238997/awards | title=''Longterm Mentality'' \u2013 AB-Soul > Awards | publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]] | work=[[AllMusic]] | accessdate=April 2, 2013}}</ref> The album, although its title is ''Longterm Mentality'', is not the third part of his ''Longterm'' series.<ref name=\"complex5\"/>\n\n[[File:SchoolboyQxAbSoul.jpg|thumb|left|Black Hippy members Ab-Soul (left) and [[Schoolboy Q]] in April 2012.]]\nSoon after the release of Schoolboy Q's second independent album, ''[[Habits & Contradictions]]'' (2012), Stevens began promoting his second independent album, releasing a song titled \"Black Lip Bastard\", on January 17, 2012. The song was produced by TDE in-house producer [[Willie B (producer)|Willie B]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2012/01/17/ab-soul-black-lip-bastard-prod-willie-b-of-digi-phonics/ |title=Ab-Soul \u2013  Black Lip Bastard (prod. Willie B of Digi+Phonics) |publisher=2DopeBoyz |date= January 17, 2012 |accessdate= May 27, 2012}}</ref> On February 28, 2012, Ab-Soul, alongside Schoolboy Q, appeared on [[Sway Calloway]]'s #SwayInTheMorning [[radio show]], where Ab-Soul called \"Black Lip Bastard\": \"pretty much one of the [[:wikt:title track|title tracks]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2012/02/28/schoolboy-q-ab-soul-5-fingers-of-death-freestyle-video/ |title=ScHoolboy Q & Ab-Soul \u2013  5 Fingers Of Death Freestyle (Video) |publisher=2DopeBoyz |date= February 28, 2012 |accessdate= May 27, 2012}}</ref> The first song that appears on the album, to be released was \"Showin' Love\", also produced by Willie B.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2012/03/02/ab-soul-showin-love-prod-willie-b-of-digiphonics/ |title=Ab-Soul \u2013  Showin' Love (prod. Willie B of Digi+Phonics) |publisher=2DopeBoyz |date= March 2, 2012 |accessdate= May 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, Schoolboy Q announced #TheGroovyTour; a month-long tour with Ab-Soul accompanying him the entire way. The tour began on April 20, at the [[Bill Graham Civic Auditorium]] in [[San Francisco]], California.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2012/03/24/schoolboy-q-announces-the-groovy-tour-w-ab-soul/ |title=ScHoolboy Q Announces The Groovy Tour w/ Ab-Soul |publisher=2DopeBoyz |date= March 24, 2012|accessdate= March 25, 2012}}</ref> On April 6, 2012, Ab-Soul liberated a song titled \"Terrorist Threats\". The song features frequent collaborator [[Jhen\u00e9 Aiko]] and fellow American rapper [[Danny Brown (rapper)|Danny Brown]], who proclaimed on [[Twitter]] that \"Black Hippy the new [[The Beatles|Beatles]] and I'm [[Harry Nilsson]]\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Fitzmaurice|first=Larry|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/13419-terrorist-threats-ft-danny-brown-and-jhene-aiko/|title=Ab-Soul: \"Terrorist Threats\" [ft. Danny Brown and Jhene Aiko] |publisher=[[Pitchfork Media]]|date= April 9, 2012|accessdate= May 27, 2012}}</ref> On April 17, 2012, Ab-Soul revealed the album's title to be ''[[Control System]]'' and unveiled the release date to be May 11, 2012. That same day, he also released a [[music video]] for \"Pineal Gland\", a song inspired by the [[psychedelic drug]] [[Dimethyltryptamine|DMT]] and of course the [[pineal gland]], a small [[endocrine system|endocrine]] gland in the [[vertebrate]] [[brain]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.djbooth.net/index/tracks/review/ab-soul-pineal-gland/ |title=Ab-Soul \u2013  Pineal Gland Music Video |publisher=DJBooth.net |date= April 17, 2012 |accessdate= May 27, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scoremoreshows.com/2012/04/ab-soul-%E2%80%93-pineal-gland-video/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130202003709/http://www.scoremoreshows.com/2012/04/ab-soul-%E2%80%93-pineal-gland-video/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 2, 2013 |title=Ab-Soul \u2013  Pineal Gland [video] |publisher=Scoremore |date=April 19, 2012 |accessdate=May 27, 2012 }}</ref> On April 24, 2012, Stevens released another song, \"SOPA\". The song, produced by Nez & Rio, references the [[Stop Online Piracy Act]] (SOPA), a United States [[Bill (proposed law)|bill]] introduced by [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] [[Lamar S. Smith]], that would have allowed the [[Federal government of the United States|U.S. government]] to control the [[Internet]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2012/04/24/ab-soul-sopa-f-schoolboy-q-prod-nez-rio/ |title=Ab-Soul \u2013  SOPA f. ScHoolboy Q (prod. Nez & Rio) |publisher=2DopeBoyz |date= April 24, 2012 |accessdate= May 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn May 1, 2012, Ab-Soul released another music video, for a new song titled \"Empathy\", the song features vocals from Stevens' late longtime [[girlfriend]] [[Alori Joh]] (December 16, 1986 - February 6, 2012), who had committed [[suicide]] earlier in February.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beatsandrants.com/2012/05/new-video-ab-soul-empathy-featuring-alori-joh-and-javonte.html |title=New Video: Ab-Soul \u2013  \"Empathy\" (Featuring Alori Joh and jaVont\u00e9) |publisher=beatsandrants.com |date= May 1, 2012 |accessdate= May 27, 2012}}</ref> Joh's death had a huge impact on Stevens and the recording process of ''Control System''.<ref name=\"alorijoh\">{{cite web|author=Alexis, Nadeska |title=Ab-Soul Had To Address Alori Joh's Death On 'The Book Of Soul'|url=http://rapfix.mtv.com/2013/02/25/ab-soul-had-to-address-alori-johs-death-on-the-book-of-soul/|publisher=[[MTV]]|date=February 25, 2013|accessdate=April 4, 2013}}</ref> On May 4, 2012, it was revealed \"Black Lip Bastard\" was [[remix]]ed and would feature his Black Hippy cohorts, Rock, Lamar and Schoolboy Q.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2012/05/04/ab-soul-black-lip-bastard-black-hippy-remix-preview/ |title=Ab-Soul \u2013  Black Lip Bastard (Black Hippy Remix) (Preview) |publisher=2DopeBoyz |date= May 4, 2012 |accessdate= May 27, 2012}}</ref> On May 8, 2012, his collaboration with Lamar, titled \"ILLuminate\", was released. The day before the album's release Ab-Soul revealed the track listing and released [[wikt:snippet|snippets]] from the album. The album, as written on the back cover, is \"Dedicated to the beautiful soul of Loriana Angel Johnson aka Alori Joh\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2012/05/10/ab-soul-controlsystem-artwork-x-tracklist-x-snippets/ |title=Ab-Soul \u2013 Control System (Tracklist x Snippets) |publisher=2DopeBoyz |date= May 10, 2012 |accessdate= May 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\n''Control System'' was released exclusively through iTunes on May 11, 2012, under Top Dawg Entertainment. The album sold approximately 5,300 units in an abbreviated week, debuting at number 83 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and appearing on several other [[Billboard charts|''Billboard'' charts]] as well.<ref>{{cite web | author= Jacobs, Allen | url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.19759/title.hip-hop-album-sales-the-week-ending-5-13-2012 | title=Hip Hop Album Sales: The Week Ending 5/13/2012 | publisher= [[HipHopDX]] | date=May 16, 2012 | accessdate=December 7, 2012}}</ref> The album sold an estimated 3,700 the next week.<ref>{{cite web | author=Jacobs, Allen | url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.19849/title.hip-hop-album-sales-the-week-ending-5-20-2012 | title=Hip Hop Album Sales: The Week Ending 5/20/2012 | publisher=[[HipHopDX]] | date=May 23, 2012 | accessdate=December 7, 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141105065517/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.19849/title.hip-hop-album-sales-the-week-ending-5-20-2012 | archive-date=November 5, 2014 | url-status=dead }}</ref> During 2012, Stevens toured with the rest of Black Hippy and fellow American rapper [[Stalley]], on [[Black Entertainment Television|BET]]'s Music Matters Tour.<ref>{{cite web | author=Daniel Isenberg | url=http://complex.com/music/2012/09/photo-recap-kendrick-lamar-schoolboy-q-ab-soul-and-stalley-rock-bets-music-matters-tour-in-dc/ | title=Photo Recap: Kendrick Lamar, ScHoolboy Q, Ab-Soul, and Stalley Rock BET's Music Matters Tour in D.C. | publisher= [[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] | date=September 16, 2012 | accessdate=January 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2012, Stevens was featured on [[Joe Budden]]'s mixtape ''A Loose Quarter'' on the track \"Cut From a Different Cloth\". The song received praise as one of the best songs on the project. Budden has since announced that he and Ab-Soul have recorded many songs together which will be seeing the light of day in the near future. Budden went on to praise Ab-Soul as \"one of the best things going in hip hop right now\".<ref>Harling, Danielle (November 30, 2012).  [http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.22058/title.joe-budden-talks-ab-soul-collaboration-touring-without-slaughterhouse \"Joe Budden Talks Ab-Soul Collaboration, Touring Without Slaughterhouse\"].  [[HipHopDX]].  Retrieved December 31, 2012.</ref>\n\n===2012-18: ''These Days\u2026'' and ''Do What Thou Wilt.''===\n{{main|These Days... (Ab-Soul album)|Do What Thou Wilt.}}\n[[File:Ab-Soul - The Smokers Club Tour 2013 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|Ab-Soul performing in [[Toronto]] in 2013.]]\nIn October 2012, American singer-songwriter and record producer [[JMSN]], who previously produced \"Nibiru\" for Stevens earlier in August, for what his label called \"TDE Fan Appreciation Week\", announced he and Stevens would be releasing a collaborative project together.<ref>{{cite web | author= | url=http://www.soulculture.co.uk/music-blog/ab-soul-and-jmsn-working-on-collaborative-ep-music-news/ | title=Ab-Soul and JMSN Working on Collaborative EP | publisher=SoulCulture | work=Music News | date=October 22, 2012 | accessdate=December 12, 2012}}</ref> The [[lead single]] for their collaborative album, which was set to be titled ''Unit 6'', was officially released via iTunes on January 22, 2013.<ref>{{cite web | title=\"You're Gone\" - Single by Ab-Soul & JMSN | url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/youre-gone-single/id593168039 | work=[[iTunes Store]] | publisher=[[Apple Inc.|Apple]] | accessdate=January 22, 2013}}</ref> The single, titled \"You're Gone\", features vocals from both artists, as well as production from JMSN.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2013/01/21/ab-soul-jmsn-youre-gone/ |title=Ab-Soul \u2013  & JMSN - \"You're Gone\" |publisher=2DopeBoyz |date= January 21, 2013 |accessdate= January 21, 2013}}</ref> On March 26, 2013, it was announced that Ab-Soul would be featured on ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]''{{'}}s 2013 Freshman Class issue, alongside Schoolboy Q and other up-and-coming rappers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2013/03/xxl-freshman-class-2013-cover-revealed/2/|title=XXL Freshman Class 2013 Cover Revealed|work=XXL|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn August 6, 2013, after a near four-month hiatus, Stevens released a new song produced by Willie B, titled \"Christopher DRONEr\", alluding to former [[LAPD]] police officer [[Christopher Dorner]]. Along with the song, he announced he was working on a new solo project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/08/ab-soul-christopher-droner|title=Listen: Ab-Soul \"Christopher DRONEr\"|author=Lauren Nostro|work=Complex|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> The following day he would speak to ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]'' and say that he and JMSN had finished the ''Unit 6'' album, however their management could not \"see eye to eye\", so the project was ultimately shelved for a possible later release, with Stevens saying: \"As of right now it\u2019s sounding like prequel to my album.\" He went on to confirm that JMSN and Jhene Aiko, will appear on the upcoming solo project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2013/08/ab-soul-speaks-on-new-single-and-upcoming-project-with-jmsn/|title=Ab-Soul Speaks On New Single And Upcoming Project With JMSN - XXL|publisher=}}</ref> On October 17, 2013, Stevens stated that he was close to finalizing the project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2013/10/ab-soul-putting-final-touches-next-project/|title=Ab-Soul Is Putting The Final Touches On His Next Project  - XXL|publisher=}}</ref> Then later that week, he confirmed that the project had been turned in for [[mixing (mathematics)|mixing]] and cleared up rumors that it was titled ''Black Lip Pastor''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/ab-soul-talks-on-upcoming-project-and-confusion-surrounding-title-isaiah-rashad-and-unit-6-news.7792.html|title=Ab-Soul Talks On Upcoming Project & Confusion Surrounding Title, Isaiah Rashad & \"Unit 6\"|author=Rose Lilah|work=HotNewHipHop|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.25844/title.ab-soul-finalizing-new-album-title-unknown|title=Ab-Soul Finalizing New Album, Title Unknown|author=HipHopDX|date=October 19, 2013|work=HipHopDX|accessdate=March 9, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141011130333/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.25844/title.ab-soul-finalizing-new-album-title-unknown|archive-date=October 11, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> With the release of the [[56th Annual Grammy Awards]] nominations, it was revealed Stevens was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] for his participation on [[Macklemore]] [[Macklemore & Ryan Lewis|&]] [[Ryan Lewis]]' debut album, ''[[The Heist (album)|The Heist]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.com/nominees |title=GRAMMY.com - The Official Site of Music's Biggest Night |work=The GRAMMYs |accessdate=March 9, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503164723/http://www.grammy.com/nominees |archivedate=May 3, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nOn January 2, 2014, Stevens revealed he had turned in two projects to his label Top Dawg, before the year 2013, was over: \"I turned in 2 projects last year, yea I know what your thinking, let's see where this year takes me\u2026\" he [[Twitter|tweeted]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.26870/title.ab-soul-says-he-turned-in-two-projects-in-2013 |title=Ab-Soul \u2013  Says He Turned In Two Projects In 2013 |publisher=Cheri Media Group |work=[[HipHopDX]] |date= January 3, 2014 |accessdate= January 4, 2014 |author=Baker, Soren}}</ref> On January 6, 2014, in an interview with Bootleg Kev, when speaking on the album Stevens stated: \"Ali is [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixing]] it right now,\" and that they were waiting on the perfect way to present the project, as a result of creative releases such as [[Nipsey Hussle]]'s ''[[Crenshaw (mixtape)|Crenshaw]]''.<ref name=\"bootlegkev\">{{cite web|url=http://bootlegkev.com/v2/2014/01/ab-soul-interview-w-bootleg-kev-exclusive/|title=Ab-Soul Interview w/ Bootleg Kev (Exclusive)|publisher=|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> He also revealed the album is about progression and confirmed there would be appearances from his TDE label-mates, as well as production from hip hop producer [[Statik Selektah]].<ref name=\"bootlegkev\"/> On April 11, 2014, Stevens announced he was also working on the third installment in the ''Longterm'' series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1725968/ab-soul-mixtape-longterm-3.jhtml|title=Ab-Soul Hints At New Mixtape In Longterm Series|work=MTV News|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rapdose.com/2014/04/11/ab-soul-announces-longterm-3-mixtape|title=Ab-Soul Announces \"Longterm 3\" Mixtape - Rap Dose|work=Rap Dose|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hypetrak.com/2014/04/ab-soul-announces-that-hes-working-on-longterm-3/|title=Ab-Soul Is Working On New Album|work=HYPETRAK|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref>\n[[File:Ab-Soul - AfroPunk Festival 2015.jpg|thumb|right|180px|Ab-Soul performing in Brooklyn in 2015.]]\nOn May 5, 2014, Stevens took to [[Twitter]] to announce his third album would be titled ''[[These Days... (Ab-Soul album)|These Days\u2026]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2014/05/ab-soul-reveal-album-title-via-twitter/|title=Ab-Soul's Album Title Is 'These Days...' - XXL|work=XXL|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> On May 30, 2014, Top Dawg management took to Twitter to reveal ''These Days...'', is scheduled for a June 24 release date. That same day, TDE management also unveiled the cover art for the album and released a snippet of a music video for Stevens' song \"Stigmata\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musictimes.com/articles/6480/20140531/ab-soul-releases-these-days%E2%80%A6-album-art-release-date-and-stigmata-teaser-video.htm|title=Ab-Soul Releases 'These Days\u2026' Album Art, Release Date And 'Stigmata' Teaser Video|work=Music Times|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2014/05/watch-ab-souls-video-for-stigmata|title=Watch Ab-Soul's Video for \"Stigmata\"|author=Zach Frydenlund|work=Complex|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> On June 21, 2014, Stevens released a music video for a song titled \"Closure\", taken from ''These Days...''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2014/06/21/video-ab-soul-closure/|title=Video: Ab-Soul \u2013 \u2018Closure\u2019|work=Rap-Up|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> The album debuted at number 11 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart, with first-week sales of 21,812 copies in the United States and has received generally positive reviews from [[music critics]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Tardio |first=Andres |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.29560/title.hip-hop-album-sales-week-ending-06-29-2014 |title=Hip Hop Album Sales: Week Ending 06/29/2014 |publisher=HipHop DX |date=2014-07-02 |accessdate=2014-07-02}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, in an interview with Montreality, Stevens revealed the title for his first in-store retail project would be ''Longterm 3''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/ab-soul-reveals-longterm-3-will-be-his-debut-album-new-video.31297.html|title=Ab-Soul Reveals \"Longterm 3\" Will Be His Debut Album|author=Trevor Smith|work=HotNewHipHop|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> In February 2015, Ab-Soul premiered the song \"47 Bars\" online, produced by [[The Alchemist (musician)|The Alchemist]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://2dopeboyz.com/2015/02/28/ab-soul-47-bars-alchemist/ |title=Ab-Soul - 47 Bars (prod. Alchemist) |publisher=2dopeboyz.com |date=February 28, 2015 |accessdate=March 2, 2015}}</ref> In July 2015, Stevens tweeted that his next album was \"almost done.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/abdashsoul/status/620942207478992898|title=Ab-Soul on Twitter|publisher=}}</ref> In July 2015, Stevens gave an update on the album: \"My album's almost done...\" he wrote on Twitter, adding, \"It's a love story\". He completed the post with the [[hashtag]] \"DWTW\", presumably the album title acronym to which he kept alluding.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/ab-souls-album-is-almost-done-news.16477.html|title=Ab-Soul's Album Is \"Almost Done\"|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn June 8, 2016, via Twitter, Stevens revealed he had completed his upcoming album and turned it in for [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/ab-soul-announces-album-tracclist-turned-in-news.22103.html|title=Ab-Soul Announces Album \"Tracclist Turned In\"|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2016/06/ab-soul-new-album-finished|title=Ab-Soul Confirms His New Album Is Finished and On the Way (UPDATE)|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/anthony-top-dawg-tiffith-blames-ab-soul-for-delaying-his-own-album-news.25408.html? |title=Ab Soul's next album is called DWTW |last=Walker |first=Angus |access-date=12 November 2016}}</ref> The album, titled ''[[Do What Thou Wilt.]]'', was released December 9, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/ab-soul-dwtw-do-what-thou-wilt-album-stream-new-mixtape.116692.html|title=Ab-Soul - DWTW (Do What Thou Wilt) [Album Stream]|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===2019-present: Upcoming Fifth Album===\n\nOn November 3, 2019, Stevens performed his set at the Day N Vegas music festival and promised fans a 2020 release date for his new album. On April 20, 2020, to commemorate Top Dawg Entertainment founder Anthony Tiffith's birthday, Stevens released the single ''Dangerookipawaa Freestyle''.\n\n== Artistry ==\n\n=== Influences ===\nAb-Soul cites fellow American rappers [[Twista]], [[Canibus]], [[Eminem]], [[Nas]] and [[Lupe Fiasco]] as major influences, with [[Jay Z]] being his biggest influence.<ref name=\"influences\">{{cite web | author=Baker, Soren | url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.24280/title.ab-soul-cites-jay-z-as-his-biggest-influence | title=Ab-Soul Cites Jay-Z As His Biggest Influence | publisher=Cheri Media Group | work=HipHopDX | date=June 11, 2013 | accessdate=June 11, 2013}}</ref> He stated: \"There are so many others, but those are the ones that came to my mind at this time. Those artists are basically the template to my format as an [[MC]]. They all capture me with their music, whether it be the vibe, delivery, [[Cadence (music)|cadence]], [[Storytelling|story]], or just the [[lyrics]] in general.\"<ref name=\"influences\"/>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|Ab-Soul discography|Black Hippy discography}}\n\n*''[[Longterm Mentality]]'' (2011)\n*''[[Control System]]'' (2012)\n*''[[These Days... (album)|These Days\u2026]]'' (2014)\n*''[[Do What Thou Wilt.]]'' (2016)\n*''Untitled Album'' (2020)\n\n==Concert tours==\n*These Days Tour (2014)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/ab-soul-announces-these-days-tour-news.11743.html?image=1|title=Ab-Soul Announces \"These Days\" Tour|publisher=}}</ref>\n*YMF Tour (2017)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/ab-soul-announces-ymf-tour-with-little-simz-news.29844.html|title=Ab-Soul Announces \"YMF\" Tour With Little Simz|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of hip hop musicians|List of hip-hop musicians]]\n* [[List of people from California]]\n* [[Music of California]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n<!-- Per [[WP:ELMINOFFICIAL]], choose one official website only -->\n{{commons category|Ab-Soul}}\n* {{twitter}}\n* {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=mn0002043281|label=Ab-Soul}}\n\n{{Ab-Soul}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:People from Carson, California]]\n[[Category:Rappers from California]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from California]]\n[[Category:West Coast hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:African-American male rappers]]\n[[Category:American male rappers]]\n[[Category:Hip hop activists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Top Dawg Entertainment artists]]\n[[Category:American hip hop singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:Singers from California]]\n[[Category:African-American male singers]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:African-American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American hip hop recording artist from California}}\n{{Update|date=September 2019}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name            = Ab-Soul\n|background      = solo_singer\n|image           = File:Ab-Soul - These Days Tour 2014 (cropped).jpg\n|alt             =\n|caption         = Ab-Soul performing in Toronto in 2014\n|birth_name      = Herbert Anthony Stevens IV\n|birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1987|2|23}}\n|birth_place     = [[Los Angeles, California]], United States\n|origin          = [[Carson, California]], United States\n|genre           = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n|occupation      = Rapper\n|years_active    = 2002\u2013present\n|label           = {{flatlist|\n* [[Top Dawg Entertainment|Top Dawg]] {{small|(current)}}\n* StreetBeat {{small|(former)}}\n}}\n|associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[Black Hippy]]\n* [[Bas (rapper)|Bas]]\n* [[BJ the Chicago Kid]]\n* [[Danny Brown]]\n* [[Jhen\u00e9 Aiko]]\n* [[JMSN]]\n* [[Mac Miller]]\n* [[Punch (rapper)|Punch]]\n* [[SZA (singer)|SZA]]\n}}\n|website         = \n}}\n'''Herbert Anthony Stevens IV''' (born February 23, 1987),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thugradio.net/absoul-main.html |title=Ab-Soul |publisher=Thugradio.net |date= |accessdate= March 29, 2012}}</ref> better known by his [[stage name]] '''Ab-Soul''', is an American rapper from [[Carson, California]]. In 2007, he signed to indie record label [[Top Dawg Entertainment]] (TDE), where he eventually formed a West Coast hip hop [[Black Hippy]] alongside West Coast rappers [[Jay Rock]], [[Kendrick Lamar]] and [[Schoolboy Q]]. He is perhaps best known for his introspective lyrics and his four [[independent album]]s under TDE, ''[[Longterm Mentality]]'', ''[[Control System]]'', ''[[These Days... (Ab-Soul album)|These Days...]]'', and ''[[Do What Thou Wilt.]]'', which were all released to positive reviews and commercial success.\n\n==Early life==\nHerbert Anthony Stevens IV was born on February 23, 1987, in [[Los Angeles]]. Stevens spent the first four years of his life in Germany while his father was in the military, right up until his parents split and he and his mother subsequently moved back to the United States, to live in his grandmother's house in [[Carson, California]].<ref name=\"germany\">{{cite web|url=http://www.csnowheaties.com/2012/07/24/the-source-presents-ab-soul-documentary/|title=The Source Presents: Ab-Soul Documentary (Video)|date=July 24, 2012|publisher=csnowheaties.com|accessdate=September 19, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102192306/http://www.csnowheaties.com/2012/07/24/the-source-presents-ab-soul-documentary/|archive-date=January 2, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He once recalled being five years old: \"I was serious into [[video games]] and [[basketball]], at five. But video games for sure. Five\u2026 What was that, [[Nintendo]]? [[Sega]]. [[Sonic the Hedgehog (series)|Sonic the Hedgehog]]. [[Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles]] on TV. But I know early on, I really, really liked [[Michael Jackson]], like we all did. Newborn babies loved Michael Jackson.\"<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite web|author= Ramirez, Erika |title=Ab-Soul's Timeline: The Rapper's Life From 5 Years Old to Now|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/480657/ab-souls-timeline-the-rappers-life-from-5-years-old-to-now| work =[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=August 8, 2012|accessdate=December 7, 2012}}</ref> At the age of 10, Stevens contracted [[Stevens\u2013Johnson syndrome]], which caused him to be hospitalized and is the origin of his dark lips and [[Light sensitivity|light-sensitive]] eyes.<ref name=\"Billboard\"/> In his adolescent years, Stevens was severely [[Teasing|teased]] about his condition.<ref name=\"complex4\">{{cite web|author= Ahmed, Insanu|title=Who Is Ab-Soul? \u2013  His Nickname, Black Lipped Bastard|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/07/who-is-ab-soul/his-nickname-black-lipped-bastard| work =[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=July 10, 2012|accessdate=July 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\nStevens encountered music at a very young age, due to his family owning a [[record store]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/videos/id.14056/title.ab-soul-grew-up-at-the-record-store-turning-points|title=Ab-Soul|author=HipHopDX|date=August 22, 2013|work=HipHopDX|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> Stevens also began crafting his [[rapping]] skills at an early age: \"I was on [[BlackPlanet]] [[Freestyle rap|freestyle]] [[Online chat|chat]], rapping my ass off. Text [[Battle rap|battle]]. It is a very interesting world. I think that it still exists online, where you [[Freestyle rap|freestyle]] but you type it. They call it keystyle. I think that is where I developed my rhyming skills. I had been rapping a little earlier, maybe around 12 [years old], but when I hopped online and into that culture, that textcee culture. It really got me going as far as being a rapper.\"<ref name=\"Billboard\"/>\n\nStevens claims to have written his first [[Verse (popular music)|verse]] when he was 12 years old, to the [[hip hop production|beat]] of [[Twista]]'s \"[[Emotions (Twista song)|Emotions]]\".<ref name=\"complex2\">{{cite web|author=Ahmed, Insanu|title=Who Is Ab-Soul? \u2013  Learning How To Rap|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/07/who-is-ab-soul/learning-to-rap| work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=July 10, 2012|accessdate=July 11, 2012}}</ref> Rapping continued on as a [[hobby]] for Stevens, whose parents \"saw a bright, college-type future\" for him and enrolled him in advanced classes.<ref name=\"Billboard\" /> It was not until Stevens graduated from high school that he began to take his music career seriously.<ref name=\"complex2\"/>\n\n== Musical career ==\n\n=== 2002\u201310: Career beginnings and signing to TDE ===\n[[File:Ab-Soul.jpg|thumb|right|Ab-Soul in 2011.]]\nIn 2002, Stevens recorded his first song. In 2005, he signed a [[recording contract]] with StreetBeat Entertainment, but just a year later, in 2006, he met [[Punch (rapper)|Punch]], [[President (corporate title)|President]] and [[Chairman]] of Carson-based [[independent record label|indie record label]], [[Top Dawg Entertainment]] (TDE), who as Stevens says, \"saw more in his music than [[metaphor]]s and [[Punch line|punchlines]]\".<ref name=\"complex3\">{{cite web|author= Ahmed, Insanu |title=Who Is Ab-Soul? \u2013  Joining TDE|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/07/who-is-ab-soul/joining-tde| work =[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=July 10, 2012|accessdate=July 11, 2012}}</ref> Before signing to TDE, Stevens was a part of a [[rap group]] called Area 51, alongside [[Brooklyn]]-native and fellow American rapper Snake Hollywood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nahright.com/news/2013/09/13/snake-hollywood-ft-ab-soul-choke/|title=Snake Hollywood ft. Ab-Soul \u2013 Choke - Nah Right|publisher=|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopfeeling.com/2013/09/13/audio-snake-hollywood-ft-ab-soul-choke/|title=hiphopfeeling.com|publisher=|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Stevens officially became part of the Top Dawg roster. Stevens cited the book ''[[The Autobiography of Malcolm X]]'' (1964) as being highly influential.<ref>Afromighty (June 29, 2012).  [http://respect-mag.com/exclusive-interview-ab-soul-appointed-genius-of-tde-is-much-more-than-meets-the-third-eye \"Ab-Soul, Appointed 'Genius' of TDE, Much More Than Meets the (Third) Eye\"].  ''[[RESPECT. (magazine)|Respect.]]''  Retrieved December 31, 2012.</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Stevens made a brief [[cameo appearance]] in the [[music video]] for his TDE-mate Jay Rock's commercial debut single, \"[[All My Life (In the Ghetto)]]\". Also in 2008, he began recording music for his debut [[mixtape]], at the TDE Recording Studio: House of Pain. In December 2008, Stevens released his first [[music video]], for a song from the mixtape, titled \"A Day in the Life\", through [[YouTube]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SKcXPeijs8k|title=Ab Soul \"Day In The LIfe\"|date=December 4, 2008|work=YouTube|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> The mixtape, entitled ''Longterm'', was released in January 2009. It was the first in a series, that Stevens claims will have four installments: \"When I did the first ''Longterm'' I knew that there would be four of them. When I did the first one. So there will be four of them: ''Longterm 1, 2, 3, and 4''. So right now we're at two. You'll have to wait for the next one. That's for the next Ab-Soul interview.\".<ref name=\"complex5\">{{cite web|author=Ahmed, Insanu|title=Who Is Ab-Soul? \u2013  The Themes of Vision and Light in His Music|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/07/who-is-ab-soul/the-themes-of-vision-and-light-in-his-music| work =[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=July 10, 2012|accessdate=July 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, he formed supergroup [[Black Hippy]], with his frequent collaborators and TDE label-mates Schoolboy Q, Jay Rock and K-Dot. Stevens released his second mixtape, and the [[sequel]] to his first, on June 28, 2010. The tape, titled ''Longterm 2: Lifestyles of the Broke and Almost Famous'' was highly acclaimed and featured Stevens [[singing]] on several songs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.djbooth.net/index/mixtapes/entry/ab-soul-longterm-2/|title=Ab-Soul - Longterm 2: Lifestyles Of The Broke & Almost Famous|work=DJBooth.net|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== 2011\u201312: ''Longterm Mentality'' and ''Control System'' ===\n{{Main|Longterm Mentality|Control System}}\nIn February 2011, Ab-Soul revealed he was working on an album titled ''[[Longterm Mentality]]'', and subsequently released \"Hell Yeah\", a track featuring Schoolboy Q.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2011/02/10/ab-soul-hell-yeah-f-schoolboy-q/ |title=Ab-Soul \u2013  Hell Yeah f. Schoolboy Q |publisher=2DopeBoyz |date= February 10, 2011 |accessdate= April 2, 2013}}</ref> On February 22, 2011 Stevens released another promotional recording taken from the album, \"Moscato\", a collaboration with another fellow Black Hippy, Kendrick Lamar.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2011/02/22/ab-soul-%E2%80%93-moscato-f-kendrick-lamar/ |title=Ab-Soul \u2013  Moscato f. Kendrick Lamar |publisher=2DopeBoyz |date= February 22, 2011 |accessdate= April 2, 2013}}</ref> In February 2011, Stevens also embarked on the \"Road to [[Paid Dues]]\" [[concert tour]], after being enlisted by fellow American rapper [[Murs (rapper)|Murs]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.13905/title.murs-launches-road-to-paid-dues-tour-with-tabi-bonney-ab-soul | title=Murs Launches Road To Paid Dues Tour With Tabi Bonney, AB-Soul | work=HipHopDX | publisher=Cheri Media Group | date=February 1, 2011 | accessdate=April 2, 2011 | author=Paine, Jake}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, 2011 Stevens released the music video for a song titled \"Nothin' New\", in promotion for the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2011/03/21/ab-soul-nothin-video/ |title=Ab-Soul \u2013  Nothin' New (video) |publisher=2DopeBoyz |date= March 21, 2011 |accessdate= April 2, 2013}}</ref> On March 25, he released \"Gone Insane\", the fourth track liberated that was taken from the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2011/03/25/ab-soul-gone-insane/ |title=Ab-Soul \u2013  Gone Insane |publisher=2DopeBoyz |date= March 25, 2011 |accessdate= April 2, 2013}}</ref> On March 30, a [[trailer (promotion)|trailer]] for ''Longterm Mentality'', was released via Top Dawg Entertainment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2011/03/30/ab-soul-longterm-mentality-trailer/ |title=Ab-Soul \u2013  LongTerm: Mentality (Trailer) |publisher=2DopeBoyz |date= March 30, 2011 |accessdate= April 2, 2013}}</ref> On April 1, 2011 he released the music video for \"Gone Insane\", directed by Top Dawg in-house directors Fredo Tovar and Scott Fleishman.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2011/04/01/ab-soul-%E2%80%93-gone-insane-video/ |title=Ab-Soul \u2013  Gone Insane (video) |publisher=2DopeBoyz |date= April 1, 2011 |accessdate= April 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\nStevens has stated the respective [[independent album]]s of his label-mates partly inspired material on ''Longterm Mentality'': \"I compare [the process behind] ''Longterm Mentality'' to the process with all of my joints. Kendrick's ''[[Overly Dedicated|OD]]'' had came out and Q's ''[[Setbacks (album)|Setbacks]]'' had came out. I had these bodies of work to go off of as references, as inspiration. I hear what Kendrick is talking about, I hear what Q is talking about, I heard what Jay Rock was talking about. So how am I going to piece this all together and add my own two cents, too? How do I continue the sound but have my individuality as an artist? It's the same challenge every single time.\"<ref name=\"complex6\">{{cite web|author= Ahmed, Insanu|title=Who Is Ab-Soul? \u2013  His Longterm Mentality Series|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/07/who-is-ab-soul/his-long-term-mentality-series| work =[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=July 10, 2012|accessdate=July 11, 2012}}</ref> Stevens released his first [[independent album]], under Top Dawg Entertainment, exclusively through [[iTunes]] on April 5, 2011. The album subsequently peaked at #73 on the US [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/longterm-mentality-mw0002238997/awards | title=''Longterm Mentality'' \u2013 AB-Soul > Awards | publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]] | work=[[AllMusic]] | accessdate=April 2, 2013}}</ref> The album, although its title is ''Longterm Mentality'', is not the third part of his ''Longterm'' series.<ref name=\"complex5\"/>\n\n[[File:SchoolboyQxAbSoul.jpg|thumb|left|Black Hippy members Ab-Soul (left) and [[Schoolboy Q]] in April 2012.]]\nSoon after the release of Schoolboy Q's second independent album, ''[[Habits & Contradictions]]'' (2012), Stevens began promoting his second independent album, releasing a song titled \"Black Lip Bastard\", on January 17, 2012. The song was produced by TDE in-house producer [[Willie B (producer)|Willie B]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2012/01/17/ab-soul-black-lip-bastard-prod-willie-b-of-digi-phonics/ |title=Ab-Soul \u2013  Black Lip Bastard (prod. Willie B of Digi+Phonics) |publisher=2DopeBoyz |date= January 17, 2012 |accessdate= May 27, 2012}}</ref> On February 28, 2012, Ab-Soul, alongside Schoolboy Q, appeared on [[Sway Calloway]]'s #SwayInTheMorning [[radio show]], where Ab-Soul called \"Black Lip Bastard\": \"pretty much one of the [[:wikt:title track|title tracks]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2012/02/28/schoolboy-q-ab-soul-5-fingers-of-death-freestyle-video/ |title=ScHoolboy Q & Ab-Soul \u2013  5 Fingers Of Death Freestyle (Video) |publisher=2DopeBoyz |date= February 28, 2012 |accessdate= May 27, 2012}}</ref> The first song that appears on the album, to be released was \"Showin' Love\", also produced by Willie B.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2012/03/02/ab-soul-showin-love-prod-willie-b-of-digiphonics/ |title=Ab-Soul \u2013  Showin' Love (prod. Willie B of Digi+Phonics) |publisher=2DopeBoyz |date= March 2, 2012 |accessdate= May 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, Schoolboy Q announced #TheGroovyTour; a month-long tour with Ab-Soul accompanying him the entire way. The tour began on April 20, at the [[Bill Graham Civic Auditorium]] in [[San Francisco]], California.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2012/03/24/schoolboy-q-announces-the-groovy-tour-w-ab-soul/ |title=ScHoolboy Q Announces The Groovy Tour w/ Ab-Soul |publisher=2DopeBoyz |date= March 24, 2012|accessdate= March 25, 2012}}</ref> On April 6, 2012, Ab-Soul liberated a song titled \"Terrorist Threats\". The song features frequent collaborator [[Jhen\u00e9 Aiko]] and fellow American rapper [[Danny Brown (rapper)|Danny Brown]], who proclaimed on [[Twitter]] that \"Black Hippy the new [[The Beatles|Beatles]] and I'm [[Harry Nilsson]]\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Fitzmaurice|first=Larry|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/13419-terrorist-threats-ft-danny-brown-and-jhene-aiko/|title=Ab-Soul: \"Terrorist Threats\" [ft. Danny Brown and Jhene Aiko] |publisher=[[Pitchfork Media]]|date= April 9, 2012|accessdate= May 27, 2012}}</ref> On April 17, 2012, Ab-Soul revealed the album's title to be ''[[Control System]]'' and unveiled the release date to be May 11, 2012. That same day, he also released a [[music video]] for \"Pineal Gland\", a song inspired by the [[psychedelic drug]] [[Dimethyltryptamine|DMT]] and of course the [[pineal gland]], a small [[endocrine system|endocrine]] gland in the [[vertebrate]] [[brain]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.djbooth.net/index/tracks/review/ab-soul-pineal-gland/ |title=Ab-Soul \u2013  Pineal Gland Music Video |publisher=DJBooth.net |date= April 17, 2012 |accessdate= May 27, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scoremoreshows.com/2012/04/ab-soul-%E2%80%93-pineal-gland-video/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130202003709/http://www.scoremoreshows.com/2012/04/ab-soul-%E2%80%93-pineal-gland-video/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 2, 2013 |title=Ab-Soul \u2013  Pineal Gland [video] |publisher=Scoremore |date=April 19, 2012 |accessdate=May 27, 2012 }}</ref> On April 24, 2012, Stevens released another song, \"SOPA\". The song, produced by Nez & Rio, references the [[Stop Online Piracy Act]] (SOPA), a United States [[Bill (proposed law)|bill]] introduced by [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] [[Lamar S. Smith]], that would have allowed the [[Federal government of the United States|U.S. government]] to control the [[Internet]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2012/04/24/ab-soul-sopa-f-schoolboy-q-prod-nez-rio/ |title=Ab-Soul \u2013  SOPA f. ScHoolboy Q (prod. Nez & Rio) |publisher=2DopeBoyz |date= April 24, 2012 |accessdate= May 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn May 1, 2012, Ab-Soul released another music video, for a new song titled \"Empathy\", the song features vocals from Stevens' late longtime [[girlfriend]] [[Alori Joh]] (December 16, 1986 - February 6, 2012), who had committed [[suicide]] earlier in February.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beatsandrants.com/2012/05/new-video-ab-soul-empathy-featuring-alori-joh-and-javonte.html |title=New Video: Ab-Soul \u2013  \"Empathy\" (Featuring Alori Joh and jaVont\u00e9) |publisher=beatsandrants.com |date= May 1, 2012 |accessdate= May 27, 2012}}</ref> Joh's death had a huge impact on Stevens and the recording process of ''Control System''.<ref name=\"alorijoh\">{{cite web|author=Alexis, Nadeska |title=Ab-Soul Had To Address Alori Joh's Death On 'The Book Of Soul'|url=http://rapfix.mtv.com/2013/02/25/ab-soul-had-to-address-alori-johs-death-on-the-book-of-soul/|publisher=[[MTV]]|date=February 25, 2013|accessdate=April 4, 2013}}</ref> On May 4, 2012, it was revealed \"Black Lip Bastard\" was [[remix]]ed and would feature his Black Hippy cohorts, Rock, Lamar and Schoolboy Q.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2012/05/04/ab-soul-black-lip-bastard-black-hippy-remix-preview/ |title=Ab-Soul \u2013  Black Lip Bastard (Black Hippy Remix) (Preview) |publisher=2DopeBoyz |date= May 4, 2012 |accessdate= May 27, 2012}}</ref> On May 8, 2012, his collaboration with Lamar, titled \"ILLuminate\", was released. The day before the album's release Ab-Soul revealed the track listing and released [[wikt:snippet|snippets]] from the album. The album, as written on the back cover, is \"Dedicated to the beautiful soul of Loriana Angel Johnson aka Alori Joh\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2012/05/10/ab-soul-controlsystem-artwork-x-tracklist-x-snippets/ |title=Ab-Soul \u2013 Control System (Tracklist x Snippets) |publisher=2DopeBoyz |date= May 10, 2012 |accessdate= May 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\n''Control System'' was released exclusively through iTunes on May 11, 2012, under Top Dawg Entertainment. The album sold approximately 5,300 units in an abbreviated week, debuting at number 83 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and appearing on several other [[Billboard charts|''Billboard'' charts]] as well.<ref>{{cite web | author= Jacobs, Allen | url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.19759/title.hip-hop-album-sales-the-week-ending-5-13-2012 | title=Hip Hop Album Sales: The Week Ending 5/13/2012 | publisher= [[HipHopDX]] | date=May 16, 2012 | accessdate=December 7, 2012}}</ref> The album sold an estimated 3,700 the next week.<ref>{{cite web | author=Jacobs, Allen | url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.19849/title.hip-hop-album-sales-the-week-ending-5-20-2012 | title=Hip Hop Album Sales: The Week Ending 5/20/2012 | publisher=[[HipHopDX]] | date=May 23, 2012 | accessdate=December 7, 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141105065517/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.19849/title.hip-hop-album-sales-the-week-ending-5-20-2012 | archive-date=November 5, 2014 | url-status=dead }}</ref> During 2012, Stevens toured with the rest of Black Hippy and fellow American rapper [[Stalley]], on [[Black Entertainment Television|BET]]'s Music Matters Tour.<ref>{{cite web | author=Daniel Isenberg | url=http://complex.com/music/2012/09/photo-recap-kendrick-lamar-schoolboy-q-ab-soul-and-stalley-rock-bets-music-matters-tour-in-dc/ | title=Photo Recap: Kendrick Lamar, ScHoolboy Q, Ab-Soul, and Stalley Rock BET's Music Matters Tour in D.C. | publisher= [[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] | date=September 16, 2012 | accessdate=January 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2012, Stevens was featured on [[Joe Budden]]'s mixtape ''A Loose Quarter'' on the track \"Cut From a Different Cloth\". The song received praise as one of the best songs on the project. Budden has since announced that he and Ab-Soul have recorded many songs together which will be seeing the light of day in the near future. Budden went on to praise Ab-Soul as \"one of the best things going in hip hop right now\".<ref>Harling, Danielle (November 30, 2012).  [http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.22058/title.joe-budden-talks-ab-soul-collaboration-touring-without-slaughterhouse \"Joe Budden Talks Ab-Soul Collaboration, Touring Without Slaughterhouse\"].  [[HipHopDX]].  Retrieved December 31, 2012.</ref>\n\n===2012-18: ''These Days\u2026'' and ''Do What Thou Wilt.''===\n{{main|These Days... (Ab-Soul album)|Do What Thou Wilt.}}\n[[File:Ab-Soul - The Smokers Club Tour 2013 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|Ab-Soul performing in [[Toronto]] in 2013.]]\nIn October 2012, American singer-songwriter and record producer [[JMSN]], who previously produced \"Nibiru\" for Stevens earlier in August, for what his label called \"TDE Fan Appreciation Week\", announced he and Stevens would be releasing a collaborative project together.<ref>{{cite web | author= | url=http://www.soulculture.co.uk/music-blog/ab-soul-and-jmsn-working-on-collaborative-ep-music-news/ | title=Ab-Soul and JMSN Working on Collaborative EP | publisher=SoulCulture | work=Music News | date=October 22, 2012 | accessdate=December 12, 2012}}</ref> The [[lead single]] for their collaborative album, which was set to be titled ''Unit 6'', was officially released via iTunes on January 22, 2013.<ref>{{cite web | title=\"You're Gone\" - Single by Ab-Soul & JMSN | url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/youre-gone-single/id593168039 | work=[[iTunes Store]] | publisher=[[Apple Inc.|Apple]] | accessdate=January 22, 2013}}</ref> The single, titled \"You're Gone\", features vocals from both artists, as well as production from JMSN.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2013/01/21/ab-soul-jmsn-youre-gone/ |title=Ab-Soul \u2013  & JMSN - \"You're Gone\" |publisher=2DopeBoyz |date= January 21, 2013 |accessdate= January 21, 2013}}</ref> On March 26, 2013, it was announced that Ab-Soul would be featured on ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]''{{'}}s 2013 Freshman Class issue, alongside Schoolboy Q and other up-and-coming rappers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2013/03/xxl-freshman-class-2013-cover-revealed/2/|title=XXL Freshman Class 2013 Cover Revealed|work=XXL|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn August 6, 2013, after a near four-month hiatus, Stevens released a new song produced by Willie B, titled \"Christopher DRONEr\", alluding to former [[LAPD]] police officer [[Christopher Dorner]]. Along with the song, he announced he was working on a new solo project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/08/ab-soul-christopher-droner|title=Listen: Ab-Soul \"Christopher DRONEr\"|author=Lauren Nostro|work=Complex|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> The following day he would speak to ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]'' and say that he and JMSN had finished the ''Unit 6'' album, however their management could not \"see eye to eye\", so the project was ultimately shelved for a possible later release, with Stevens saying: \"As of right now it\u2019s sounding like prequel to my album.\" He went on to confirm that JMSN and Jhene Aiko, will appear on the upcoming solo project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2013/08/ab-soul-speaks-on-new-single-and-upcoming-project-with-jmsn/|title=Ab-Soul Speaks On New Single And Upcoming Project With JMSN - XXL|publisher=}}</ref> On October 17, 2013, Stevens stated that he was close to finalizing the project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2013/10/ab-soul-putting-final-touches-next-project/|title=Ab-Soul Is Putting The Final Touches On His Next Project  - XXL|publisher=}}</ref> Then later that week, he confirmed that the project had been turned in for [[mixing (mathematics)|mixing]] and cleared up rumors that it was titled ''Black Lip Pastor''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/ab-soul-talks-on-upcoming-project-and-confusion-surrounding-title-isaiah-rashad-and-unit-6-news.7792.html|title=Ab-Soul Talks On Upcoming Project & Confusion Surrounding Title, Isaiah Rashad & \"Unit 6\"|author=Rose Lilah|work=HotNewHipHop|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.25844/title.ab-soul-finalizing-new-album-title-unknown|title=Ab-Soul Finalizing New Album, Title Unknown|author=HipHopDX|date=October 19, 2013|work=HipHopDX|accessdate=March 9, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141011130333/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.25844/title.ab-soul-finalizing-new-album-title-unknown|archive-date=October 11, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> With the release of the [[56th Annual Grammy Awards]] nominations, it was revealed Stevens was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] for his participation on [[Macklemore]] [[Macklemore & Ryan Lewis|&]] [[Ryan Lewis]]' debut album, ''[[The Heist (album)|The Heist]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.com/nominees |title=GRAMMY.com - The Official Site of Music's Biggest Night |work=The GRAMMYs |accessdate=March 9, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503164723/http://www.grammy.com/nominees |archivedate=May 3, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nOn January 2, 2014, Stevens revealed he had turned in two projects to his label Top Dawg, before the year 2013, was over: \"I turned in 2 projects last year, yea I know what your thinking, let's see where this year takes me\u2026\" he [[Twitter|tweeted]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.26870/title.ab-soul-says-he-turned-in-two-projects-in-2013 |title=Ab-Soul \u2013  Says He Turned In Two Projects In 2013 |publisher=Cheri Media Group |work=[[HipHopDX]] |date= January 3, 2014 |accessdate= January 4, 2014 |author=Baker, Soren}}</ref> On January 6, 2014, in an interview with Bootleg Kev, when speaking on the album Stevens stated: \"Ali is [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixing]] it right now,\" and that they were waiting on the perfect way to present the project, as a result of creative releases such as [[Nipsey Hussle]]'s ''[[Crenshaw (mixtape)|Crenshaw]]''.<ref name=\"bootlegkev\">{{cite web|url=http://bootlegkev.com/v2/2014/01/ab-soul-interview-w-bootleg-kev-exclusive/|title=Ab-Soul Interview w/ Bootleg Kev (Exclusive)|publisher=|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> He also revealed the album is about progression and confirmed there would be appearances from his TDE label-mates, as well as production from hip hop producer [[Statik Selektah]].<ref name=\"bootlegkev\"/> On April 11, 2014, Stevens announced he was also working on the third installment in the ''Longterm'' series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1725968/ab-soul-mixtape-longterm-3.jhtml|title=Ab-Soul Hints At New Mixtape In Longterm Series|work=MTV News|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rapdose.com/2014/04/11/ab-soul-announces-longterm-3-mixtape|title=Ab-Soul Announces \"Longterm 3\" Mixtape - Rap Dose|work=Rap Dose|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hypetrak.com/2014/04/ab-soul-announces-that-hes-working-on-longterm-3/|title=Ab-Soul Is Working On New Album|work=HYPETRAK|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref>\n[[File:Ab-Soul - AfroPunk Festival 2015.jpg|thumb|right|180px|Ab-Soul performing in Brooklyn in 2015.]]\nOn May 5, 2014, Stevens took to [[Twitter]] to announce his third album would be titled ''[[These Days... (Ab-Soul album)|These Days\u2026]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2014/05/ab-soul-reveal-album-title-via-twitter/|title=Ab-Soul's Album Title Is 'These Days...' - XXL|work=XXL|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> On May 30, 2014, Top Dawg management took to Twitter to reveal ''These Days...'', is scheduled for a June 24 release date. That same day, TDE management also unveiled the cover art for the album and released a snippet of a music video for Stevens' song \"Stigmata\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musictimes.com/articles/6480/20140531/ab-soul-releases-these-days%E2%80%A6-album-art-release-date-and-stigmata-teaser-video.htm|title=Ab-Soul Releases 'These Days\u2026' Album Art, Release Date And 'Stigmata' Teaser Video|work=Music Times|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2014/05/watch-ab-souls-video-for-stigmata|title=Watch Ab-Soul's Video for \"Stigmata\"|author=Zach Frydenlund|work=Complex|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> On June 21, 2014, Stevens released a music video for a song titled \"Closure\", taken from ''These Days...''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2014/06/21/video-ab-soul-closure/|title=Video: Ab-Soul \u2013 \u2018Closure\u2019|work=Rap-Up|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> The album debuted at number 11 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart, with first-week sales of 21,812 copies in the United States and has received generally positive reviews from [[music critics]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Tardio |first=Andres |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.29560/title.hip-hop-album-sales-week-ending-06-29-2014 |title=Hip Hop Album Sales: Week Ending 06/29/2014 |publisher=HipHop DX |date=2014-07-02 |accessdate=2014-07-02}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, in an interview with Montreality, Stevens revealed the title for his first in-store retail project would be ''Longterm 3''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/ab-soul-reveals-longterm-3-will-be-his-debut-album-new-video.31297.html|title=Ab-Soul Reveals \"Longterm 3\" Will Be His Debut Album|author=Trevor Smith|work=HotNewHipHop|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> In February 2015, Ab-Soul premiered the song \"47 Bars\" online, produced by [[The Alchemist (musician)|The Alchemist]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://2dopeboyz.com/2015/02/28/ab-soul-47-bars-alchemist/ |title=Ab-Soul - 47 Bars (prod. Alchemist) |publisher=2dopeboyz.com |date=February 28, 2015 |accessdate=March 2, 2015}}</ref> In July 2015, Stevens tweeted that his next album was \"almost done.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/abdashsoul/status/620942207478992898|title=Ab-Soul on Twitter|publisher=}}</ref> In July 2015, Stevens gave an update on the album: \"My album's almost done...\" he wrote on Twitter, adding, \"It's a love story\". He completed the post with the [[hashtag]] \"DWTW\", presumably the album title acronym to which he kept alluding.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/ab-souls-album-is-almost-done-news.16477.html|title=Ab-Soul's Album Is \"Almost Done\"|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn June 8, 2016, via Twitter, Stevens revealed he had completed his upcoming album and turned it in for [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/ab-soul-announces-album-tracclist-turned-in-news.22103.html|title=Ab-Soul Announces Album \"Tracclist Turned In\"|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2016/06/ab-soul-new-album-finished|title=Ab-Soul Confirms His New Album Is Finished and On the Way (UPDATE)|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/anthony-top-dawg-tiffith-blames-ab-soul-for-delaying-his-own-album-news.25408.html? |title=Ab Soul's next album is called DWTW |last=Walker |first=Angus |access-date=12 November 2016}}</ref> The album, titled ''[[Do What Thou Wilt.]]'', was released December 9, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/ab-soul-dwtw-do-what-thou-wilt-album-stream-new-mixtape.116692.html|title=Ab-Soul - DWTW (Do What Thou Wilt) [Album Stream]|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===2019-present: Upcoming Fifth Album===\n\nOn November 3, 2019, Stevens performed his set at the Day N Vegas music festival and promised fans a 2020 release date for his new album. On April 20, 2020, to commemorate Top Dawg Entertainment founder Anthony Tiffith's birthday, Stevens released the single ''Dangerookipawaa Freestyle''.\n\n== Artistry ==\n\n=== Influences ===\nAb-Soul cites fellow American rappers [[Twista]], [[Canibus]], [[Eminem]], [[Nas]] and [[Lupe Fiasco]] as major influences, with [[Jay Z]] being his biggest influence.<ref name=\"influences\">{{cite web | author=Baker, Soren | url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.24280/title.ab-soul-cites-jay-z-as-his-biggest-influence | title=Ab-Soul Cites Jay-Z As His Biggest Influence | publisher=Cheri Media Group | work=HipHopDX | date=June 11, 2013 | accessdate=June 11, 2013}}</ref> He stated: \"There are so many others, but those are the ones that came to my mind at this time. Those artists are basically the template to my format as an [[MC]]. They all capture me with their music, whether it be the vibe, delivery, [[Cadence (music)|cadence]], [[Storytelling|story]], or just the [[lyrics]] in general.\"<ref name=\"influences\"/>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|Ab-Soul discography|Black Hippy discography}}\n\n*''[[Longterm Mentality]]'' (2011)\n*''[[Control System]]'' (2012)\n*''[[These Days... (album)|These Days\u2026]]'' (2014)\n*''[[Do What Thou Wilt.]]'' (2016)\n\n==Concert tours==\n*These Days Tour (2014)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/ab-soul-announces-these-days-tour-news.11743.html?image=1|title=Ab-Soul Announces \"These Days\" Tour|publisher=}}</ref>\n*YMF Tour (2017)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/ab-soul-announces-ymf-tour-with-little-simz-news.29844.html|title=Ab-Soul Announces \"YMF\" Tour With Little Simz|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of hip hop musicians|List of hip-hop musicians]]\n* [[List of people from California]]\n* [[Music of California]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n<!-- Per [[WP:ELMINOFFICIAL]], choose one official website only -->\n{{commons category|Ab-Soul}}\n* {{twitter}}\n* {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=mn0002043281|label=Ab-Soul}}\n\n{{Ab-Soul}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:People from Carson, California]]\n[[Category:Rappers from California]]\n