 Kong)</small>\n| iptv chan 6       = Channel 326\n| iptv serv 7       = [[:zh:\u6fb3\u9580\u6709\u7dda\u96fb\u8996|Macau Cable TV]] <small>([[Macau]])</small>\n| iptv chan 7       = Channel 806\n| iptv serv 8       = [[Meo (telecommunication service)|MEO]]<br/><small>(Portugal)</small>\n| iptv chan 8       = Channel 203 (POR)\n| iptv serv 9       = [[Unifi TV]]<br/><small>([[Malaysia]])</small>\n| iptv chan 9       = Channel 402 (old) <br> Channel 612 (new) \n| iptv serv 10      = NexTV-America<br/><small>(United States, Canada)</small>\n| iptv chan 10      = Channel 28\n| iptv serv 12      = [[Chunghwa Telecom|CHT MOD]]<br/><small>([[Taiwan]])</small>\n| iptv chan 12      = Channel 555\n| iptv serv 13      = [[Olleh TV]]<br/><small>([[South Korea]])</small>\n| iptv chan 13      = Channel 176\n| iptv serv 14      = [[Moja TV]]<br/><small>([[Bosnia and Herzegovina]])</small>\n| iptv chan 14      = Channel 6\n| iptv serv 15      = Open IPTV<br/><small>([[Bosnia and Herzegovina]])</small>\n| iptv chan 15      = Channel 502\n| iptv serv 16      = [[Canal (TV provider)|Canal]]\n| iptv chan 16      = Channel 104\n| iptv serv 17      = [[TTNET]] <small>(Turkey)</small>\n| iptv chan 17      = Channel 76\n| iptv serv 18      = [[AKTA TV|Max TV]] <small>(Macedonia)</small>\n| iptv chan 18      = Channel 655\n| iptv serv 19      = ZAP <small>(Cape Verde)</small>\n| iptv chan 19      = Channel 8 (POR)\n| iptv serv 20      = [[Eir (telecommunications)|Eir TV]] <small>(Ireland)</small>\n| iptv chan 20      = Channel 508\n| iptv serv 21      = [[KPN]] <small>(Netherlands)</small>\n| iptv chan 21      = Channel 41\n| online serv 1     = euronews.com\n| online chan 1     = [https://www.euronews.com/live Watch live]\n| online serv 2     = [[Ziggo#Ziggo_GO|Ziggo GO]] <small>(Netherlands)</small>\n| online chan 2     = [https://www.ziggogo.tv ZiggoGO.tv] (Europe only)\n}}\n\n'''Euronews''' is a European pay television [[news broadcasting|news]] network, headquartered in [[Lyon]], [[France]]. The network began broadcasting on 1 January 1993 and aimed to cover world news from a [[Pan-European identity|pan-European]] perspective.\n\nIt is jointly owned by several European and [[North Africa]]n state broadcasting organizations, and since 2015 majority-owned (53%) by Media Globe Networks led by Egyptian billionaire [[Naguib Sawiris]] who is chairman of the supervisory board. It is also a provider of [[live streaming world news]] which can be viewed via its website, [[YouTube]], and various [[mobile devices]] and [[digital media players]].\n\n==History and organisation==\n[[File: Euronews HQ \u00a9euronews photo St\u00e9phane Audras 2015.10.15 (169).JPG|thumb|Euronews headquarters in Lyon]]\n\nIn 1992, following the [[Gulf War|Persian Gulf War]], during which [[CNN]]'s position as the preeminent source of [[24-hour news cycle|24-hour news]] programming was cemented, the [[European Broadcasting Union]] decided to establish Euronews to present information from a European perspective. The channel's first broadcast was on 1 January 1993 from Lyon. An additional broadcast studio was set up in London in 1996. It was founded by a group of ten public broadcasters:<ref>{{cite book|last1=Collins|first1=Richard|title=From Satellite to Single Market: New Communication Technology and European Public Service Television|publisher=Routledge|year=1998|location=London|pages=130|isbn=9780415179706}}</ref>\n\n*[[Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation|CyBC]], Cyprus\n*[[France T\u00e9l\u00e9visions]], France\n*[[RAI]], Italy\n*[[RTBF]], Belgium\n*[[R\u00e1dio e Televis\u00e3o de Portugal|RTP]], Portugal\n*[[RTVE]], Spain (former shareholder)\n*[[TMC (TV channel)|TMC]], Monaco (former shareholder)\n*[[Yle]], Finland\n*[[ERTU]], Egypt\n\nIn 1997, the British news broadcaster [[ITN]] purchased a 49 percent share of Euronews for \u00a35.1&nbsp;million from [[Alcatel-Lucent]].<ref>{{cite news|title=ITN Acquires 49% Euronews Stake|date=1 December 1997|url=https://www.telecompaper.com/news/itn-acquires-49-euronews-stake--124079|work=Telecom Paper|accessdate=5 June 2012}}</ref> ITN supplies the content of the channel along with the remaining shareholders, which are represented by the '''SOCEMIE''' ({{lang-fr|Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 \u00e9ditrice de la cha\u00eene europ\u00e9enne multilingue d'information Euronews}}) [[consortium]]. Euronews SA is the operating company that produces the channel and holds the broadcasting licence. It is co-owned by the ten founders and:\n\n*[[All-Russia State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company|VGTRK]], Russia\n*[[Turkish Radio and Television Corporation|TRT]], Turkey\n*[[\u010cesk\u00e1 televize|\u010cT]], Czech Republic\n*[[Public Broadcasting Services|PBS]], Malta\n*[[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Nationale de Radiodiffusion et de T\u00e9l\u00e9vision|SNRT]], Morocco\n*[[Radiotelevizija Slovenija|RTVSLO]], Slovenia\n*[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RT\u00c9]], Ireland\n*[[UA:PBC]], Ukraine\n*[[Swiss Broadcasting Corporation|SRG-SSR]], Switzerland\n*[[Romanian Television|TVR]], Romania\n*[[Sveriges Television|SVT]]/[[Modern Times Group|MTG]], Sweden\n*[[\u00c9tablissement de la radiodiffusion-t\u00e9l\u00e9vision tunisienne|ERTT]], Tunisia\n*[[Public Establishment of Television|ENTV]], Algeria\n\nThe broadcast switched from solely [[Analog transmission|analogue]] to mainly [[Digital data|digital]] transmission in 1999. In the same year, the Portuguese audio track was added. The Russian audio track appeared in 2001.\n\nIn 2003, ITN sold its stake in Euronews as part of its drive to streamline operations and focus on news-gathering rather than channel management.<ref name=\"BroadcastMagazine\">{{cite news|url=https://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/multi-platform/news/itn-drops-out-of-euronews-channel/1116586.article|title=ITN Drops Out of Euronews Channel|newspaper=[[Broadcast (magazine)|Broadcast]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 February 2006, Ukrainian public broadcaster [[UA:PBC|Natsionalna Telekompanya Ukra\u00efny (NTU)]] purchased a one percent interest in SOCEMIE.<ref name=\"digitalspy\">{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/media/a28857/ntu-becomes-20th-euronews-shareholder/|title=NTU Becomes 20th EuroNews Shareholder|date=5 February 2006|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 May 2008, Spanish public broadcaster [[RTVE]] decided to leave Euronews to promote its international channel [[TVE Internacional]]. It also cited legal requirements to maintain low debt levels through careful spending as a factor influencing its decision to leave.<ref name=\"elmundo\">{{cite news|url=https://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2008/06/05/comunicacion/1212656729.html|title=TVE abandona EuroNews|language=Spanish|date=5 February 2006|newspaper=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2009, the Turkish public broadcaster [[Turkish Radio and Television Corporation|TRT]] became a shareholder in the channel and joined its supervisory board.<ref>{{cite news|title=Turkey's TRT joins Euronews supervisory board|date=15 September 2009|url=https://www.worldbulletin.net/archive/turkeys-trt-joins-euronews-supervisory-board-h47271.html|work=World Bulletin|accessdate=5 June 2012}}</ref> TRT purchased 15.70% of the channel's shares and became the fourth main partner after France T\u00e9l\u00e9visions (23.93%), RAI (21.54%), and [[All-Russia State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company|VGTRK]] (16.94%).\n\nIn February 2015, the channel's executive board approved a bid by Media Globe Networks, owned by Egyptian telecom magnate [[Naguib Sawiris]], to acquire a 53% controlling stake in the media outlet. The deal raised questions over Euronews's future editorial posture and independence.<ref>{{cite news|title=Egyptian Mogul Plans to Buy Controlling Stake in Europe's Answer to CNN|date=27 February 2015|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/egyptian-mogul-sawiris-buy-euronews-778229|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=25 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Controversial ventures pose questions for Euronews|date=24 March 2015|url=https://euobserver.com/news/128098|work=EU Observer|accessdate=25 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Euronews investor Naguib Sawiris: we will resist state interference|date=27 February 2015|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/feb/27/euronews-investor-naguib-sawiris-we-will-resist-state-interference|work=The Guardian|accessdate=25 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Language availability===\n[[File:COTY 2018, Le Grand-Saconnex (1X7A9290).jpg|thumb|Good Morning Europe anchor Belle Donati]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! #\n! Language\n! Launch\n! Stopped\n|-\n| 1\n| [[Modern English|English]]\n| 1 January 1993\n|\n|-\n| 2\n| [[French language|French]]\n| 1 January 1993\n|\n|-\n| 3\n| [[Standard German|German]]\n| 1 January 1993\n|\n|-\n| 4\n| [[Italian language|Italian]]\n| 1 January 1993\n|\n|-\n| 5\n| [[Castilian Spanish|Spanish]]\n| 1 January 1993\n|\n|-\n| 6\n| [[European Portuguese|Portuguese]]\n| November 1999\n|\n|-\n| 7\n| [[Russian language|Russian]]\n| 17 September 2001\n|\n|-\n| 8\n| [[Modern Standard Arabic|Arabic]]\n| 12 July 2008\n|\n|-\n| 9\n| [[Turkish language|Turkish]]\n| 30 January 2010\n|\n|-\n| 10\n| [[Persian language|Persian]]\n| 27 October 2010\n|\n|-\n| 11\n| [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]]\n| 24 August 2011\n| May 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.broadbandtvnews.com/2017/05/22/euronews-closes-ukrainian-service/|title=Euronews closes Ukrainian service|date=22 May 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 12\n| [[Modern Greek|Greek]]\n| 18 December 2012\n|\n|-\n| 13\n| [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]]\n| 30 May 2013\n|\n|-\n|14\n| [[Georgian language|Georgian]]\n| July 2019 \n| \n|-\n|  15\n|  [[Albanian language|Albanian]]\n| 21 November 2019\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n===Radio service===\nOn 2 October 2012, Euronews launched Euronews Radio. The service was designed for viewers for whom \"watching news is not an option\" by providing a direct simulcast to the TV channel, with \"No Comment\" segment being replaced by music. The music of the bulletin openings is also transmitted on Euronews Radio. Weather reports are read by a female announcer.\n\n===Africanews===\n{{main|Africanews}}\n\nOn 20 April 2016, the French subsidiary of Euronews launched an African version of their news service called Africanews in French and English.\n\n===Partnership with NBC===\nIn November 2016, the channel's executive board was in talks with [[NBCUniversal]], the parent company of [[NBC News]], for a \"strategic partnership\". NBCU would acquire 15 to 30% ownership of the Euronews network, would contribute to Euronews content, and facilitate NBC News' expanded operations in Europe.<ref>{{cite news|title=NBC News, Euronews in Talks for Strategic Partnership|date=11 November 2016|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/global/nbc-news-euronews-talks-strategic-partnership-1201915855/|work=Variety Media|accessdate=11 November 2016}}</ref> After successful negotiations with the [[European Commission]], who feared that the partnership would result in an ''Americanization'' of Euronews, the NBCUniversal News Group finally purchased a 25% stake in Euronews in February 2017 for $30&nbsp;million. NBC News president [[Deborah Turness]] was appointed to head up international operations, and incumbent Euronews CEO Michael Peters, who had led it since 2004, became CEO of the new partnership. Both report directly to NBC News chairman [[Andrew Lack (executive)|Andrew Lack]]. The resulting partnership became known as Euronews NBC.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Palmeri|first1=Christopher|title=NBC Acquires Stake in Euronews, Taps U.S. News Chief to Lead It|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-02-14/nbc-acquires-stake-in-euronews-taps-u-s-news-chief-to-lead-it|accessdate=17 February 2017|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.|date=14 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Sawiris and NBC News have the largest stakes in Euronews, editorial control by SOCEMIE members has been assured, with the broadcasters having seven slots in the editorial board, as opposed to Sawiris' company (which has three slots) and NBC News, which only has one, thereby reducing rumors of an ''Americanization'' of Euronews' values. Editorial control is fully handled by Euronews' teams, with NBC only focusing on planning and coordinating tasks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-eco/2017/05/31/97002-20170531FILWWW00300-euronews-le-rapprochement-avec-nbc-finalise.php|title=Euronews: le rapprochement avec NBC finalis\u00e9 (in French)|date=31 May 2017|work=Le Figaro}}</ref> After the formation of the partnership, video reports from NBC News' properties began to appear frequently on the TV channel and reports from [[NBCNews.com]] began to be distributed on its digital platforms.\n\nOn 9 May 2017, Euronews split its service into 12 language-specific editions, of which nine have a linear TV channel with its own language voiceover, but now including contents, on-air graphics (except for some segments) and its lower-third news ticker in the language. The ''glocal'' strategy allows the language editorial teams to personalize the content and presentation of their channel, not only by sharing own-produced content with other languages but by producing content that is relevant to local audiences and allowing local reporters and presenters to appear on camera in all its language editions. The splitting process finished on 24 May 2017.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.panoramaaudiovisual.com/2017/05/10/euronews-reinventa-su-oferta-de-difusion-y-digital/|title=Euronews reinventa su oferta de difusi\u00f3n y digital (in Spanish)|date=10 May 2017|website=Panorama Audiovisual}}</ref>\n\nAlongside the major language split, satellite distribution for the German, Spanish, Portuguese and Turkish channels was discontinued, now being only available via fiber-optic IP uplink.<ref name=\":0\" /> However, the discontinuation of the German-language channel from satellite distribution generated outcry from many German satellite TV owners, resulting in the restoration of the German-language channel on the [[Astra 1L]] satellite on 25 July 2017, via an unencrypted SD feed sitting alongside the French-language channel. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.broadbandtvnews.com/2017/07/26/euronews-puts-german-channel-back-on-satellite/|title=Euronews puts German channel back on satellite|last=Krieger|first=J\u00f6rn|date=26 July 2017|work=Broadband TV News}}</ref> Additionally, the Arabic and Persian language editions became available only on Euronews' website and apps, with the TV channels being discontinued, and the Ukrainian edition was discontinued outright, due to lack of funding from the Ukrainian government.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telesatellite.com/actu/49612-fin-de-la-version-ukrainienne-euronews.html|title=Fin de la version ukrainienne d'Euronews (in French)|date=23 May 2017|work=T\u00e9l\u00e9 Satellite et Num\u00e9rique}}</ref> Finally, the Euronews channel in English became known as the ''World'' edition, and distribution to premises in the American continent via fiber-optic IP uplink is set to begin later in 2018.<ref name=\":0\" /> These changes caused the elimination of 43 staff positions, mainly from the Ukrainian edition, causing major layoffs and production staff having more flexible roles.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://lexpansion.lexpress.fr/actualites/1/actualite-economique/euronews-43-departs-a-l-issue-du-plan-de-sauvegarde_1911482.html|title=Euronews: 43 d\u00e9parts \u00e0 l'issue du plan de sauvegarde (in French)|date=24 May 2017|work=L'Express-L'Expansion}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Euronews' English-language channel began to gradually revamp its programming schedule, with the roll-out of a new slate of presenter-led programming to complement its already existing shows, a move that was reported earlier in the year, after the success of its presenter-led special reports and weekly programming introduced in recent years.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.a516digital.com/2018/01/big-changes-for-euronews-in-2018.html|title=Big changes for Euronews in 2018|date=2 January 2018|work=a516digital}}</ref> Alongside conventional rolling news shows, debate programming, talk shows, and new presenter-led shows will be offered during the weekly schedule, and throughout programs, Euronews reporters from different nationalities will be offering context on stories close to their respective home nationalities.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedrum.com/opinion/2017/05/11/euronews-overhauls-its-broadcasting-strategy-bid-become-the-unrivalled-chronicler|title=Euronews overhauls its broadcasting strategy in bid to become the unrivaled chronicler of Europe|last=Burrell|first=Ian|date=11 May 2017|work=The Drum}}</ref>\n\nThe roll-out began on 22 May, when Euronews debuted the first of these new shows, ''Good Morning Europe'', a five-hour morning show which airs every weekday morning from 7 am. It was first anchored by former [[RT (TV network)|RT]] correspondent and [[TVB Pearl]] news presenter Tesa Arcilla, which anchored it on a temporary basis. Some weeks later, former [[France 24]] presenter Belle Donati began presenting the show, alternating with Arcilla; after she moved to [[Brussels]] in September, she became the main anchor of the slot. Two months later, on 17 July, Euronews debuted a six-hour breaking news show, ''Euronews Now'', anchored by Tokunbo Salako, covering the dayside and afternoon slots. On 3 September, the new evening program lineup was launched, starting with a politics-focused show, ''Raw Politics'', hosted by Tesa Arcilla, and featuring former [[Sky News]] reporter Darren McCaffrey from [[Brussels]]. Two weeks later, on 17 September, the full roll-out was completed with the introduction of a 5-hour evening rolling news show, ''Euronews Tonight'', presented by former [[Sky News]] and [[BBC News]] presenter [[Sam Naz]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedrum.com/opinion/2018/08/09/inside-euronews-nbc-fresh-rolling-news-channel-striving-help-save-united-europe|title=Inside Euronews NBC: a fresh rolling news channel striving to help save united Europe|last=Burrell|first=Ian|date=9 August 2018|work=The Drum|access-date=}}</ref> The traditional pre-produced blocks of video content still remains on late nights and weekends. Most overnights now repeat the previous day's edition (either full or half-length) of ''Euronews Now''.\n\nNew weekly programming is also being produced, including the weekly interview series ''Uncut'', which feature conversations from political leaders and newsmakers worldwide with minimum to no editing. The first episodes feature German-French politician [[Daniel Cohn-Bendit]] interviewing former [[UK Independence Party|UKIP]] leader [[Nigel Farage]] and former [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|UK Prime Minister]] [[Tony Blair]] about [[Brexit]]. Additionally, a new social media unit was created, with journalists with a background on digital news verification leading it. The newly-created team help to produce ''The Cube'', a social media segment during rolling news shows, focusing on analysis on treatment and reactions about news headlines on social media, with special attention at the major stories of the day. ''No Comment'', a long-standing element of Euronews' programming, remains on the channels' schedule, and it's being gradually integrated into the rolling news shows on the English-language channel.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nAdditionally, a major investment in mobile reporting via [[iPhone]] devices helped Euronews gain a major [[Scoop (news)|scoop]], becoming the only TV news outlet worldwide to broadcast live coverage from the [[Aquarius Dignitus|MV Aquarius]], with Paris correspondent Annelise Borges (formerly with [[France 24]]) on assignment. Borges broadcast lives for 10 days as the new Italian far-right government denied the Aquarius access to Italian ports. The coverage made headlines on many news outlets worldwide and helped Euronews boost its credibility and its audience.<ref name=\":2\" /> The new Euronews also hired new correspondents in London, Berlin, Moscow, Rome, Madrid and Washington D.C., and gained access to NBC News' large network of correspondents worldwide. This included [[Jack Parrock]] in the Euronews Brussels bureau. \n\nAs of September 2018, the other language editions are unaffected, with the pre-produced blocks of video content remaining at all times, although there are plans to introduce presenter-led programming during the morning slots on these other channels.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAfter the takeover of [[Sky (company)|Sky plc]] by NBCUniversal's parent company [[Comcast]] on 22 September 2018, EuronewsNBC will increase its worldwide reach, as it plans to closely integrate its operations (and those of NBC News) with those of [[Sky News]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/card/what-s-so-great-about-sky-n890601|title=What's so great about Sky?|last=Atkinson|first=Claire|date=11 July 2018|work=NBCNews.com}}</ref>\n\n==Broadcast==\nThe channel is available in 430&nbsp;million households in 166 countries worldwide. It reaches more than 170&nbsp;million European households by [[cable television|cable]], [[satellite television|satellite]] and [[terrestrial television|terrestrial]]. It also began to secure availability on [[multimedia]] platforms such as [[IPTV]] and digital media.<ref name=\"MediaPressPack\">{{cite news|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131126032901/http://www.euronews.com/media/the-station/mediapackpress_EN.pdf|title=Euronews Media Presspack|accessdate=27 June 2010|newspaper=Euronews}}</ref>\n\nEuronews launched an application for mobile devices ([[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iPhone]], and [[iPad]]) which is called \"Euronews Live\". The application is free of charge and is available on Google Play and the App Store.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euronews.com/services/euronews-live-app/|title=euronews live application|accessdate=20 August 2011|newspaper=Euronews|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308144516/http://www.euronews.com/services/euronews-live-app/|archivedate=8 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> This app was later shut down quietly.\n\nThe following countries also broadcast Euronews through terrestrial channels for a limited amount of time:\n{{Div col}}\n*ArmNews.Eu ([[Sweden]]) in Russian\n*[[Face TV (Bosnia and Herzegovina)|Face TV]] ([[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]) in English\n*[[Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation|CyBC]] DTV Platform ([[Cyprus]]) in English and [[Modern Greek|Greek]] (also simulcasted by [[RIK 2]] when its programming is over)\n*[[Hellenic Broadcasting Corporation|ERT]] ([[Greece]]) in English and [[Modern Greek|Greek]]\n*[[T\u00e9l\u00e9 Liban|TL]] ([[Lebanon]]) in [[Modern Standard Arabic|Arabic]] daily at 8:00\n*[[RT\u00c9 One]], [[RT\u00c92]], [[RT\u00c9 News Now]] (Ireland) in English\n*[[Canal Extremadura Televisi\u00f3n|Canal Extremadura]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canalextremadura.es/alacarta/radio/audios/ettore-scola|title=Programaci\u00f3n de Euronews en Extremadura TV|accessdate=10 February 2013|date=10 February 2013|publisher=[[Extremadura TV]]|language=Spanish}}</ref> [[Arag\u00f3n TV]], [[La 7 Televisi\u00f3n Regi\u00f3n de Murcia|7RM]] Murcia (Spain) in [[Castilian Spanish|Spanish]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.heraldo.es/noticias/comunicacion/2013/01/14/euronews-llega-a-la-tdt-a-traves-de-aragon-tv-213120.html|title=Euronews llega a la TDT en Espa\u00f1a a trav\u00e9s de Arag\u00f3n TV|accessdate=27 January 2013|date=1 January 2013|newspaper=Heraldo|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n*[[Television Malta|TVM]] ([[Malta]]) in English\n*[[RTP2]] and [[RTP Africa]] ([[Portugal]]) in [[European Portuguese|Portuguese]]\n*[[TVR News]] ([[Romania]]) in [[Romanian language|Romanian]]\n*[[TV Koper-Capodistria]] ([[Slovenia]]) in Italian\n*[[RSI La 1]] & [[RSI La 2]] ([[Switzerland]]) in Italian and [[Standard German|German]]\n*[[RTS Un]] ([[Switzerland]]) in French and English\n*[[TRT Haber]] ([[Turkey]]) in [[Turkish language|Turkish]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\nThe channel's programmes are also available by [[podcast]], and it has also maintained a YouTube channel since October 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=\"No Comment\" sur YouTube ? Affirmatif|date=10 August 2007|url=https://www.liberation.fr/ecrans/2007/10/10/no-comment-sur-youtube-affirmatif_103492|newspaper=Lib\u00e9ration|accessdate=5 June 2012|language=French}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the largest Belarusian state network MTIS stopped broadcasting Euronews for unknown reasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://naviny.by/rubrics/society/2012/01/01/ic_news_116_383897|script-title=ru:\u0412 \u0441\u0435\u0442\u0438 \u041c\u0422\u0418\u0421 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0449\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043b\u044f\u0446\u0438\u044f \u043a\u0430\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0430 \"\u0415\u0432\u0440\u043e\u043d\u044c\u044e\u0441\"|accessdate=5 June 2012|date=1 January 2012|publisher=Naviny|language=Russian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://euroradio.fm/ru/report/v-minske-otklyuchayut-euronews-87163|title=\u0412 \u041c\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0435 \u043e\u0442\u043a\u043b\u044e\u0447\u0430\u044e\u0442 Euronews|accessdate=5 June 2012|date=31 December 2011|publisher=Euroradio|language=Russian}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the new commercial channel Planet TV started broadcasting Euronews dubbed in Slovenian after Antenna TV SL purchased a major stake in the company. Euronews airs after closedown (or sign-off) of Planet TV, but both call sign logos are displayed.\n\nIn September 2016, Euronews disappeared from the [[Freesat]] channel list in the UK, in a move made by Sawiris.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.a516digital.com/2016/09/satellite-update-sky-q-by-default.html|title=Satellite Update: SkyQ by default, Freesat withdrawals|date=26 September 2016|website=a516digital|access-date=3 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, VGTRK ceased simulcasting Euronews to expand broadcasting hours of [[Russia-K]] channel.\n\n===Euronews Albania franchise===\nIn 2019, Euronews launched its first franchise through a joint venture with local [[IN TV (Albania)|RTV In]] in Albania. The new channel known as Euronews Albania is based in [[Tirana]], [[Albania]] and covers the Western Balkans countries of Albania, Montenegro, Kosovo, and North Macedonia.<ref> https://www.innovationmcc.com/post/euronews-launches-albanian-franchise-airing-in-2019</ref>\n===HD===\n[[High-definition television|High-definition]] (HD) broadcasting was started on 2 November 2016 via satellite using [[Hot Bird]]-capacities (English audio only). Regarding the audio codec, Euronews used the [[Dolby Digital|AC3]] format at the beginning here, changing to the [[Advanced Audio Coding|AAC]] codec in March 2017, and changing it again to the MPEG codec in April 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=digitalbitrate|url=http://www.digitalbitrate.com/files/s21/S21_11565_801_a.png?v=1493887506|publisher=digitalbitrate.com|accessdate=7 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Logos==\n[[File:Euronews logo globe.png|135px|thumb|right|Identifying graphic used with logo below]]\n[[File:Euronews logo text.svg|135px|thumb|right|Logo used from October 1998 to June 2008]]\n[[File:Euronews grey logo.svg|135px|thumb|right|Logo used from June 2008 to May 2016]]\n\nThe current Euronews logo is the fifth. From 1 January 1993 to February 1999 the logo was in the lower right corner of the screen, from February 1999 to June 2008 it was in the upper left corner of the screen, from June 2008 to May 2016 it was in the upper right corner of the screen, and from May 2016 to present it has been in the lower-left corner of the screen.\n\n*January 1993{{snd}}September 1996: blue lower case word \"euro\" in a yellow parallelogram and yellow capital word \"NEWS\".\n*September 1996{{snd}}February 1999: white lower case word \"euro\" above and blue lower case word \"news\" below.\n*February 1999{{snd}}June 2008: blue rectangle enclosing white camel case word \"EuroNews\".\n*June 2008{{snd}}May 2016: the white lowercase word \"Euronews\" on a neutral grey background featuring a white circle symbolizing both the world and star circle on the flag of Europe.\n*In January 2016, Euronews was accused of plagiarism by the Congolese media group AfricaNews,<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.jeuneafrique.com/mag/294349/economie/euronews-accuse-de-plagiat-groupe-kinois/|title=Africanews \u2013 Euronews accus\u00e9 de plagiat|date=25 January 2016}}</ref> because the Lyon-based channel used the logo \"Africanews\" for its African subsidiary in 2016. However, AfricaNews in the Democratic Republic of Congo<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.africanewsrdc.com/|title=Africa News RDC \u2013 L'actualit\u00e9 de la RD Congo et de l'Afrique|publisher=africanewsrdc.com}}</ref> has existed since 2005 and can be found on the Internet. Its employees sent letters to French authorities and managing director of Euronews, Michael Peters, to change the related logo and not to use it for the African subsidiary of Euronews.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.africanewsrdc.net/featured/africanews-vs-euronews-affaire-de-plagiat/|title=AfricaNews vs Euronews: affaire de plagiat|first=R\u00e9daction|last=AfricaNews|date=25 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalbusiness.africa/rd-congo-euronews-accuse-de-plagiat-avec-africanews/|title=RD Congo : Euronews accus\u00e9 de plagiat Avec AfricaNews|first=TIC MagTIC|last=Mag|date=8 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n*{{As of|2016|May|alt=Since}} May 2016: silver-white lower case word \"Euronews\" followed by a small circle at foot of the last letter, all on a light navy background.\n\n===Programming===\n'''Flagship'''\n*Good Morning Europe (''J\u00f3 Reggelt Eur\u00f3pa in Hungary'')\n*Euronews Now\n*Euronews Tonight\n*Euronews am Abend (German-speaking territories)\n*Euronews Soir (French-speaking territories)\n*Euronews Hoy (Spanish-speaking territories)\n*Euronews Noite (Portuguese-speaking territories)\n*Euronews Sera (Italian-speaking territories)\n*Euronews Live (for breaking news stories)\n*Prime Edition\n*Late Edition\n*No Comment\n*World News\n*Euronews Weekend\n\n'''Europe and global'''\n*Brussels Bureau\n*Smart Regions\n*State of the Union\n*Raw Politics (discontinued from October 2019) \n*Raw Politis: Your Call (discontinued from October 2019)\n*Aid Zone\n*Global Japan\n*Insider\n*Insight\n*Inspire Africa\n*Inspire Middle East\n*Learning World\n*The Global Conversation\n*View\n\n'''Weather'''\n*Meteo Europe\n*Meteo Global\n*Meteo Airport\n*Meteo\n\n'''Culture and technology'''\n*Cult\n*Cinema\n*European Lens\n*Musica\n*Climate Update\n*Ocean\n*Sci-tech\n*Space\n*Style\n\n'''Travel'''\n*Futuris\n*Adventures\n*Focus\n*Notes from the USA\n*Taste\n*Postcards\n*Wander\n\n==Bureau locations==\nEuronews primarily broadcasts from its headquarters in Lyon, but also maintains international bureaux for editorial or marketing purposes in [[Athens]], Brussels, [[Budapest]], [[Doha]], [[Dubai]], [[Istanbul]], London, Paris and Washington D.C. {{citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Africanews]]\n*[[BBC World News]]\n*[[E!Sharp]]\n*[[EUobserver]]\n*[[The Brussels Times]]\n*[[EURACTIV]]\n*[[Eurosport]]\n*''[[New Europe (newspaper)|New Europe]]'' newspaper\n*[[Politico Europe]]\n*[[Europe Elects]]\n\n{{portal bar|European Union|Journalism|Television}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Euronews}}\n*[https://www.euronews.com/ Official website]\n\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{France T\u00e9l\u00e9visions}}\n{{World news channels}}\n{{Television in Russia}}\n{{Portuguese television stations}}\n{{Television in Germany}}\n{{Television in Ukraine}}\n{{Subscription television channels in Australia}}\n{{RTBF}}\n{{NBCUniversal}}\n}}\n{{Portal bar|Companies|Television|Journalism|European Union}}\n\n[[Category:1993 establishments in the European Union]]\n[[Category:24-hour television news channels in France]]\n[[Category:Arabic-language television stations]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Lyon]]\n[[Category:English-language television stations]]\n[[Category:European Initiative Prize recipients]]\n[[Category:International broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Foreign television channels broadcasting in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:French-language television stations]]\n[[Category:German-language television stations]]\n[[Category:Greek-language television stations]]\n[[Category:Italian-language television stations]]\n[[Category:Media in the European Union]]\n[[Category:Multilingual news services]]\n[[Category:Pan-European media companies]]\n[[Category:Persian-language television stations]]\n[[Category:Portuguese-language television stations]]\n[[Category:Publicly funded broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Russian-language television stations]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language television stations]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1993]]\n[[Category:Television channels in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Television channels in Flanders]]\n[[Category:Television channels in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Television channels in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Television channels in Russia]]\n[[Category:Television stations in France]]\n[[Category:Turkish-language television stations]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian-language television stations]]\n[[Category:French news websites]]\n", "name_user": "Lukeskywalker1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euronews"}
{"title_page": "Fashion (David Bowie song)", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Fashion\n| cover      = Bowie_Fashion.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[David Bowie]]\n| album      = [[Scary Monsters (And Super Creeps)]]\n| B-side     = [[Scream Like a Baby]]\n| released   = 24 October 1980\n| format     = [[Single (music)|7\" single]]\n| recorded   = February 1980\u2014April 1980\n| studio     = [[Avatar Studios|Power Station]], New York; Good Earth, London\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Funk rock]]\n* [[New wave music|new wave]]\n* [[post-punk]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/david-bowies-essential-albums-251055/|title=Rob Sheffield on David Bowie's Essential Albums|last=Sheffield|first=Rob|date=18 August 2016|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=4 August 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n| length     = 3:23 <small>(7\" single edit)</small><br/>4:46 <small>(album version)</small>\n| label      = [[RCA Records]] \n| writer     = [[David Bowie]]\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n* [[David Bowie]]\n* [[Tony Visconti]]\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Ashes to Ashes (David Bowie song)|Ashes to Ashes]]\n| prev_year  = 1980\n| next_title = [[Scary Monsters (And Super Creeps) (song)|Scary Monsters (And Super Creeps)]]\n| next_year  = 1981\n| misc       = \n{{External music video|{{YouTube|GA27aQZCQMk|\"Fashion\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Fashion'''\" is a song by English singer-songwriter [[David Bowie]], released on his 1980 album ''[[Scary Monsters (And Super Creeps)]]''. It was released as the second single from the album and was accompanied, like its predecessor \"[[Ashes to Ashes (David Bowie song)|Ashes to Ashes]]\", by a highly regarded music video.<ref name=\"Bowie: An Illustrated Record\">[[Roy Carr]] & [[Charles Shaar Murray]] (1981). ''Bowie: An Illustrated Record'': pp.113-114</ref><ref name=\"The Complete David Bowie\">[[Nicholas Pegg]] (2000). ''The Complete David Bowie'': pp.75-76</ref>\n\nIt was ranked as the 8th best single of 1980 by the ''NME'' magazine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/1980.html|title=Rocklist.net...NME End Of Year Lists 1980...|website=www.rocklistmusic.co.uk|access-date=2018-03-10}}</ref>\n\n==Music and lyrics==\nAccording to co-producer [[Tony Visconti]], \"Fashion\" was the last song completed in the ''Scary Monsters'' sessions, its bassline and some of the melody taking inspiration from Bowie's 1975 hit \"[[Golden Years (song)|Golden Years]]\".<ref name=\"The Complete David Bowie\"/> Guest guitarist [[Robert Fripp]] contributed a series of harsh, mechanical riffs to complement the band's [[funk]]/[[reggae]] arrangement.\n\nThe track was noted for its emotionally vacant choir effect, and the recurring [[onomatopoeia]] \"beep beep\" that Bowie had first used in an unreleased 1970 song called \"Rupert the Riley\".<ref name=\"Strange Fascination\"/> Another phrase in the lyrics that Bowie borrowed from his past was \"People from Bad Homes\", the title track of a 1973 album he recorded with his prot\u00e9g\u00e9s The Astronettes, which went unreleased until 1995.<ref>David Buckley (1999). Ibid: p.207</ref>\n\nReferences to a \"[[goon squad]]\" coming to town provoked theories that the song actually concerns [[fascism]] (\"the [[British National Front|National Front]] invade the discos\", inferred ''[[NME]]'' critics [[Roy Carr]] and [[Charles Shaar Murray]]).<ref name=\"Bowie: An Illustrated Record\"/> However Bowie played down this interpretation in an interview shortly before the release of ''Scary Monsters'', saying that what he was trying to do was \"move on a little from that [[Ray Davies]] concept of fashion, to suggest more of a gritted teeth determination and an unsuredness about why one's doing it\".<ref>Angus MacKinnon (1980). \"The Future Isn't What It Used to Be\". ''[[NME]] (13 September 1980)'': p.37</ref> Biographer David Buckley believed the song \"poked fun at the banality of the dance-floor and the style fascists\" of the [[New Romantic]] movement.<ref name=\"Strange Fascination\">David Buckley (1999). ''Strange Fascination - David Bowie: The Definitive Story'': pp.372\u2013374</ref>\n\n==Music video==\n[[David Mallet (director)|David Mallet]] shot a music video for the single \"Fashion\" in a famous nightclub owned by his friend Robert Boykin called [[Hurrah (nightclub)|Hurrah]]. The opening shot of the clip features David Bowie on the Hurrah stage which was draped in khaki canvas for this shoot. The faceted mirror walls surrounding the dance floor can be seen in the background of various shots, and all the band scenes are shot in this club setting. Other locations around Manhattan are intercut throughout the clip. Amid a series of facial contortions and other gestures, Bowie made use of a move he had employed in the \"Ashes to Ashes\" video: slowly crouching and bringing his arm down to the ground in a slow vertical arc. ''[[Record Mirror]]'' readers voted \"Fashion\" and \"Ashes to Ashes\" the best music videos of 1980.<ref name=\"The Complete David Bowie\"/>\n\nThe video features [[Carlos Alomar]], [[G.E. Smith]] ([[Hall & Oates]]), [[Khandi Alexander]], [[Obba Babatund\u00e9]], the guitarist Steve Love who plays drums in the video, John Kay, [[May Pang]] (later married to the song's producer Tony Visconti) and [[Alan Hunter (VJ)|Alan Hunter]], who became one of the first MTV VJs and also the first VJ to appear in a music video.\n\n==Release and aftermath==\n\"Fashion\" was the second single from ''Scary Monsters'' and the first issued after the album's September 1980 release. The edited 7\" cut reached No. 5 in the UK, and by hitting No. 70 in America gave Bowie his first chart single there in almost four years. The UK sleeve design was adapted for the cover art on the 1980 compilation ''[[Best of Bowie (1980 version)|Best of Bowie]]''.<ref name=\"Bowie: An Illustrated Record\"/>  It was featured in the movie ''[[Clueless (film)|Clueless]]''. During the ''[[2012 Summer Olympics closing ceremony|Closing Ceremony of the 2012 London Olympics]]'', \"Fashion\" was used during a tribute to the British fashion industry in a parade that featured a number of top models from the UK.\n\n==Live performances==\nBowie performed the song on most of his tours after 1980, including the [[Serious Moonlight Tour]] (1983), [[Glass Spider Tour]] (1987), [[Sound+Vision Tour]] (1990), [[Earthling Tour]] (1997), [[Heathen Tour]] (2002), and [[A Reality Tour]] (2003-2004). The song appears on two of his live concert videos: ''[[Serious Moonlight (1983 film)|Serious Moonlight]]'' (1983) and ''[[Glass Spider]]'' (1988).\n\n==Critical reception==\nThe song was ranked among the top ten \"Tracks of the Year\" for 1980 by ''[[NME]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/bestalbumsandtracksoftheyear/1980-2-1045402 |title=Albums and Tracks of the Year |author= |date=2016 |publisher=[[NME]] |accessdate=30 October 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll tracks written by [[David Bowie]].<ref name=\"single liner notes\">{{Cite AV media notes|title=''\"Fashion\"''|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=1980|publisher=[[RCA Records]]|location=UK|type=Single liner notes|id=BOW 7/PB 9622}}</ref>\n# \"Fashion\" \u2013 3:23\n# \"[[Scream Like a Baby]]\" \u2013 3:35\n\n==Production credits==\n* '''Producers''':\n** [[Tony Visconti]]\n** [[David Bowie]]\n* '''Musicians''':\n** David Bowie \u2013\u00a0lead vocals, keyboards\n** [[Robert Fripp]] \u2013 guitar\n** [[Carlos Alomar]] \u2013 guitar\n** [[George Murray (musician)|George Murray]] \u2013 bass guitar\n** [[Dennis Davis]] \u2013 drums\n** [[Andy Clark (musician)|Andy Clark]] \u2013 synthesiser\n\n==Other releases==\n* The song appeared on the following compilations:\n** ''[[Changestwobowie]]'' (1981) \u2013 single edit\n** ''[[Golden Years (album)|Golden Years]]'' (1983) \u2013 album version\n** ''[[Fame and Fashion]]'' (1984) \u2013 album version\n** ''[[Changesbowie|ChangesBowie]]'' (1990) \u2013 album version\n** ''[[The Singles Collection (David Bowie album)|The Singles Collection]]'' (1993) \u2013 album version\n** ''[[Best of Bowie]]'' (2002) \u2013 single edit\n** ''[[The Best of David Bowie 1980/1987]]'' (2007) \u2013 single edit\n** ''[[Nothing Has Changed]]'' (3-CD & 2-CD versions) (2014) \u2013 incorrectly edited \"single version\"\n** ''[[Bowie Legacy]]'' (2-CD version) (2016) \u2013 single edit\n* The single edit of the song was also included on ''Re:Call 3'', part of the ''[[A New Career in a New Town (1977\u20131982)]]'' compilation (2017).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.davidbowie.com/news/new-career-new-town-1977-1982-57146 |title=A NEW CAREER IN A NEW TOWN (1977 \u2013 1982) - David Bowie Latest News |publisher=DavidBowie.com |date=2016-07-22 |access-date=2017-09-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729155132/http://www.allaccess.com/hot-modern-ac/future-releases |archive-date=29 July 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Charts==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1980\u20131981)\n!Peak<br/>position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])\n|align=\"center\"|27\n|-\n|[[Irish Singles Chart]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishcharts.ie/search/placement |title=Fashion in Irish Chart |publisher=IRMA |access-date=28 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5hFf8iFDu?url=http://www.irishcharts.ie/search/placement |archive-date=3 June 2009 |df=dmy }} 4th result of the 1st page when searching \"Fashion\"</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|11\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|22|artist=David Bowie|song=Fashion}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Norway|9|artist=David Bowie|song=Fashion}}\n|-\n|South African Chart<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.rock.co.za/files/springbok_top_20_(B).html |title= Fashion in South African Chart |first= John|last= Samson |accessdate= 28 June 2013}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|8\n|-\n{{singlechart|Sweden|7|artist=David Bowie|song=Fashion}}\n|-\n|UK ([[Official Charts Company]])<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/1980-11-22/ |title= 1980 Top 40 Official UK Singles Archive - 22nd November 1980 |publisher= Official Charts Company |accessdate= 28 June 2013}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|5\n|-\n|U.S. [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref name=\"awards\">{{cite web |url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/scary-monsters-mw0000251983/awards |title= Scary Monsters awards on Allmusic |publisher= Allmusic |accessdate= 28 June 2013}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|70\n|-\n{{singlechart|West Germany|34|artist=David Bowie|song=Fashion|songid=7146|accessdate=18 February 2019}}\n|}\n\n==Cover versions==\n* [[Frank Black]] - Live recording with Bowie in January 1997 on Bowie's 50th birthday party\n* [[The Dandy Warhols]] - Sampled the song in \"Scientist\" on the album ''[[Welcome to the Monkey House (album)|Welcome to the Monkey House]]''\n* Die Lady Di - ''Ashes to Ashes: A Tribute to David Bowie'' (1998)\n* [[Glamma Kid]] - Single release as \"Fashion '98\" (1998)\n* High Blue Star - ''.2 Contamination: A Tribute to David Bowie'' (2006)\n* Botox - ''BowieMania: Mania, une collection obsessionelle de Beatrice Ardisson'' (2007)\n* [[Joey Negro|The Sunburst Band]] - ''Moving with the Shakers'' (2008)\n* [[Afghan Raiders]] - ''[[We Were So Turned On: A Tribute to David Bowie]]'' (2010)\n* [[Grum]] - Covered on the first album ''Heartbeats'' (2010)\n* ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'' - As a promotional music video for ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' \"Fashion's Night Out\"\n* ''[[Bratz: Forever Diamondz Soundtrack]]'' - Changing the name to \"Ooooh Fashion\" and doing various other edits in the lyrics to accommodate the franchise\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== References ==\n{{cite book|last1=Pegg|first1=Nicholas|title=The Complete David Bowie|date=2000|publisher=Reynolds & Hearn Ltd|isbn=1-903111-14-5}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|david-bowie|fashion}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n* {{Youtube|GA27aQZCQMk|Fashion official video}}\n\n{{David Bowie singles}}\n\n[[Category:David Bowie songs]]\n[[Category:1980 singles]]\n[[Category:Funk rock songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by David Bowie]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by David Bowie]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Tony Visconti]]\n[[Category:RCA Records singles]]\n[[Category:1980 songs]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by David Mallet (director)]]\n[[Category:Songs about clothing and fashion]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Fashion\n| cover      = Bowie_Fashion.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[David Bowie]]\n| album      = [[Scary Monsters (And Super Creeps)]]\n| B-side     = [[Scream Like a Baby]]\n| released   = 24 October 1980\n| format     = [[Single (music)|7\" single]]\n| recorded   = February 1980\u2014April 1980\n| studio     = [[Avatar Studios|Power Station]], New York; Good Earth, London\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Funk rock]]\n* [[New wave music|new wave]]\n* [[post-punk]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/david-bowies-essential-albums-251055/|title=Rob Sheffield on David Bowie's Essential Albums|last=Sheffield|first=Rob|date=18 August 2016|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=4 August 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n| length     = 3:23 <small>(7\" single edit)</small><br/>4:46 <small>(album version)</small>\n| label      = [[RCA Records|RCA]] \n| writer     = [[David Bowie]]\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n* [[David Bowie]]\n* [[Tony Visconti]]\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Ashes to Ashes (David Bowie song)|Ashes to Ashes]]\n| prev_year  = 1980\n| next_title = [[Scary Monsters (And Super Creeps) (song)|Scary Monsters (And Super Creeps)]]\n| next_year  = 1981\n| misc       = \n{{External music video|{{YouTube|GA27aQZCQMk|\"Fashion\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Fashion'''\" is a song by English singer-songwriter [[David Bowie]], released on his 1980 album ''[[Scary Monsters (And Super Creeps)]]''. It was released as the second single from the album and was accompanied, like its predecessor \"[[Ashes to Ashes (David Bowie song)|Ashes to Ashes]]\", by a highly regarded music video.<ref name=\"Bowie: An Illustrated Record\">[[Roy Carr]] & [[Charles Shaar Murray]] (1981). ''Bowie: An Illustrated Record'': pp.113-114</ref><ref name=\"The Complete David Bowie\">[[Nicholas Pegg]] (2000). ''The Complete David Bowie'': pp.75-76</ref>\n\nIt was ranked as the 8th best single of 1980 by the ''NME'' magazine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/1980.html|title=Rocklist.net...NME End Of Year Lists 1980...|website=www.rocklistmusic.co.uk|access-date=2018-03-10}}</ref>\n\n==Music and lyrics==\nAccording to co-producer [[Tony Visconti]], \"Fashion\" was the last song completed in the ''Scary Monsters'' sessions, its bassline and some of the melody taking inspiration from Bowie's 1975 hit \"[[Golden Years (song)|Golden Years]]\".<ref name=\"The Complete David Bowie\"/> Guest guitarist [[Robert Fripp]] contributed a series of harsh, mechanical riffs to complement the band's [[funk]]/[[reggae]] arrangement.\n\nThe track was noted for its emotionally vacant choir effect, and the recurring [[onomatopoeia]] \"beep beep\" that Bowie had first used in an unreleased 1970 song called \"Rupert the Riley\".<ref name=\"Strange Fascination\"/> Another phrase in the lyrics that Bowie borrowed from his past was \"People from Bad Homes\", the title track of a 1973 album he recorded with his prot\u00e9g\u00e9s The Astronettes, which went unreleased until 1995.<ref>David Buckley (1999). Ibid: p.207</ref>\n\nReferences to a \"[[goon squad]]\" coming to town provoked theories that the song actually concerns [[fascism]] (\"the [[British National Front|National Front]] invade the discos\", inferred ''[[NME]]'' critics [[Roy Carr]] and [[Charles Shaar Murray]]).<ref name=\"Bowie: An Illustrated Record\"/> However Bowie played down this interpretation in an interview shortly before the release of ''Scary Monsters'', saying that what he was trying to do was \"move on a little from that [[Ray Davies]] concept of fashion, to suggest more of a gritted teeth determination and an unsuredness about why one's doing it\".<ref>Angus MacKinnon (1980). \"The Future Isn't What It Used to Be\". ''[[NME]] (13 September 1980)'': p.37</ref> Biographer David Buckley believed the song \"poked fun at the banality of the dance-floor and the style fascists\" of the [[New Romantic]] movement.<ref name=\"Strange Fascination\">David Buckley (1999). ''Strange Fascination - David Bowie: The Definitive Story'': pp.372\u2013374</ref>\n\n==Music video==\n[[David Mallet (director)|David Mallet]] shot a music video for the single \"Fashion\" in a famous nightclub owned by his friend Robert Boykin called [[Hurrah (nightclub)|Hurrah]]. The opening shot of the clip features David Bowie on the Hurrah stage which was draped in khaki canvas for this shoot. The faceted mirror walls surrounding the dance floor can be seen in the background of various shots, and all the band scenes are shot in this club setting. Other locations around Manhattan are intercut throughout the clip. Amid a series of facial contortions and other gestures, Bowie made use of a move he had employed in the \"Ashes to Ashes\" video: slowly crouching and bringing his arm down to the ground in a slow vertical arc. ''[[Record Mirror]]'' readers voted \"Fashion\" and \"Ashes to Ashes\" the best music videos of 1980.<ref name=\"The Complete David Bowie\"/>\n\nThe video features [[Carlos Alomar]], [[G.E. Smith]] ([[Hall & Oates]]), [[Khandi Alexander]], [[Obba Babatund\u00e9]], the guitarist Steve Love who plays drums in the video, John Kay, [[May Pang]] (later married to the song's producer Tony Visconti) and [[Alan Hunter (VJ)|Alan Hunter]], who became one of the first MTV VJs and also the first VJ to appear in a music video.\n\n==Release and aftermath==\n\"Fashion\" was the second single from ''Scary Monsters'' and the first issued after the album's September 1980 release. The edited 7\" cut reached No. 5 in the UK, and by hitting No. 70 in America gave Bowie his first chart single there in almost four years. The UK sleeve design was adapted for the cover art on the 1980 compilation ''[[Best of Bowie (1980 version)|Best of Bowie]]''.<ref name=\"Bowie: An Illustrated Record\"/>  It was featured in the movie ''[[Clueless (film)|Clueless]]''. During the ''[[2012 Summer Olympics closing ceremony|Closing Ceremony of the 2012 London Olympics]]'', \"Fashion\" was used during a tribute to the British fashion industry in a parade that featured a number of top models from the UK.\n\n==Live performances==\nBowie performed the song on most of his tours after 1980, including the [[Serious Moonlight Tour]] (1983), [[Glass Spider Tour]] (1987), [[Sound+Vision Tour]] (1990), [[Earthling Tour]] (1997), [[Heathen Tour]] (2002), and [[A Reality Tour]] (2003-2004). The song appears on two of his live concert videos: ''[[Serious Moonlight (1983 film)|Serious Moonlight]]'' (1983) and ''[[Glass Spider]]'' (1988).\n\n==Critical reception==\nThe song was ranked among the top ten \"Tracks of the Year\" for 1980 by ''[[NME]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/bestalbumsandtracksoftheyear/1980-2-1045402 |title=Albums and Tracks of the Year |author= |date=2016 |publisher=[[NME]] |accessdate=30 October 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll tracks written by [[David Bowie]].<ref name=\"single liner notes\">{{Cite AV media notes|title=''\"Fashion\"''|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=1980|publisher=[[RCA Records]]|location=UK|type=Single liner notes|id=BOW 7/PB 9622}}</ref>\n# \"Fashion\" \u2013 3:23\n# \"[[Scream Like a Baby]]\" \u2013 3:35\n\n==Production credits==\n* '''Producers''':\n** [[Tony Visconti]]\n** [[David Bowie]]\n* '''Musicians''':\n** David Bowie \u2013\u00a0lead vocals, keyboards\n** [[Robert Fripp]] \u2013 guitar\n** [[Carlos Alomar]] \u2013 guitar\n** [[George Murray (musician)|George Murray]] \u2013 bass guitar\n** [[Dennis Davis]] \u2013 drums\n** [[Andy Clark (musician)|Andy Clark]] \u2013 synthesiser\n\n==Other releases==\n* The song appeared on the following compilations:\n** ''[[Changestwobowie]]'' (1981) \u2013 single edit\n** ''[[Golden Years (album)|Golden Years]]'' (1983) \u2013 album version\n** ''[[Fame and Fashion]]'' (1984) \u2013 album version\n** ''[[Changesbowie|ChangesBowie]]'' (1990) \u2013 album version\n** ''[[The Singles Collection (David Bowie album)|The Singles Collection]]'' (1993) \u2013 album version\n** ''[[Best of Bowie]]'' (2002) \u2013 single edit\n** ''[[The Best of David Bowie 1980/1987]]'' (2007) \u2013 single edit\n** ''[[Nothing Has Changed]]'' (3-CD & 2-CD versions) (2014) \u2013 incorrectly edited \"single version\"\n** ''[[Bowie Legacy]]'' (2-CD version) (2016) \u2013 single edit\n* The single edit of the song was also included on ''Re:Call 3'', part of the ''[[A New Career in a New Town (1977\u20131982)]]'' compilation (2017).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.davidbowie.com/news/new-career-new-town-1977-1982-57146 |title=A NEW CAREER IN A NEW TOWN (1977 \u2013 1982) - David Bowie Latest News |publisher=DavidBowie.com |date=2016-07-22 |access-date=2017-09-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729155132/http://www.allaccess.com/hot-modern-ac/future-releases |archive-date=29 July 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Charts==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1980\u20131981)\n!Peak<br/>position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])\n|align=\"center\"|27\n|-\n|[[Irish Singles Chart]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishcharts.ie/search/placement |title=Fashion in Irish Chart |publisher=IRMA |access-date=28 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5hFf8iFDu?url=http://www.irishcharts.ie/search/placement |archive-date=3 June 2009 |df=dmy }} 4th result of the 1st page when searching \"Fashion\"</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|11\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|22|artist=David Bowie|song=Fashion}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Norway|9|artist=David Bowie|song=Fashion}}\n|-\n|South African Chart<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.rock.co.za/files/springbok_top_20_(B).html |title= Fashion in South African Chart |first= John|last= Samson |accessdate= 28 June 2013}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|8\n|-\n{{singlechart|Sweden|7|artist=David Bowie|song=Fashion}}\n|-\n|UK ([[Official Charts Company]])<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/1980-11-22/ |title= 1980 Top 40 Official UK Singles Archive - 22nd November 1980 |publisher= Official Charts Company |accessdate= 28 June 2013}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|5\n|-\n|U.S. [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref name=\"awards\">{{cite web |url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/scary-monsters-mw0000251983/awards |title= Scary Monsters awards on Allmusic |publisher= Allmusic |accessdate= 28 June 2013}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|70\n|-\n{{singlechart|West Germany|34|artist=David Bowie|song=Fashion|songid=7146|accessdate=18 February 2019}}\n|}\n\n==Cover versions==\n* [[Frank Black]] - Live recording with Bowie in January 1997 on Bowie's 50th birthday party\n* [[The Dandy Warhols]] - Sampled the song in \"Scientist\" on the album ''[[Welcome to the Monkey House (album)|Welcome to the Monkey House]]''\n* Die Lady Di - ''Ashes to Ashes: A Tribute to David Bowie'' (1998)\n* [[Glamma Kid]] - Single release as \"Fashion '98\" (1998)\n* High Blue Star - ''.2 Contamination: A Tribute to David Bowie'' (2006)\n* Botox - ''BowieMania: Mania, une collection obsessionelle de Beatrice Ardisson'' (2007)\n* [[Joey Negro|The Sunburst Band]] - ''Moving with the Shakers'' (2008)\n* [[Afghan Raiders]] - ''[[We Were So Turned On: A Tribute to David Bowie]]'' (2010)\n* [[Grum]] - Covered on the first album ''Heartbeats'' (2010)\n* ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'' - As a promotional music video for ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' \"Fashion's Night Out\"\n* ''[[Bratz: Forever Diamondz Soundtrack]]'' - Changing the name to \"Ooooh Fashion\" and doing various other edits in the lyrics to accommodate the franchise\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== References ==\n{{cite book|last1=Pegg|first1=Nicholas|title=The Complete David Bowie|date=2000|publisher=Reynolds & Hearn Ltd|isbn=1-903111-14-5}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|david-bowie|fashion}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n* {{Youtube|GA27aQZCQMk|Fashion official video}}\n\n{{David Bowie singles}}\n\n[[Category:David Bowie songs]]\n[[Category:1980 singles]]\n[[Category:Funk rock songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by David Bowie]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by David Bowie]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Tony Visconti]]\n[[Category:RCA Records singles]]\n[[Category:1980 songs]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by David Mallet (director)]]\n[[Category:Songs about clothing and fashion]]\n", "name_user": "75.145.78.121", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fashion_(David_Bowie_song)"}
{"title_page": "William Locker", "text_new": "{{for|the Royal Navy officer|William Locker (Royal Navy officer)}}\n{{short description|English footballer and cricketer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = William Locker\n| image          = \n| fullname       = William Locker<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/>\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1866|2|16|df=y}}<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/>\n| birth_place    = [[Long Eaton]], England<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/>\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1952|8|15|1866|2|16|df=y}}<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/>\n| death_place    = [[California, Derby]], England<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/>\n| position       = [[Forward (association football)|Inside left]]\n| years1         = 1885\u20131888 | clubs1 = [[Long Eaton Rangers F.C.|Long Eaton Rangers]] | caps1 =    | goals1 =   \n| years2         = 1888\u20131889 | clubs2 = [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]]             | caps2 = 0  | goals2 = 0\n| years3         = 1889      | clubs3 = [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke]]                      | caps3 = 1  | goals3 = 0\n| years4         = 1889      | clubs4 = Notts Olympic                                  | caps4 =    | goals4 = \n| years5         = 1889\u20131890 | clubs5 = [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]]             | caps5 = 0  | goals5 = 0\n| years6         = 1890\u20131892 | clubs6 = [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]]             | caps6 = 21 | goals6 = 12\n| years7         = 1891      | clubs7 = [[Loughborough F.C.|Loughborough]]             | caps7 =    | goals7 =  \n| years8         = 1892      | clubs8 = [[Long Eaton Rangers F.C.|Long Eaton Rangers]] | caps8 =    | goals8 =  \n}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| name =   \n| batting           = Right-handed batsman  \n| bowling           =  \n| role = \n| family =  \n| international = \n| testdebutdate     =  \n| testdebutyear     =   \n| testdebutagainst = \n| testcap = \n| lasttestdate      =   \n| lasttestyear =  \n| lasttestagainst = \n| club1 = [[Derbyshire County Cricket Club|Derbyshire]] \n| year1 = [[Derbyshire County Cricket Club in 1894|1894]]\u2013[[Derbyshire County Cricket Club in 1903|1903]]\n| club2 = \n| year2 = \n| club3 = \n| year3 = \n| type1 = [[First-class cricket|First-class]]\n| debutdate1 = 10 May\n| debutyear1 = 1894\n| debutfor1 = [[Derbyshire County Cricket Club|Derbyshire]] \n| debutagainst1 = [[Surrey County Cricket Club|Surrey]]\n| lastdate1 = 21 May\n| lastyear1 = 1903\n| lastfor1 = [[Derbyshire County Cricket Club|Derbyshire]] \n| lastagainst1 = [[Marylebone Cricket Club|MCC]] \n| columns           = 1\n| column1           = [[First-class cricket|First-class]]\n| matches1          = 16\n| runs1             = 511\n| bat avg1          = 17.03\n| 100s/50s1         =  0/2 \n| top score1        = 76\n| deliveries1       = \n| wickets1          = \n| bowl avg1         = \n| fivefor1          = \n| tenfor1           = \n| best bowling1     = \n| catches/stumpings1= 4/-\n| date = February\n| year = 2012\n| source = https://cricketarchive.com/Players/31/31040/31040.html \n}}\n'''William Locker''' (16 February 1866 \u2013 15 August 1952)  was an English [[association football|footballer]] and [[cricket]]er. He played first-class cricket for [[Derbyshire County Cricket Club|Derbyshire]] between 1894 and 1903 and football for [[Stoke F.C.|Stoke]], [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] and [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]].<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\">{{cite book|last=Matthews|first=Tony|title=The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City|year=1994|publisher=Lion Press|isbn=0952415100}}</ref> He was one of nineteen sportsmen to achieve the Derbyshire Double of playing cricket for Derbyshire and football for Derby County.\n\nLocker was born in [[Long Eaton]], Derbyshire, the son of William Locker and his wife Mary. His father was a lace maker and at the age of 15 Locker was a lace threader.<ref>British Census 1881</ref>\n\n==Football career==\nLocker played association football for [[Stoke F.C.|Stoke]], [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] and [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]].<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/> His only appearance for Stoke came in a 2\u20131 defeat at home to [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] in November 1889.<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/> Whilst with Notts County he achieved 12 goals in the 1890/91 season<ref>[http://www.iffhs.de/?d85f94e8378cf047b0f02e9d857285fdcdc3bfcdc0aec70aeedb4a388610 IFFHS 1890//91 Season]</ref> and played in the [[1891 FA Cup Final]] on the losing side.<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/>\n\n==Cricket career==\nLocker made his first appearances for Derbyshire in the [[Derbyshire County Cricket Club in 1894|1894 season]]. He next played for them in one match in the [[Derbyshire County Cricket Club in 1899|1899 season]] which was his County Championship debut \u2013 an innings defeat by [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club|Worcestershire]]. He played fully for Derbyshire in the [[Derbyshire County Cricket Club in 1901|1901 season]]. He played one match in the [[Derbyshire County Cricket Club in 1902|1902 season]] and one in the [[Derbyshire County Cricket Club in 1903|1903 season]]. He was a right-handed batsman who played 30 innings in 16 matches with a top score of 76 and an average of 17.03. During his time with Derbyshire, he was an upper-middle order batsman.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Players/31/31040/31040.html William Locker at Cricket Archive]</ref>\n\nLocker died in [[California, Derby]] aged 86.\n\n==Career statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|FA Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|[[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke]]\n|[[1889\u201390 Stoke F.C. season|1889\u201390]]<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/>\n|[[English Football League|The Football League]]\n|1||0||0||0||1||0\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]]\n|[[1890\u201391 in English football|1890\u201391]]<ref name=\"ENFA\">{{ENFA}}</ref>\n|The Football League\n|21||12||6||2||27||14\n|-\n|[[1891\u201392 in English football|1891\u201392]]<ref name=\"ENFA\"/>\n|The Football League\n|0||0||1||0||1||0\n|-\n!colspan=3|Career Total\n!22!!12!!7!!2!!29!!14\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n;[[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]]\n*[[FA Cup]] finalists: [[1891 FA Cup Final|1891]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of English cricket and football players]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Locker, William}}\n[[Category:1866 births]]\n[[Category:1952 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Long Eaton]]\n[[Category:English cricketers]]\n[[Category:Derbyshire cricketers]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football inside forwards]]\n[[Category:Long Eaton Rangers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Stoke City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Notts County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Derby County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English footballer and cricketer}}\n{{for|the Royal Navy officer|William Locker (Royal Navy officer)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = William Locker\n| image          = \n| fullname       = William Locker<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/>\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1866|2|16|df=y}}<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/>\n| birth_place    = [[Long Eaton]], England<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/>\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1952|8|15|1866|2|16|df=y}}<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/>\n| death_place    = [[California, Derby]], England<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/>\n| position       = [[Forward (association football)|Inside left]]\n| years1         = 1885\u20131888 | clubs1 = [[Long Eaton Rangers F.C.|Long Eaton Rangers]] | caps1 =    | goals1 =   \n| years2         = 1888\u20131889 | clubs2 = [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]]             | caps2 = 0  | goals2 = 0\n| years3         = 1889      | clubs3 = [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke]]                      | caps3 = 1  | goals3 = 0\n| years4         = 1889      | clubs4 = Notts Olympic                                  | caps4 =    | goals4 = \n| years5         = 1889\u20131890 | clubs5 = [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]]             | caps5 = 0  | goals5 = 0\n| years6         = 1890\u20131892 | clubs6 = [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]]             | caps6 = 21 | goals6 = 12\n| years7         = 1891      | clubs7 = [[Loughborough F.C.|Loughborough]]             | caps7 =    | goals7 =  \n| years8         = 1892      | clubs8 = [[Long Eaton Rangers F.C.|Long Eaton Rangers]] | caps8 =    | goals8 =  \n}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| name =   \n| batting           = Right-handed batsman  \n| bowling           =  \n| role = \n| family =  \n| international = \n| testdebutdate     =  \n| testdebutyear     =   \n| testdebutagainst = \n| testcap = \n| lasttestdate      =   \n| lasttestyear =  \n| lasttestagainst = \n| club1 = [[Derbyshire County Cricket Club|Derbyshire]] \n| year1 = [[Derbyshire County Cricket Club in 1894|1894]]\u2013[[Derbyshire County Cricket Club in 1903|1903]]\n| club2 = \n| year2 = \n| club3 = \n| year3 = \n| type1 = [[First-class cricket|First-class]]\n| debutdate1 = 10 May\n| debutyear1 = 1894\n| debutfor1 = [[Derbyshire County Cricket Club|Derbyshire]] \n| debutagainst1 = [[Surrey County Cricket Club|Surrey]]\n| lastdate1 = 21 May\n| lastyear1 = 1903\n| lastfor1 = [[Derbyshire County Cricket Club|Derbyshire]] \n| lastagainst1 = [[Marylebone Cricket Club|MCC]] \n| columns           = 1\n| column1           = [[First-class cricket|First-class]]\n| matches1          = 16\n| runs1             = 511\n| bat avg1          = 17.03\n| 100s/50s1         =  0/2 \n| top score1        = 76\n| deliveries1       = \n| wickets1          = \n| bowl avg1         = \n| fivefor1          = \n| tenfor1           = \n| best bowling1     = \n| catches/stumpings1= 4/-\n| date = February\n| year = 2012\n| source = https://cricketarchive.com/Players/31/31040/31040.html \n}}\n'''William Locker''' (16 February 1866 \u2013 15 August 1952)  was an English [[association football|footballer]] and [[cricket]]er. He played first-class cricket for [[Derbyshire County Cricket Club|Derbyshire]] between 1894 and 1903 and football for [[Stoke F.C.|Stoke]], [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] and [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]].<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\">{{cite book|last=Matthews|first=Tony|title=The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City|year=1994|publisher=Lion Press|isbn=0952415100}}</ref> He was one of nineteen sportsmen to achieve the Derbyshire Double of playing cricket for Derbyshire and football for Derby County.\n\nLocker was born in [[Long Eaton]], Derbyshire, the son of William Locker and his wife Mary. His father was a lace maker and at the age of 15 Locker was a lace threader.<ref>British Census 1881</ref>\n\n==Football career==\nLocker played association football for [[Stoke F.C.|Stoke]], [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] and [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]].<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/> His only appearance for Stoke came in a 2\u20131 defeat at home to [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] in November 1889.<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/> Whilst with Notts County he achieved 12 goals in the 1890/91 season<ref>[http://www.iffhs.de/?d85f94e8378cf047b0f02e9d857285fdcdc3bfcdc0aec70aeedb4a388610 IFFHS 1890//91 Season]</ref> and played in the [[1891 FA Cup Final]] on the losing side.<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/>\n\n==Cricket career==\nLocker made his first appearances for Derbyshire in the [[Derbyshire County Cricket Club in 1894|1894 season]]. He next played for them in one match in the [[Derbyshire County Cricket Club in 1899|1899 season]] which was his County Championship debut \u2013 an innings defeat by [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club|Worcestershire]]. He played fully for Derbyshire in the [[Derbyshire County Cricket Club in 1901|1901 season]]. He played one match in the [[Derbyshire County Cricket Club in 1902|1902 season]] and one in the [[Derbyshire County Cricket Club in 1903|1903 season]]. He was a right-handed batsman who played 30 innings in 16 matches with a top score of 76 and an average of 17.03. During his time with Derbyshire, he was an upper-middle order batsman.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Players/31/31040/31040.html William Locker at Cricket Archive]</ref>\n\nLocker died in [[California, Derby]] aged 86.\n\n==Career statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|FA Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|[[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke]]\n|[[1889\u201390 Stoke F.C. season|1889\u201390]]<ref name=\"The Encyclopaedia of Stoke City\"/>\n|[[English Football League|The Football League]]\n|1||0||0||0||1||0\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]]\n|[[1890\u201391 in English football|1890\u201391]]<ref name=\"ENFA\">{{ENFA}}</ref>\n|The Football League\n|21||12||6||2||27||14\n|-\n|[[1891\u201392 in English football|1891\u201392]]<ref name=\"ENFA\"/>\n|The Football League\n|0||0||1||0||1||0\n|-\n!colspan=3|Career Total\n!22!!12!!7!!2!!29!!14\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n;[[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]]\n*[[FA Cup]] finalists: [[1891 FA Cup Final|1891]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of English cricket and football players]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Locker, William}}\n[[Category:1866 births]]\n[[Category:1952 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Long Eaton]]\n[[Category:English cricketers]]\n[[Category:Derbyshire cricketers]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football inside forwards]]\n[[Category:Long Eaton Rangers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Stoke City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Notts County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Derby County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Locker"}
{"title_page": "Stupid Love (Lady Gaga song)", "text_new": "{{short description|2020 single by Lady Gaga}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name         = Stupid Love\n| cover        = Lady Gaga - Stupid Love.png\n| alt          =\n| type         = single \n| artist       = [[Lady Gaga]]\n| album        = [[Chromatica]]\n| released     = {{Start date|2020|02|28|mf=yes}}\n| format       =\n* [[7-inch vinyl]]\n* [[CD single]]\n* [[Cassette tape|cassette]]\n* [[Music download|digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| recorded     = 2019<ref name=\"recorded\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B9GyJPNFqqy/|title=Tchami Instagram Post|date=February 28, 2020|website=Instagram|access-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref>\n| studio       =\n| genre        = <!--Do not add unsourced genres --> <!-- Sourced in the \"Composition\" section -->\n* [[Dance-pop]]\n* [[electropop]]\n| length       = {{Duration|m=3|s=13}}\n| label        = <!--Do not add unsourced labels--> <!-- Sourced in the \"Release history\" section --> [[Interscope Records|Interscope]]\n| writer       =\n* [[Lady Gaga]]\n* [[Max Martin]]\n* Ely \"Rise\" Weisfeld\n* [[BloodPop|Michael Tucker]]\n* [[Tchami|Martin Bresso]]\n| producer     = <!-- No co-producer or vocal producer here, see [[Template: Infobox song#producer]]. -->\n* [[BloodPop]]\n* [[Tchami]]\n| prev_title   = [[I'll Never Love Again]]\n| prev_year    = 2019\n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n| misc         = {{External music video|1={{YouTube|5L6xyaeiV58|\"Stupid Love\"}}}}\n}}\n\"'''Stupid Love'''\" is a song recorded by American singer [[Lady Gaga]]. It was leaked in January 2020, before being officially released along with a music video on February 28, 2020, as the lead single from Gaga's upcoming sixth studio album, ''[[Chromatica]]'' (2020).<ref name=\"Variety\">{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/lady-gaga-stupid-love-new-single-leak-1203474728/|title=Lady Gaga's New Single, 'Stupid Love,' Is Dropping Friday|last=Stedman|first=Alex|date=February 25, 2020|website=Variety|access-date=February 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225171654/https://variety.com/2020/music/news/lady-gaga-stupid-love-new-single-leak-1203474728/|archive-date=February 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Upon release, the song garnered a positive critical response. Commercially, the song reached the top five of the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and the [[UK Singles Chart]], and achieved a top 10 placement on music charts in over 15 territories.\n\n==Composition==\n\n\"Stupid Love\" has been described as a return to the [[dance-pop]]<ref name=\"Vanity Fair\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2020/02/lady-gaga-stupid-love|title=Lady Gaga's \"Stupid Love\" Charts Another Thrilling, Electric Course|last=Adler|first=Dan|date=February 28, 2020|website=[[Vanity Fair (magazines)|Vanity Fair]]|access-date=February 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"uproxx\">{{Cite web|url=https://uproxx.com/pop/lady-gaga-stupid-love-comeback-single/|title=Lady Gaga's Epic Comeback Single 'Stupid Love' Is Alien Dance Pop Of The Highest Order|last=White|first=Caitlin|website=[[Uproxx]]|date=February 28, 2020|access-date=February 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229081314/https://uproxx.com/pop/lady-gaga-stupid-love-comeback-single/|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Stuff\">{{Cite web|url=https://i.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/music/119912985/lady-gaga-returns-to-modern-pop-with-new-single-stupid-love-i-want-people-to-dance|title=Lady Gaga returns to modern pop with new single Stupid Love: 'I want people to dance'|last=Wood|first=Mikael|date=February 29, 2020|access-date=February 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229073744/https://i.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/music/119912985/lady-gaga-returns-to-modern-pop-with-new-single-stupid-love-i-want-people-to-dance|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[electropop]]<ref name=\"NME\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/lady-gaga-stupid-love-track-review-2020-chromatica-2615757|title=Lady Gaga heads back to the dancefloor with vibrant electro-pop banger 'Stupid Love'|last=Daly|first=Rhian|website=[[NME]]|date=February 29, 2020|access-date=February 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228130642/https://www.nme.com/reviews/lady-gaga-stupid-love-track-review-2020-chromatica-2615757|archive-date=February 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"uproxx\"/><ref name=\"Vulture\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/02/lady-gaga-stupid-love-song-review.html|title=Lady Gaga's Message Remains Clear on 'Stupid Love': Just Dance|last=Jenkins|first=Craig|date=February 28, 2020|website=Vulture|access-date=February 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228232300/https://www.vulture.com/2020/02/lady-gaga-stupid-love-song-review.html|archive-date=February 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Nylon\">{{Cite web|url=https://nylon.com/lady-gaga-stupid-love-leak|title=A New Lady Gaga Song Has Leaked And Fans Are Stupid (In) Love|date=January 21, 2020|website=[[Nylon (magazine)|Nylon]]|access-date=January 22, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225182054/https://nylon.com/lady-gaga-stupid-love-leak|archive-date=February 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> sound of [[Lady Gaga]]'s earlier career, with influences of [[Dance music|dance]],<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\"/> [[Disco music|disco]],<ref name=Variety/><ref name=\"Consequence of Sound\"/> and [[Electronic music|electronic]].<ref name=\"Consequence of Sound\"/> Dan Adler of ''[[Vanity Fair (magazines)|Vanity Fair]]'' noted \"Lady Gaga's new single 'Stupid Love' arrives in declarations: 'All I ever wanted was love'; 'I want your stupid love.' She issues them over glittering dance pop, and they're less plaintive than euphoric\u2014the act of expression is the triumph.\"<ref name=\"Vanity Fair\"/> The song is composed in the key of [[B-flat major|B\u266d major]] and is played at a [[tempo]] of 118 beats per minute. Gaga's vocals span from A\u266d<sub>3</sub> to F<sub>5</sub> in the song.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0208308|title=Stupid Love|last=Germanotta|first=Stefani|last2=Martin|first2=Max|date=2020-02-28|website=Musicnotes.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-02|last3=Weisfeld|first3=Ely|last4=Bresso|first4=Martin|last5=Tucker|first5=Michael}}</ref>\n\n==Release and promotion==\nClips of the song first leaked online in January 2020, shortly followed by the entire track leaking.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/01/20/lady-gaga-stupid-love-lg6-twitter-halloween-new-album-twitter/|title=Lady Gaga actually teased new single Stupid Love last Halloween and nobody even realised|last=|first=|date=January 20, 2020|website=[[PinkNews]]|access-date=January 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200120234052/https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/01/20/lady-gaga-stupid-love-lg6-twitter-halloween-new-album-twitter/|archive-date=January 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://instinctmagazine.com/has-lady-gagas-new-song-stupid-love-leaked-online/|title=Has Lady Gaga's New Song \"Stupid Love\" Leaked Online?|last=|first=|date=January 21, 2020|website=[[Instinct (magazine)|Instinct]]|access-date=January 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223053419/https://instinctmagazine.com/has-lady-gagas-new-song-stupid-love-leaked-online/|archive-date=February 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The song went viral on Twitter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/01/lady-gaga-responds-to-leaked-track-stupid-love.html|title=Lady Gaga Is Here to Warn You About the Dangers of Online Piracy|last=Sinha|first=Charu|date=January 22, 2020|website=Vulture|access-date=January 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200123080951/https://www.vulture.com/2020/01/lady-gaga-responds-to-leaked-track-stupid-love.html|archive-date=January 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Gaga responded to the leak by tweeting \"can y'all stop\" with a stock photo of a young girl wearing a balaclava while listening to music on a cassette player.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8548801/lady-gaga-song-allegedly-leaks-tweet|title=Did Lady Gaga Just Address a Reported Song Leak With This New Tweet?|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=January 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225180314/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8548801/lady-gaga-song-allegedly-leaks-tweet|archive-date=February 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gaytimes.co.uk/culture/131691/lady-gaga-had-the-best-response-after-her-song-stupid-love-leaked-online/|title=Lady Gaga had the best response after her song Stupid Love leaked online|date=January 23, 2020|website=[[Gay Times]]|access-date=January 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200123201527/https://www.gaytimes.co.uk/culture/131691/lady-gaga-had-the-best-response-after-her-song-stupid-love-leaked-online/|archive-date=January 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/01/23/lady-gaga-stupid-love-leak-reaction-twitter-lg6/|title=Lady Gaga freaks out after new song Stupid Love leaked online and broke the internet|last=|first=|date=January 23, 2020|website=PinkNews|access-date=January 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200213090448/https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/01/23/lady-gaga-stupid-love-leak-reaction-twitter-lg6/|archive-date=February 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Gaga did not perform \"Stupid Love\" during her [[AT&T TV]] Super Saturday Night pre-[[Super Bowl LIV]] show in [[Miami]], despite requests from audience members. Instead, Gaga performed her [[Lady Gaga Enigma|Enigma]] set from her [[Las Vegas]] [[Concert residency|residency]] and did not address the leaked track.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.queerty.com/not-ask-lady-gaga-perform-leaked-track-stupid-love-20200203|title=Do not ask Lady Gaga to perform leaked track \"Stupid Love\"|last=Hudson|first=David|date=2020-02-03|website=Queerty|access-date=2020-03-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204122435/https://www.queerty.com/not-ask-lady-gaga-perform-leaked-track-stupid-love-20200203|archive-date=February 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Online chatter of the song began as early as October 30, 2019, when Gaga posted a picture to her Twitter of a [[Halloween]] pumpkin she painted. In the corner of the photo was an [[iPhone]]; when zoomed in it appeared to show \"Stupid Love\" being played on the phone.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nGaga announced the song's release via social media on February 25, 2020.<ref>{{cite tweet |user= ladygaga |number=1232347823787560960 |date=February 25, 2020 |title=\"STUPID LOVE\" THE NEW SINGLE BY LADY GAGA OUT FRIDAY AT MIDNIGHT ET #LG6}}</ref> The announcement was accompanied with a photograph of a billboard in [[Los Angeles]] that had \"an image of the song\u2019s title splashed across an image of bright pink lips.\"<ref name=\"EW2\">{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/music/2020/02/25/lady-gaga-stupid-love-new-song-announcement-lg6-album/|title=Lady Gaga announces new single 'Stupid Love' ahead of LG6 album|last=Nolfi|first=Joey|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=February 25, 2020|access-date=February 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225194202/https://ew.com/music/2020/02/25/lady-gaga-stupid-love-new-song-announcement-lg6-album/|archive-date=February 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"RS2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/lady-gaga-new-album-everything-we-know-958227/|title=Lady Gaga's New Album: Here's Everything We Know About LG6|last1=Hissong|first1=Samantha|last2=Spanos|first2=Brittany|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=February 25, 2020|access-date=February 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226182601/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/lady-gaga-new-album-everything-we-know-958227/|archive-date=February 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The billboard also features stills from the music video embedded to the right of the center text, as well as a silhouette of characters in the video ingrained in the text.<ref name=\"EW2\" /><ref name=\"RS2\" /> The word \"Chromatica\" is written twice on the billboard: one vertically adjacent to the music video stills, and again as the last line of the copyright message in the lower left corner. The prominence of this word led news outlets to speculate the title of Gaga's sixth studio album.<ref name=\"EW2\" /><ref name=\"RS2\" />\n\nJeena Sharma of ''[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]'' magazine described promotional images of Gaga for \"Stupid Love\" as \"pop-meets-punk.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> The images featured Gaga wearing a pink monochromatic look with makeup from her Haus Laboratories beauty line.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.papermag.com/lady-gaga-stupid-love-beauty-2645290223.html|title=Every Haus Labs Product Used for Lady Gaga's 'Stupid Love' Promo|date=2020-02-27|website=PAPER|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228151623/https://www.papermag.com/lady-gaga-stupid-love-beauty-2645290223.html|archive-date=February 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Just before dropping \"Stupid Love\" and its music video, Gaga tweeted \"earth is cancelled.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/lady-gaga-stupid-love-music-video-twitter-stans/|title=Lady Gaga's \"Stupid Love\" Video Has Left the Internet With a Lot to Say|website=W Magazine {{!}} Women's Fashion & Celebrity News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229212526/https://www.wmagazine.com/story/lady-gaga-stupid-love-music-video-twitter-stans/|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The song was prominently featured on an [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] commercial as part of its \"Shot on iPhone 11 Pro\" campaign.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailycommercials.com/apple-lady-gaga/|title=Apple: Lady Gaga|date=2020-02-28|website=DAILY COMMERCIALS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229211731/https://dailycommercials.com/apple-lady-gaga/|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Apple confirmed the music video was filmed entirely using the Filmic Pro app on an [[iPhone 11 Pro]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcmag.com/news/lady-gaga-shot-entire-stupid-love-music-video-on-iphone-11-pro|title=Lady Gaga Shot 'Stupid Love' Music Video on iPhone 11 Pro|website=PCMAG|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229211733/https://www.pcmag.com/news/lady-gaga-shot-entire-stupid-love-music-video-on-iphone-11-pro|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The song was placed at the top of [[Apple Music]]'s Today's Top Hits playlist, [[Spotify]]'s New Music Daily playlist, and Spotify's Today's Hits playlist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://headlineplanet.com/home/2020/02/28/lady-gagas-stupid-love-tops-key-spotify-apple-music-playlists-makes-big-us-itunes-sales-chart-splash-scores-early-radio-support/|title=Lady Gaga's \"Stupid Love\" Tops Key Spotify, Apple Music Playlists, Makes Big US iTunes Sales Chart Splash, Scores Early Radio Support|date=2020-02-28|website=Headline Planet|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228065910/https://headlineplanet.com/home/2020/02/28/lady-gagas-stupid-love-tops-key-spotify-apple-music-playlists-makes-big-us-itunes-sales-chart-splash-scores-early-radio-support/|archive-date=February 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In the hours after its release, both the song \"Stupid Love\" and Lady Gaga herself were the top two trending topics on Twitter worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9325151/lady-gaga-stupid-love-reaction|title=Lady Gaga's 'Stupid Love' Is Getting a Lot of Love From Her Little Monsters|date=2020-02-28|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-02-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229221649/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9325151/lady-gaga-stupid-love-reaction|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Referred to as \"what historians in the year 3020 will dub as the most aggressively 2020 moment ever recorded,\"<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/03/03/lady-gaga-stupid-love-chromatica-coronavirus-italy-regione-liguria/|title=Lady Gaga\u2019s \u2018Stupid Love\u2019 interrupts a crucial press conference about the coronavirus|date=2020-03-03|website=PinkNews - Gay news, reviews and comment from the world's most read lesbian, gay, bisexual, and trans news service|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> a [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19]] press conference in [[Italy]] was interrupted by \"Stupid Love\" playing on a phone. After video footage of the interruption circulated on Twitter, a reporter tweeted to confess responsibility and expressed being glad to cause some smiles in a rather tense meeting.<ref name=\":13\" />\n\n== Critical reception ==\n\"Stupid Love\" received positive reviews, with several critics praising Gaga's return to her dance-pop roots. Following the leak, [[W (magazine)|''W'' magazine]]'s Kyle Munzenrieder wrote, \"It was classic Gaga with a chugging power chorus, and a [[Big room house|big room]] backing track. Her fans began dissecting what it told us about the upcoming album. Gaga herself, however, wasn't having it.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/lady-gaga-stupid-love-miami-performance/|title=Lady Gaga Stubbornly Refuses to Start a New Era|last=|first=|date=|website=[[W (magazine)|W]]|access-date=February 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225182711/https://www.wmagazine.com/story/lady-gaga-stupid-love-miami-performance/|archive-date=February 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Commenting on the leak, ''[[Harper's Bazaar]]'' described \"Stupid Love\" as an \"upbeat cut with big vocals and dance and electronic-inspired production\", seemingly \"poised to be another radio hit from the singer\".<ref name=\"Harper's Bazaar\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.harpersbazaar.com/culture/art-books-music/a30624546/lady-gaga-stupid-love/|title=A Lady Gaga Song Reportedly Leaked Online, and No One Is Okay Right Now|last=Gonzales|first=Erica|date=January 22, 2020|website=[[Harper's Bazaar]]|access-date=January 22, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200122231842/https://www.harpersbazaar.com/culture/art-books-music/a30624546/lady-gaga-stupid-love/|archive-date=January 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Variety'' described the leak as a \"disco-infused anthem whose style harkens back to Gaga's ''[[Born This Way (album)|Born This Way]]'' album\".<ref name=\"Variety\" />\n\nUpon the song's official release, Michael Cuby of ''[[Nylon (magazine)|Nylon]]'' described the song as a \"mix between 'Bad Kids' and '[[The Edge of Glory]]' with a beat that instantly recalls the joyous [[electropop]] of '[[Do What U Want]]',\"<ref name=\"Nylon\" /> and \"the type of song you can easily imagine both blasting out of an expensive sound-system at your local [[gay club]] and out of a car speaker as it speeds down the highway with its top down in the summertime.\"<ref name=\"Nylon\" /> Jamieson Cox for ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' also compared the song to \"Do What U Want,\" saying the \"brawny, shiny disco\"<ref name=\":9\">{{Citation|title=Listen to \"Stupid Love\" by Lady Gaga|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/lady-gaga-stupid-love/|language=en|access-date=2020-03-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302161004/https://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/lady-gaga-stupid-love/|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> of \"Stupid Love\" sounds like a sped-up version of the former. Cox claims \"Stupid Love\" recalls Gaga's late 2000s era \"without achieving the same kind of grandeur,\" yet welcomes Gaga's return and \"the goofy, indomitable spirit that made her so refreshing in the first place.\"<ref name=\":9\" />  Writing for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', Claire Shaffer and Althea Legaspi described the song as a \"dance jam,\"<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{cite web |last1=Shaffer |first1=Claire |last2=Legaspi |first2=Althea |title=Lady Gaga Fights for Compassion in 'Stupid Love' Video |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/lady-gaga-stupid-love-video-959231/ |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=February 28, 2020 |date=February 28, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228053420/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/lady-gaga-stupid-love-video-959231/ |archive-date=February 28, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> while Ben Kaye of ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' as an \"[[Electronic music|electronic]] [[disco]] banger.\"<ref name=\"Consequence of Sound\">{{cite web |last1=Kaye |first1=Ben |title=Lady Gaga Shares New Song \"Stupid Love\": Stream |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/02/lady-gaga-stupid-love-song-video-stream/ |website=[[Consequence of Sound]] |accessdate=February 28, 2020 |date=February 28, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228053847/https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/02/lady-gaga-stupid-love-song-video-stream/ |archive-date=February 28, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSpencer Kornhaber for ''[[The Atlantic]]'' called the single a \"glorious comeback\"<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2020/02/lady-gaga-stupid-love-review-glorious-pop-yearning/607207/|title=Lady Gaga's 'Stupid Love' Is a Glorious Comeback|last=Kornhaber|first=Spencer|date=2020-02-28|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301011249/https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2020/02/lady-gaga-stupid-love-review-glorious-pop-yearning/607207/|archive-date=March 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and a \"return to form not only for the singer, but also for her genre.\"<ref name=\":11\" /> Kornhaber added that even though the [[Max Martin]] production \"feels perfectly calibrated for catchiness, Gaga\u2019s voice is so big and personable that a sense of humanity remains intact\"<ref name=\":11\" /> and concluded that \"Stupid Love\" is \"light, sweet, and orderly.\"<ref name=\":11\" /> Kornhaber also praised [[BloodPop]] and [[Tchami]]'s keyboard work and mixing of the song, mentioning the microseconds before the drop of the final chorus, calling it a \"fake-out that tricks the ear every time, as superfans who\u2019ve been giddily listening to the song since it leaked in January can attest.\"<ref name=\":11\" /> For ''[[Slant Magazine]]'', Alexa Camp was more critical of the track, describing it as a \"catchy but uninventive slice of electro-pop\"<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review-lady-gaga-stupid-love-single-and-video-fail-to-spark-joy/|title=Review: Lady Gaga's \"Stupid Love\" Single and Video Fail to Spark Joy|last=Camp|first=Alexa|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229142609/https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review-lady-gaga-stupid-love-single-and-video-fail-to-spark-joy/|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and compared its [[bassline]] to \"Do What U Want.\"<ref name=\":10\" />\n\n==Chart performance==\nIn the US, \"Stupid Love\" debuted at number five on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], becoming Gaga's sixteenth top 10, twelfth top five hit, and her highest-debuting entry since \"[[The Edge of Glory]]\" debuted at number three in 2011. It also marked her first top 10 debut since \"[[Dope (Lady Gaga song)|Dope]]\" when it entered at number eight in November 2013, and first top ten since \"[[Shallow (Lady Gaga and Bradley Cooper song)|Shallow]]\" peaked number one in March 2019.\u00a0Additionally, with \"Stupid Love\", Gaga became the fifth artist to have ranked in the Hot 100's top 10 in the 2000s, 2010s and 2020s. The song debuted at the summit on [[Digital Songs]], with 53,000 downloads sold and becoming Gaga's seventh leader on the chart. It also debuted at number one on the [[Dance/Electronic Songs|Hot Dance/Electronic Songs]] chart,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9330849/lady-gaga-stupid-love-hot-100-debut|title=Lady Gaga's 'Stupid Love' Launches at No. 5 on Hot 100, Roddy Ricch's 'The Box' Notches Ninth Week at No. 1|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref> becoming her fifth topper and 28th charted title, the most of any solo female.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9333434/stupid-love-tops-hot-dance-electronic-songs|title=Lady Gaga's 'Stupid Love' Launches at No. 1 on Hot Dance/Electronic Songs Chart|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Murray|first=Gordon|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe song also debuted at number five on the [[UK Singles Chart]], becoming Gaga's thirteenth top 10 in the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-weeknds-blinding-lights-claims-fourth-week-at-uk-number-1-lady-gagas-stupid-love-scores-highest-new-entry__28976/|title=The Weeknd keeps singles Number 1, Lady Gaga scores big new entry|website=www.officialcharts.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\n===Background and summary===\n[[File:Trona Pinnacles (68132057).jpeg|thumb|left|[[Trona Pinnacles]], the film location of \"Stupid Love\"<ref name=\":5\" />]]\nThe accompanying music video was directed by [[Daniel Askill]] and choreographed by [[Richard Jackson (choreographer)|Richard Jackson]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/lady-gaga-to-release-new-song-stupid-love-this-week/|title=Lady Gaga Shares Video for New Song \"Stupid Love\"|last1=SHAFFER|first1=CLAIRE|last2=LEGASPI|first2=ALTHEA|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228052102/https://pitchfork.com/news/lady-gaga-to-release-new-song-stupid-love-this-week/|archive-date=February 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.papermag.com/lady-gaga-stupid-love-video-2645328161.html?rebelltitem=1#rebelltitem1?rebelltitem=1|title=Lady Gaga's New Video Is a 'Mad Max' Pride Parade|date=2020-02-28|website=PAPER|language=en|access-date=2020-03-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301002822/https://www.papermag.com/lady-gaga-stupid-love-video-2645328161.html?rebelltitem=1#rebelltitem1?rebelltitem=1|archive-date=March 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It was released on February 28 online and on the United States [[MTV]] channel, with teasers being released one day prior.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/MTV/status/1233112062253027329|title=It is my HONOR and PRIVILEGE (as a Little Monster myself) to give you an MTV first look at @ladygaga's new video for #StupidLove, tonight at midnight ET on MTV! pic.twitter.com/EgtaK5jtMV|date=February 27, 2020|access-date=March 1, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227194501/https://twitter.com/MTV/status/1233112062253027329|archive-date=February 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |user= ladygaga |number=1232900786486558720 |date=February 27, 2020 |title=\"Stupid Love\" the single & music video out Friday 2/28 at midnight ET}}</ref> Filmed on location at [[Trona Pinnacles]], [[California]], the video features Gaga combatting \"warring factions to establish a more compassionate world order\".<ref>{{cite journal |title=Lady Gaga Fights for Compassion in 'Stupid Love' Video |journal=Rolling Stone |date=February 28, 2020 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/lady-gaga-stupid-love-video-959231/ |accessdate=February 28, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228053420/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/lady-gaga-stupid-love-video-959231/ |archive-date=February 28, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2020/02/28/lady-gaga-stupid-love-video-facts-costume-iphone-camera-location/|title=Three crazy facts about Lady Gaga's Stupid Love video - costume design, iPhone camera, filming location!|last=Fogarty|first=Paul|date=2020-02-28|website=HITC|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229120714/https://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2020/02/28/lady-gaga-stupid-love-video-facts-costume-iphone-camera-location/|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The video was entirely filmed using Apple's [[iPhone 11 Pro]] triple camera system.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Stupid Love film with iPhone 11 Pro |journal=Apple Insider |date=28 February 2020 |url=https://appleinsider.com/articles/20/02/27/apples-iphone-11-pro-used-to-film-new-lady-gaga-music-video-stupid-love |accessdate=28 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228123203/https://appleinsider.com/articles/20/02/27/apples-iphone-11-pro-used-to-film-new-lady-gaga-music-video-stupid-love |archive-date=February 28, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe music video opens with the text \"The world rots in conflict. Many tribes battle for dominance. While the Spiritual ones pray and sleep for peace, the Kindness punks fight for Chromatica.\"<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/music/a31156086/lady-gaga-stupid-love-video-lyrics-meaning/|title=Lady Gaga and Her Posse of Pink Power Rangers Will Save the World|last=Holmes|first=Dave|date=2020-02-28|website=Esquire|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref> The camera pans to a desert scene with crystal mountains.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2020/2/28/21157536/lady-gaga-new-music-video-stupid-love|title=Lady Gaga's 'Stupid Love' music video is a neon-swathed, magical-girl B-movie|last=Radulovic|first=Petrana|date=2020-02-28|website=Polygon|language=en|access-date=2020-03-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301081754/https://www.polygon.com/2020/2/28/21157536/lady-gaga-new-music-video-stupid-love|archive-date=March 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Gaga and her squad are running to the scene of a battle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/1126759/lady-gaga-is-ready-for-battle-in-futuristic-stupid-love-music-video-watch-now|title=Lady Gaga Is Ready for Battle in Futuristic Stupid Love Video: Watch|date=February 28, 2020|website=E! Online|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301005919/https://www.eonline.com/news/1126759/lady-gaga-is-ready-for-battle-in-futuristic-stupid-love-music-video-watch-now|archive-date=March 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Gaga is seen in various hot pink outfits dancing it out with groups of dance warriors, each group with a corresponding color and logo.<ref name=\":6\" /> Once the factions begin to fight again, Gaga cannot take it anymore. She levitates two fighters and slams them back to the ground. With that move, the battle is won.<ref name=\":7\" /> Gaga leads the dance warriors into one big celebration to conclude the video.<ref name=\":6\" /> The faction in pink, led by Gaga, restored peace to the desert region.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nIn a ''[[Harper's Bazaar]]'' interview with Gaga's makeup artist Sarah Tanno, Tanno described using pieces that evoke armor to satisfy Gaga's desire to feel strong for the video. Describing Gaga's wishes, Tanno explains, \"she wanted to exude a 'Kindness Punk', someone who fights for kindness and leads with love.\u201d<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.harpersbazaar.com/beauty/makeup/a31137257/lady-gaga-stupid-love-music-video-makeup-sarah-tanno/|title=Lady Gaga's Makeup Artist Spills The Details on Her \"Stupid Love\" Music Video Beauty Look|last=Rosenstein|first=Jenna|date=2020-02-28|website=Harper's BAZAAR|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229095039/https://www.harpersbazaar.com/beauty/makeup/a31137257/lady-gaga-stupid-love-music-video-makeup-sarah-tanno/|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Tanno sought inspiration from a prior era in Gaga's career in creating Gaga's face pieces for the music video. \"In the ''[[Born This Way (album)|Born This Way]]'' era she had these cheek prosthetics\u2014so I thought, what is the new special thing that I can make for her? This armor naturally will come in different shades of metallic pink,\"<ref name=\":2\" /> explained Tanno. Wanting the pieces to move with Gaga as she moved and danced, Tanno crafted the face pieces out of materials resembling bone prosthetics instead of opting for metal.<ref name=\":2\" /> Unlike the face pieces, Gaga's costumes featured pieces crafted of actual metal designed by Laurel DeWitt. \"The mood boards were a crazy mash of futuristic armor, aliens, and even an insect type vibe. Everything had to be pink so I worked with her style team and just did my interpretation on it. Pink metal! I mean c'mon! It was perfect,\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://hollywoodlife.com/2020/02/28/lady-gaga-stupid-love-costume-designer-interview-laurel-dewitt/|title=Lady Gaga's 'Stupid Love' Costume Designer Reveals How Involved Singer Was In Music Video Looks|last=Brody|first=Beth Shilliday,Lanae|date=2020-02-28|website=Hollywood Life|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229134034/https://hollywoodlife.com/2020/02/28/lady-gaga-stupid-love-costume-designer-interview-laurel-dewitt/|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  DeWitt described. The four different outfits crafted for Gaga by DeWitt and Gaga's pink wig were seen as a departure from Gaga's previous style. DeWitt added that Gaga loved the styles, but she found some to be painful to wear, and said \"but you know Gaga, anything for fashion.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Reception===\n[[British Vogue|British ''Vogue'']] described Gaga's look for the music video as a \"Y2K-inspired desert warrior\"<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.co.uk/arts-and-lifestyle/article/lady-gaga-stupid-love-video|title=Lady Gaga Is A Y2K-Inspired Desert Warrior In First Clips Of Her \"Stupid Love\" Music Video|website=British Vogue|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229221237/https://www.vogue.co.uk/arts-and-lifestyle/article/lady-gaga-stupid-love-video|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and called the singer's aesthetics a return to her \"[[Lady Gaga's meat dress|meat-dress]]-era form.\"<ref name=\":8\" /> Dave Holmes for ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'' described Gaga's dancing in the video as \"back to a kind of movement that is less 'dance' and more a series of gestures. The classics are back: 'wrists on forehead' makes a triumphant return, as do 'hand covering eye' and 'forearms in x formation.{{'\"}}<ref name=\":7\" /> Craig Jenkins for ''[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]'' described the video as a \"purposeful visual overkill\"<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/02/lady-gaga-stupid-love-song-review.html|title=Lady Gaga's Message Remains Clear on 'Stupid Love': Just Dance|last=Jenkins|first=Craig|date=2020-02-28|website=Vulture|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228232300/https://www.vulture.com/2020/02/lady-gaga-stupid-love-song-review.html|archive-date=February 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> with tight choreography and compared the video to the music video for \"[[Genesis (Grimes song)|Genesis]]\" by [[Grimes (musician)|Grimes]], the video game ''[[Bayonetta]]'', and ''[[Star Trek]]''.<ref name=\":4\" /> Brandon Wetmore for ''[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]'' magazine described the video as a ''[[Mad Max]]''-evoking \"[[pride parade]]\"<ref name=\":3\" /> pairing \"[[Bad Romance]]\"-era choreography with ''[[Artpop]]''-era [[Camp (style)|camp]] and contrasted the vibrancy and color of the video with the muted and somber tones of the visuals from the previous ''[[A Star Is Born (2018 soundtrack)|A Star Is Born]]'' era.<ref name=\":3\" /> Alexa Camp for ''Slant Magazine'' was critical of the single and its video, calling the video corny and lacking \"the (comparatively) sophisticated mythology or narrative of videos like 2011's 'Born This Way.{{'\"}}<ref name=\":10\" />\n\n== Credits and personnel ==\nCredits adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/132719184|title=Stupid Love / Lady Gaga|website=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228072328/https://listen.tidal.com/album/132719184|archive-date=February 28, 2020|access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{div col}}\n* [[Lady Gaga]] \u2013 vocals, songwriter\n* [[BloodPop]] \u2013 producer, songwriter, bass, drums, guitar, keyboards, percussion\n* [[Tchami]] \u2013 producer, songwriter, mixer, bass, drums, guitar, keyboards, percussion\n* [[Max Martin]] \u2013 co-producer, songwriter, vocal producer\n* Ely Rise \u2013 songwriter\n* Benjamin Rice \u2013 vocal producer, mixer, recording engineer\n* [[Tom Norris (record producer)|Tom Norris]] \u2013 mixer\n* John \"JR\" Robinson \u2013 drums\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Charts ==\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\n=== Weekly charts ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardargentinahot100|49|artist=Lady Gaga|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Australia|7|artist=Lady Gaga|song=Stupid Love|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 7, 2020}}\